<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AdvancedPlacement     12-12 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Advanced Placement,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Number of Minorities Taking Advanced Placement Exams Doubles in
Five Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-School Discipline, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than twice the number of minority high
school students took advancement placement exams in 1988 than five
years ago, led by a surge among Hispanics and Asian-Americans, the
College Board reported.
   The board's annual survey of advanced placement tests, which high
school students take to qualify for credit or placement in
upper-level college courses, also found that California, New York
and Florida had by far the most black and Hispanic test-takers who
scored qualifying grades.
   In all, 288,372 students took 419,101 advanced placement exams in
1988. The program, sponsored by the College Board, offers 27
college-level examinations in 16 subjects.
   Nearly 52,000 minority students nationwide took the exams in
1988, compared with 39,517 in 1987, and 142 percent more than the
21,501 who took it five years ago, the College Board said Sunday.
   Forty-nine thousand of those students scored high enough to
qualify for college credit. The tests are scored on a scale of 1-5,
with colleges usually requiring at least a 3 to qualify for credit.
   Minority students made up nearly 20 percent of all advanced
placement test-takers in 1988, compared with 18.4 percent in 1987
and 14.7 percent in 1984.
   ``By using AP to raise the expectations of minority students and
helping them achieve higher goals ... schools are bringing more
minorities into professional and graduate schools,'' said board
president Donald M. Stewart.
   The number of Asian-American students taking the exams was
27,396, up from 21,101 in 1987 and 140 percent greater than the
11,413 in 1984.
   The number of Hispanics taking the test grew 156 percent over
five years: from 5,200 to 13,322; the number of blacks grew by 135
percent, from 4,448 to 10,448.
   The number of whites taking the tests totaled 210,582, up 27
percent from 165,924 in 1987, and 80 percent higher than the 117,302
in 1984.
   Some 8,247 schools offered the exams in 1988, 470 more than last
year.
   Plano High School, near Dallas, with a student body of 2,600, had
the largest number of advanced placement candidates of any school _
490 _ and the largest number of tests taken _ 887, according to the
report.
   California led the nation with 5,125 black and Hispanic
test-takers last year. New York was second with 2,526, followed by
Florida with 2,439.
   The College Board is a nonprofit organization representing 2,600
colleges and other educational groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
