<DOCNO> AP881212-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0057EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Botha-Mandela     12-12 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Botha-Mandela,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandela Overshadows Botha's Efforts To Ease Pressure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha is
campaigning doggedly to improve South Africa's image overseas, but
he faces constant reminders that success will be limited until he
comes to terms with Nelson Mandela.
   Among those conveying that message in recent days were South
Africa's best-known novelist, black and white corporate executives,
and two leading U.S. senators who were rebuffed curtly when they
asked Botha if they could meet the jailed African National Congress
leader.
   Even the government's recent decision to transfer Mandela to a
prison farm staff house, complete with swimming pool and patio,
seemed to underscore the special stature of the 70-year-old black
nationalist.
   ``They are showing that he is the major kingpin in the
constitutional future of South Africa,'' said Dave Dalling,
parliament member from the anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party.
   Perhaps the most dramatic evidence of the influence wielded over
South Africa by Mandela and his ANC came in court testimony last
week on behalf of 11 black activists about to be sentenced for
treason and terrorism in the same courthouse where Mandela received
a life sentence for sabotage in 1964.
   Most of the 11 treason defendants were affiliated to the United
Democratic Front, a nationwide anti-apartheid coalition which the
trial judge said had collaborated with the ANC.
   The defense lawyers, instead of repudiating the ANC, summoned
several of South Africa's most respected opposition figures to speak
about their support for and understanding of the outlawed guerrilla
movement.
   Nadine Gordimer, the country's foremost novelist, said she
considered Mandela her leader and blamed her fellow whites for South
Africa's political violence.
   Sam Motsuenyane, a black bank chairman, said of Mandela:
``Unquestionably, he is my hero.''
   Similar statements came from a university administrator and the
leader of a black homeland. In a subsequent magazine interview, a
prominent Afrikaner business leader, Anton Rupert, said he wanted to
meet Mandela ``man to man'' to discuss a peaceful political
settlement.
   Botha has declined to spell out his plans for Mandela as he
presses ahead with an unprecedented campaign to ease international
pressure on South Africa.
   In the past few weeks, he has commuted the widely denounced death
sentences of a group of blacks known as the Sharpeville Six, freed
two elderly black political prisoners and endorsed a tentative peace
plan that could end South African rule over Namibia.
   All these steps, as well as Mandela's transfer, have been
welcomed in Western capitals. But always, the pressure to deal
politically with Mandela and the ANC resumes.
   Botha also is under fire for continued repression of dissidents
at home while he tries to impress power brokers abroad.
   Even a seemingly benevolent gesture, the recent release of
detained black newspaper editor Zwelakhe Sisulu, had a harsh edge to
it. Sisulu, like several other freed detainees, was prohibited from
returning to his job, restricted to the area around his home and
barred from anti-government political activity.
   U.S. Senators Sam Nunn of Georgia and David Boren of Oklahoma, at
the close of a one-week fact-finding trip, acknowledged Saturday
that Botha had taken some positive steps but said they came away
with a feeling of pessimism.
   ``If those who are working for real change are foreclosed from
using non-violent political methods, it is our great fear that they
will be forced to turn to methods that will undoubtedly lead to
violence and tragedy,'' the two Democrats said.
   Botha, said Boren, ``deeply disappointed us by wanting to talk
only about the past, not trying to engage and assess and share ideas
about the future.''
   Even if Mandela were released, opposition leaders say the gesture
would mean little unless he and other prominent black militants,
young and old, are allowed to engage freely in politics and to work
for a one-person, one-vote system.
   Botha says he is not willing to even discuss such a system, and
there is no sign that Mandela's release would mean an easing of
restrictions on opposition activity.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Crary is the Associated Press news editor
in Johannesburg and has been reporting from East and Southern Africa
since 1985.
</TEXT>
