<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-RainMan     12-12 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Rain Man,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dustin Hoffman Joins Film Role Model For Preview</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An autistic man who served as a model
for Dustin Hoffman's latest movie character watched the premiere of
``Rain Man'' with the actor three rows behind him.
   Joseph Sullivan, 28, was one of three autistic people Hoffman
studied to prepare for the role of Raymond Babbitt, an idiot savant
who inherits $3 million from his father's estate but has no concept
of money.
   Hoffman, director Barry Levinson and producer Mark Johnson came
to Huntington to help raise funds for the Autism Services Center,
which is run by Sullivan's mother, Ruth.
   About 1,500 people attended Sunday's benefit at the ornate
Keith-Albee Theater. The center said it expected to get $30,000 to
$35,000.
   ``It's not something that's happened to us before, coming to a
town which has a family in it which was the inspiration for our
film,'' Hoffman told the 600 people attending a dinner following the
premiere. ``It's just a very moving experience for myself and my
wife, and Barry and his wife, and Mark and his wife.
   ``We just made a film that's going to play for, you know, a month
or two, or whatever, in cities in America and around the world and
be put out on (video) cassette and put on shelves and seen once.
   ``You people have Joe in your community for the rest of your
lives, and I would take that any day of the week, and I think that's
a really important thing because he is a very special person who
shines through this ... magic he has.''
   Autism is an affliction in which the brain doesn't process
information correctly. Some autistics are self-abusive and lack
social skills but excel in music, math and art.
   Generally, though, autism is misunderstood, said Mrs. Sullivan.
   ``I had people say, `Isn't it nice your little boy knows how to
draw,'' Mrs. Sullivan said.
   Mrs. Sullivan gave the movie credit for advancing knowledge of
autism, telling Hoffman, ``You have done with one film what we have
been trying to do in our field for 25 years.''
   Hoffman said, however, ``If we do one-tenth of what Mrs. Sullivan
has done, we will have made a little advance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
