<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--CanalettoCanvas     12-12 0113</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Canaletto Canvas,0116</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venetian Painting Sells for Record Amount</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A painting by Canaletto has been sold for
1.4 billion lire ($1.01 million), a record amount for a Venetian
artist's work, the Italian news service ANSA reported.
   The work, called ``The Bull Hunt in St. Mark's Piazza,'' was sold
at an auction Sunday in Venice's Giovannelli Palace.
   Canaletto, whose real name was Giovanni Antonio Canal, lived from
1697 to 1768 and won fame for his precisely painted views of Venice,
London and the English countryside.
   The previous record was not disclosed.
   Venice has a long artistic tradition and has produced such
painters as Titian, Paolo Veneziano and Giovanni Bellini.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0059EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland     12-12 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protestant Schoolgirl Crosses The Sectarian Divide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leanne Patton, a 16-year-old
Protestant, had never met a Roman Catholic until she went to a
memorial service for the victims of an IRA bombing and ended up
holding hands with two nuns.
   That moment at St. Anne's Cathedral in Belfast, when the minister
asked everyone in the overflowing congregation to join hands and
pray, marked a turning point in Leanne's life.
   She had been crying for the 11 people killed in Enniskillen on
Nov. 8, 1987 and was so wrapped up in the service she didn't realize
she had picked up the hands of two nuns who were sitting beside her.
   ``I went home and I thought, `I'm just really fed up that I have
to hate this woman because she's wearing a nun's habit, I have to
hate this fellow because he's a Catholic.' It just went over and
over in my mind, you know, what am I going to do?,'' she said.
   ``I'd never met any Catholics, never, never. ... My mom and dad
are very good, they really are. They didn't keep me away from
Catholics. It's just where I lived there weren't any,'' she said.
   In Northern Ireland, with its history of sectarian animosities,
it is common for youngsters, and even adults, never to have met
someone of another religion.
   Many of Northern Ireland's 1 million Protestants and 600,000
Catholics live in neighborhoods segregated along religious lines,
and all but 1,000 of the province's 350,000 children attend schools
that are almost entirely Protestant or Catholic.
   Leanne is studying for college entrance exams at mainly
Protestant Grosvenor High School in east Belfast.
   After the Enniskillen memorial service, she decided to try to
arrange an exchange with a Catholic high school.
   ``I never thought it would be anything big, just a small
meeting,'' Leanne said. ``I was a very quiet person ... but
something inside of me said, `I think you should really advertise
this,' and before I knew what I was saying, I asked ... if I could
(address) the school assembly.
   ``Well, I went and did that assembly, and they clapped and they
clapped and I was just shocked. I didn't think anybody felt the same
way I did. And there were hundreds of them. ... They said this is
the right thing we're doing.''
   The first exchange late last year was with a group of Catholic
students from two schools, Our Lady of Mercy and St. Patrick's.
   As the Grosvenor students waited for the Catholics to arrive,
Leanne said, ``they were literally trying to think what these
Catholics were going to look like. Are they going to talk funny and
what are their names going to be like?
   ``Because we'd never met, we just had these ideas about the other
side, and then when we came together, we just realized they were
just like us.''
   Over the past year, the students have exchanged further visits.
Friendships have grown outside school, with frequent visits to local
discos, restaurants and the movies, and shared stays at a
government-sponsored camp.
   The Grosvenor girls have also participated in a play, ``Bridges
of Celebration,'' with boys from Corpus Christi College, a Catholic
secondary school in west Belfast, an Irish Republican Army
stronghold. It filled the Opera House in Belfast and will be
performed again in Dublin in February.
   Recalling the first rehearsal, on neutral ground at Queen's
University in Belfast, Leanne said:
   ``When they first walked in ... they just sat down and stared at
you. I said, `Oh dear, what's this going to be like?' But then we
got to know them and we realized they were great.''
   She has no illusions that her activities will change the country.
``No way. I'm never going to become a Catholic and none of them are
ever going to become a Protestant just because they've met,'' she
said.
   ``But just the fact that we are meeting and becoming friends ...
it is harder to hate someone if you know them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
