<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JailedMoms     12-12 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jailed Moms,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Community Jailhouse For Pregnant Inmates Seeks To Preserve Mom-Baby
Bond</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new kind of state prison _ for pregnant inmates
only _ opens today in an effort to keep new mothers and their babies
together.
   Although a few other prison systems in the country make efforts
to allow mothers to remain for a time with their infants, the Neil
J. Houston House in Boston's Roxbury section will offer features
unavailable elsewhere.
   Separating women and babies at birth causes ``a serious rupture
in mother-infant bonding,'' said Lyla Austin, co-director of Social
Justice for Women, a private, non-profit advocacy group for women
prison inmates.
   The group will run the $550,000 program under a contract with the
state Department of Correction.
   ``It's a historic step for the state and the country, to show
respect for the mother and infant bond,'' Ms. Austin said last week.
   Currently, inmates in Massachusetts are separated from their
children and returned to their cells within days of giving birth.
   Inmates of the 15-bed facility will be confined to the building
but have access to counselors, drug rehabilitation, help in
readjusting to society and medical care during pregnancy and after.
   The first resident, expected to be admitted in January, will find
an atmosphere more like a halfway house than a jail. Guards will
wear civilian clothes.
   Only women eligible for early release will be considered for
admission, and it is expected that they will complete their
sentences at the house.
   ``Three years ago, Social Justice for Women decided some
immediate action was needed,'' Ms. Austin said. ``We had been
working with women at (the state prison at) Framingham. We saw the
numbers of pregnant women growing.''
   About 50 pregnant women go through the state prison system every
year; there were 17 prison births in 1986, the last year for which
figures were available.
   The average sentence for women convicted in this state is four
months, usually for drug-related crimes and prostitution, correction
officials said.
   Since 1980 the number of women imprisoned in Massachusetts has
risen 239 percent, an increase Ms. Austin attributed to the general
trend nationwide toward incarcerating people and away from sexism.
   Early in this century women routinely kept their babies with them
in prison until people began to worry about the stigma attached to
anyone who claimed a prison as their birthplace.
   More recently, New York started allowing babies born in prison to
stay with their mothers until their first birthday, said Kenneth
Perlman, deputy superintendent for services at the New York State
prison at Bedford Hills.
   ``The bonding that results is very positive, both for mother and
child, the way the babies develop and mature,'' Perlman said in a
telephone interview.
   In Georgia, qualified pregnant inmates receive a 60-day furlough
30 days before they are due to give birth so that delivery can occur
outside prison.
   But most women imprisoned in Georgia, like those in other states,
must return to their cells 40 to 72 hours after giving birth.
   Prison officials around the country said they knew of no such
community-based program and said the Massachusetts program sounded
like a good idea.
   ``I see when the women come in here that one of the hardest
things is being separated from their children,'' said Maureen
Atwood, associate warden of prisons at the federal minimum-security
prison for women in Alderson, W.Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
