<DOCNO> AP881212-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0118EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DanceBan     12-12 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dance Ban,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After First Dance, School Board Still Wants Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PURDY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first dance in this 100-year-old Ozark
town's high school is just a memory, but the students who thought it
was ``a blast'' may not get an encore.
   The school board is appealing a court ruling that its policy
against school dances is unconstitional. A federal appeals court
allowed Saturday night's dance while the matter is considered.
   Officials restricted the dance to Purdy High School's 161
students, saying they wanted to avoid any chance of trouble. Among
those barred were reporters and photographers, and even an alumnus
who was the lead plaintiff in the federal lawsuit that brought
dancing to Purdy High.
   Jonathan Clayton, a 1987 graduate, got only as close as the
basketball game that preceded the homecoming dance.
   ``It's OK, though _ I won,'' Clayton said as he watched the game
and greeted old friends. ``It's still worth it. The idea was to
allow Purdy students to have a dance, and we did that.''
   Clayton, a business school student, and 20 other Purdy students
and parents sued in 1986 to overturn the school board's written
policy banning dancing.
   Longtime residents in this town of 900 say Purdy has never been
without a ban on social dancing in the schools. Some have said they
associate dancing with drinking, drugs and illicit sex.
   But U.S. District Judge Russell Clark ruled this summer that the
school board's ban promoted the values of those who oppose dancing
for religious reasons.
   The board appealed Clark's order that they stop enforcing the
ban, but the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals is not expected to
rule in the case before next year.
   The dance ban evoked comparisons to the hit movie ``Footloose''
about a similar ban in a fictional town.
   Although barred from dancing at school, Purdy students have held
dances at the community center or in neighboring towns. But they
said that was inconvenient and unfair.
   Sheldon Buxton, superintendent of the Purdy school system, said
about 85 students attended Saturday night's dance. He said it went
smoothly, but he refused to comment on whether other dances could be
expected.
   Student council president Nancy Fox said board members attended
the dance. But the board members, who sat on the sidelines during
the dance talking among themselves, apparently did not cramp
students' style.
   ``It was a blast, we had a great time,'' Miss Fox said.
   ``It was really fun, everybody's dancing,'' said Shannon
Francisco, a senior who left the dance early.
   But Miss Francisco, 17, added that the dance had caused
controversy and bitterness in the southwestern Missouri town.
   ``I don't think it was worth all that,'' she said.
   Miss Fox, appearing tired but happy after a day that included a
college entrance exam and the history-making dance, said early
Sunday that she wasn't ready to plan another dance.
   ``I'm still thinking about cleanup for this one,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
