<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BaseClosings     12-12 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Base Closings,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Base-Closing Panel Will Meet Year-End Deadline, Chairman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presidential commission studying the nation's
more than 3,800 military installations is closing in on its goal of
determining which ones should be shut down.
   Former Rep. Jack Edwards, the Alabama Republican who is
co-chairman of the 12-member panel, says it will meet its year-end
deadline of recommending which bases should be closed.
   But Edwards said a final list has yet to be prepared by the
commission, which will report to Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci.
   ``People keep asking about a list and wanting to know how many
bases, but we don't have a goal in terms of numbers,'' he said. ``We
haven't made any final decisions yet.''
   The commission is an attempt to untie a congressional knot that
has blocked the Pentagon from closing any bases since 1977.
Legislators, loathe to lose the jobs that bases provide, have
erected a long and complicated series of barriers to individual
closings.
   ``Closing bases is tough for any congressman,'' said Rep. Les
Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee.
``You're talking lost jobs and that means unhappy voters. This is
near and dear to all our hearts.''
   Edwards said he doesn't know how many bases will be on the final
list, but Aspin predicted ``the figure will likely be 20 to 25
bases, perhaps a few more.''
   Aspin, who said he has purposefully remained aloof from the
panel's work, estimated that annual savings will be about $2 billion.
   Besides evaluating data from the Pentagon, the commission is also
listening to petitions from congressmen and their constituents.
   Last week, Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., delivered more than
13,000 letters from Enid, Okla., urging the panel not to close Vance
Air Force Base.
   Earlier, legislators from northeastern states ranging from Maine
to New Jersey and Pennsylvania had written the panel, urging that
Sunbelt states suffer the most reductions because they said those
states had the most bases.
   After the Edwards' panel finishes its work, Carlucci will have
until Jan. 15 _ five days before he leaves office _ to accept or
reject the entire list. He can't make any other changes.
   If Carlucci approves the list as expected, Congress could only
block the closures if the House and Senate each pass a disapproval
resolution. That resolution could be vetoed by George Bush, meaning
it would effectively take a two-thirds vote in each chamber to block
the shutdowns.
   Edwards explained that his panel is using a complicated set of
criteria to make its decisions.
   First, installations are being grouped by military mission; for
example, all Army depots, all Air Force fighter bases, all Navy
ports for surface ships.
   Then bases in a particular category will be evaluated for five
factors _ mission suitability, including geographical location and
ease of deployment; physical facilities in place; the quality of
those facilities; quality of life for personnel, such as housing;
and community support.
   Bases at the bottom of each ``mission'' list will be considered
for closure, partly by determining if other, higher-ranking bases
can become ``receiving'' facilities.
   Next, cost evaluations will be done, environmental factors such
as hazardous waste problems will be considered, and the impact of
the lost jobs will be weighed.
   ``It's an extremely complicated process,'' said Edwards. ``We
have a huge amount of information to evaluate and judgments to
make.''
   The Pentagon and the services haven't offered any lists. ``What
we have done is asked the services for information, a tremendous
amount of information,'' he said.
   ``We're checking that information by sending staff members and
commission members out to the bases in some instances, talking to
base commanders and local people.''
   Edwards insists politics isn't an issue. ``This the most
non-partisan committee I've ever been associated with. Believe me,
that's the truth.''
   ``We don't look at our charge as having anything to do with
politics. We haven't looked at whose district a base is located
in,'' he said. ``Obviously, everybody else in Washington approaches
it from the perspective of politics, but we haven't.''
</TEXT>
