<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-12 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There were cats with no hair. Cats with too
much. Blow-dried cats. Brushed cats. Cats from animal shelters and
cats with pedigrees to meow about.
   The 600 felines at the International Cat Show held in San
Francisco this weekend attracted more than 8,000 humans.
   ``Most of us have multiple breeds,'' said Bill Schumacher of
Albuquerque, N.M. ``I own a Persian, several Maine Coons and
Chartreux.''
   He said cats undoubtedly reflect their owners' personalities.
   ``If a person is very flamboyant and outspoken, they'll go for a
flashy cat, like a black or white Persian,'' said Schumacher.
``Someone who is shy and reserved would go for a much more mellow
cat, a British Blue or an American Shorthair.
   ``But a lot of people like bigger and better so they go for the
big cats like Maine Coons or Rag Dolls, which are 36 inches long.''
   A cat named Elvis won the Supercat Contest. The long-haired
Siamese and tabby mix is named for singer Elvis Costello.
   His owner, Linn Hom, said she may enter her $25 cat from an
animal shelter in future contests, but she won't alter his strict
training regimen: ``All he does is sleep and eat all day.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patriot Patrick Henry showed up in
this southern Illinois town. Ulysses S. Grant and Robert E. Lee have
visited, too.
   Their appearances have been thanks to teacher Phil Alsman, who
began dressing up in historical costumes to perk up his ``boring''
history classes.
   ``After Christopher Columbus, I even had a couple of kids come
after me wanting autographs,'' said Alsman, laughing. ``I had one
woman call me up and say, `Will you tell my boy Christopher Columbus
is dead?'''
   Alsman, 42, conceived his gimmick three years ago when he was
tapped to teach history to seventh graders. He had taught science
for 16 years, but his history background was limited.
   ``To me, it was very boring,'' he said. ``I felt that they needed
something that they could relate to at that time.''
   So the next day he came dress up as Patrick Henry for a class on
the Revolutionary War.
   Alsman, who has no formal acting training, recalled the first
time he wore the costume he felt ``silly.''
   ``You ought to see all the people give me second looks,'' he
said. ``I don't know who was more dumbfounded, the students or the
staff _ because teachers don't dress weird.''
   Alsman became principal of Arlington Grade School in September.
But that hasn't stopped his theatrics.
   He's treated the school to Christopher Columbus and ``the unknown
pilgrim.'' He also performs before civic groups.
   ``Once I get into the costume, I never respond to anything other
than that person,'' said Alsman. ``It's serious to me because I
think American history is not something to be laughed about.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state has $3 million in checks it
can't seem to give away.
   Companies and residents across Pennsylvania have not cashed
thousands of checks worth almost $3 million issued by the state
Treasury Department in 1984, 1985, and 1986.
   Even governmental agencies have been lax. In 1986, for example,
about 25 checks to townships, boroughs, cities and county
governments totaling more than $30,000 were uncashed, according to
department records.
   The blame may simply lie in the foibles of human nature, but for
department officials it's a serious problem they're trying to solve.
   ``Why haven't they been cashed? Who knows?'' said Greg Penney,
executive assistant to state Treasurer G. Davis Greene Jr. ``You
almost have to ask the question `Why haven't auditors caught this?'
''
   The volume of unclaimed payments has led the Treasury Department
to start a program to trace the recipients of wayward checks.
   Since Nov. 21, Edward L. Short, director of the Treasury's Bureau
of Investigation, and his staff have returned $38,640 to various
municipalities.
   ``Human nature being what it is (the recipients) just put them in
drawers or use them as book marks. Or kids find checks of their
parents after they've died. We're just trying to get money back to
the people,'' Short said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
