<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Deficit     12-12 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deficit,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Social Security, Taxes Eyed By Deficit Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican co-chairman of the National
Economic Commission says the government should consider taking back
some of the Social Security benefits paid to higher-income
individuals.
   Drew Lewis expressed optimism Sunday that the 12-member panel
eventually will produce a consensus report on cutting the federal
deficit, with the emphasis on reduced federal spending.
   ``The position all of us have taken is that we're going to
address this based on cutting the spending,'' Lewis, a former
transportation secretary in the Reagan administration, said on NBC's
``Meet the Press'' program.
   However, he added, ``this does not mean if we are not able to
address the issue on that basis, that there are not a number of
members on the commission who would prefer a tax increase.''
   Lewis specifically mentioned, as ``a last resort,'' some sort of
consumption tax that would be adjusted according to each
individual's ability to pay.
   He also offered the term ``rebates'' to describe other revenue
sources which do not involve raising taxes. Among these rebates, he
said, would be taking back some of the Social Security benefits paid
to people with other incomes over $90,000 a year, and collecting
repayment of some Medicare benefits from the estates of wealthy
elderly recipients who die.
   Lewis said he did not think much of the savings could be achieved
in military spending. ``Over half the budget is now in entitlements
and interest. Unfortunately, that's where we're going to have to go
if we're going to find reductions in spending,'' he said.
   Lewis' Democratic counterpart on the panel. Robert Strauss,
appeared on the same program and said he believes that simply
cutting spending won't be enough.
   ``I must tell you that in my judgment I have not found sufficient
spending cuts to make up the shortfall'' in meeting a
deficit-reducing target, said Strauss.
   Such a finding by the panel would be directly at odds with
President-elect Bush's campaign pledge not to raise taxes. Democrats
are turning up the heat for Bush to show how he would close the $35
billion gap in meeting next year's deficit-reduction goal.
   ``I haven't seen a way to get there without some increased
revenue. Hopefully we'll find it. If we don't, I'm going to be for
some increased revenue,'' said Strauss, a former Democratic national
chairman.
   Tax increases, while viewed as political poison, have been
identified by many economists as the only realistic way to slash
deficits and calm nervous financial markets. Though Strauss has
expressed similar opinions in the past, he was unusually blunt in
Sunday's public appraisal.
   Strauss said he would consider so-called ``sin taxes'' on alcohol
and tobacco, or a gasoline or other broad-based energy tax, as
likely sources for the needed revenue.
   Such ideas have received broad support from many members of
Congress. Strauss also agreed that Social Security payments to
high-income Americans _ such as himself _ should be taxed.
   Upper-income recipients of Social Security now pay taxes on half
their benefits under a provision that was part of a 1983 change in
the law. Some commission witnesses have suggested boosting that
level to 85 percent.
</TEXT>
