<DOCNO> AP881212-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Quake-WorldAid     12-12 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quake-World Aid,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquake Relief Makes Unlikely Bedfellows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Soviet Quake, Bjt
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   From the Jewish state of Israel to the Moslem nation of Iran, the
earthquake in Soviet Armenia spurred nations across the world to set
aside political differences and rush to the aid of the stricken
Soviets.
   Children opened their piggy banks, musicians offered their art
and a search dog wearing a Star of David on his chest was flown into
the region as part of an international mission of mercy.
   The Red Cross and Red Crescent relief organizations announced
that 23 countries worldwide collected about $44 million in aid, the
official Soviet news agency Tass reported Sunday.
   In Montreal, the donations were so great they couldn't all fit
onto one plane. A Soviet aircraft loaded with about 80 search and
rescue workers, six dogs and 9{ tons of medical supplies and winter
clothing was delayed for hours at Mirabel Airport on Sunday while
workers tried to cram everything aboard.
   Armenians in Iran were organizing a medical team and collecting
money to help victims, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
   Though Soviet-Iranian relations improved somewhat with the
increasing U.S. military presence in the Persian Gulf, they have
often been strained. Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini has
backed Moslem rebels fighting Soviet and government troops in
Afghanistan.
   In Jerusalem, a 42-member Israeli rescue team headed by an army
general flew to Yerevan, the Armenian capital, to help search for
earthquake survivors.
   The team included experts specially trained in operating heavy
cranes, several doctors, and an Alsatian shepherd dog named Tim, who
is trained to sniff people under rubble and wore a red Star of David
on a white chest cloth.
   Two other planes were scheduled to fly to the Soviet Union today
with a 46-member medical team, equipment and 4{ tons of medical
supplies.
   The Soviet Union broke diplomatic relations with Israel after the
1967 Middle East war and does not officially recognize the Jewish
state, but relations have been gradually warming.
   The United States' Armenian community collected millions of
dollars for relief.
   ``This little girl came with her grandfather, and she apparently
had a piggy bank that she was saving for Christmas. She said
`Grandpa, instead of me getting something, why don't I give this'''
said Hazel Barsamian, who is working with the Armenian Relief
Society's Chicago chapter.
   A hastily assembled telethon that ran from midnight Saturday to 6
a.m. Sunday on the West Coast drew $2.9 million in pledges, said Los
Angeles station KSCI-TV. The telethon was shown on that station, on
cable channels throughout Southern California, and on independent
stations in Houston; Norfolk, Va.; Seattle; San Francisco; and
Sacramento, Calif.
   In Washington, President Reagan told reporters that four U.S.
planes had already arrived in Armenia to provide help.
   The London branch of Moscow Narodny Bank, the Soviet state bank,
said late Sunday that donations to earthquake relief from the
British public had reached $1.04 million.
   Organizers of British relief efforts announced a London concert
to raise money for victims. Conductor Andre Previn, flutist James
Galway and cellist Mstislav Rostropovich are among those scheduled
to perform Saturday.
   Almost 30 tons of emergency relief supplies, mostly blankets and
clothing, were flown out of London's Heathrow Airport, officials
said. The supplies were donated mainly by individuals who drove them
to the airport from throughout southern England.
   Not all the relief efforts went smoothly.
   A Dutch medical relief crew was refused visas to assist in the
rescue operations, according to a Red Cross spokesman speaking on
condition of anonymity in Amsterdam, the Netherlands. The source
said Soviet diplomats claimed no more foreign relief was needed.
   Some foreign relief workers said they ran into snags upon
reaching the disaster areas.
   ``The relief effort until you reach the spot here has been very
good,'' said Sverre Kilde, a Norwegian U.N. officer. ``But here on
the spot there is no control.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
