<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Fire 8thLd-Writethru   12-12 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Fire, 8th Ld-Writethru,a0787,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fireworks Explosion Kills 61</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with four grafs to update death toll. Picks up 4th pvs,
``They can't ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illegal fireworks exploded in a crowded street
market Sunday and started a chain reaction and fire that spread to
five buildings, killing at least 61 people and injuring 45.
   ``We'll be searching all night. They're still finding bodies,''
said Salvador Padillo, the Red Cross commander at the scene.
   Floodlights lit the narrow street and an alley as rescuers dug
into the night, putting bodies on stretchers, tagging them and
putting them in ambulances. A bulldozer began plowing away the
rubble.
   At least 61 people were killed, Commander Enrique Mejia
Guadarrama of the Red Cross said early Monday.
   ``They can't get inside the storerooms, but they are full of
bodies,'' said Roberto Castanon Romo, city director of medical
services. ``You can no longer talk of survivors.''
   At least 11 of the dead were children, officials said.
   Padillo said at least 45 people were injured, but an official on
duty at Red Cross headquarters put the number at 83. Two
firefighters were among the injured, medical workers said.
   The first explosion apparently was in a market stall set up in a
narrow street leading to the popular Merced market and jammed with
Christmas shoppers, said Red Cross worker Jorge Torres San Juan.
   Fire spread to a two-story building of candy and fireworks shops,
where fireworks also were stored, and to a building of candy shops
next door.
   A city legal official, Jesus Sandoval, said the fireworks were
being sold illegally.
   The shops ``were all full of people buying,'' Luis Contreras,
another rescue worker said.
   After the explosions began, an estimated 500 people streamed from
the building screaming, ``Get out, get out,'' said Fernando
Dominguez, who was working in shoe store less than 100 feet away.
   ``At first it sounded like bullets. Then there were more and more
and then the explosion,'' Dominguez said.
   The narrow street was crowded with people buying fireworks for
the celebration of the Day of the Virgin of Guadalupe on Monday.
   The explosion began with one crate of fireworks on the end of the
street nearest the Merced, said Mario Roberto Andrade, who lives
next to one of the buildings that caught fire and was in the street
at the time. He said boxes of fireworks kept exploding down the
street.
   Windows shattered throughout the block. Spent Chinese
firecrackers, charred wood and comic books, twisted metal and
tangles of high tension wires littered the street.
   As smoke billowed from the second floor of the building more than
two hours after the fire was reported at 2:40 p.m., six young men on
the third floor refused to leave.
   ``We're staying here to hold onto our things,'' one shouted to
police. ``If it were your house, you'd do the same.''
   Police sent firemen and police officers into the building.
   By about 5 p.m. fires had been extinguished in a six-story
building across the street and a four-story building down the block.
Some smoke also was coming from one floor of an apartment building.
   For at least an hour, the white smoke could be seen billowing
from the site from more than two miles away. As darkness fell, a
bulldozer began plowing away the rubble.
   Distraught relatives searched for missing relatives while vendors
and residents vented anger at Mayor Manuel Camacho Solis, who walked
through the water-soaked debris of burned metal, canvas street
stalls, and scattered merchandise.
   ``Many children died here, Mr. Mayor,'' said one man.
   Earlier, Victor Gutierrez Cruz, a leader of the area's commercial
association, said it had been protesting illegal sales of fireworks.
He complained that people who don't belong to the group come in and
sell fireworks without permits during the holidays.
   ``These present a great danger .... to the shops,'' he said.
   District Attorney Ignacio Morales Lechuga said that fireworks are
illegal to sell without a permit.
   ``This does not mean there is going to be an attack on Mexican
culture,'' he said. ``These things (fireworks) are part of Mexican
culture.''
   ``It's a case of corruption,'' said Andrade's wife, Angelica
Peredo. ``We don't want street vendors selling fireworks here.''
   For years, the Merced was the main market in this city of 18
million, supplying dozens of other markets and individual customers.
   A new main market was built on the edge of the city in 1982, but
the Merced remains important because of tradition and its location
about half a mile from the main Zocalo Plaza in a densely populated
area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
