<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Quake-Scene     12-12 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quake-Scene,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Still Search for Survivors in Collapsed Apartment Building</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Soviet Quake, Bjt
^By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINAKAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outside the ruins of 270 Sverdlovsk
St., families picked at the heap of wreckage that used to be home
and prayed that relatives still buried in the rubble might somehow
survive.
   Several people were pulled from the 50-apartment building alive
immediately after Wednesday's earthquake, but by Sunday, relatives
of the missing were losing hope.
   Stacks of red, black or unfinished wood coffins were piled on
street corners.
   Eduard Manoyan knew that his wife, mother-in-law and a
brother-in-law were dead. The three were in a ground floor apartment
when the quake struck.
   Tamara Kazaryan's husband had found his son but not his wife, who
had come home from work for her lunch break when the earth began to
shake and the long, five-story concrete building collapsed.
   ``We don't know whether anyone is alive or not,'' said Mrs.
Kazaryan's husband, a laborer. ``I went to the school where my son
studies. The building was ruined, but he was alive. Then I came home
and started searching for my wife.''
   People were trying to dig out their belongings from one end of
the 15-year-old building, which was built on a slight rise above the
street and had slid into a heap by the roadside. Some worked in a
pile of rubble, digging through the ruins. Others simply milled
about.
   A young man was accused of trying to steal something, and
shouting erupted. Soldiers arrested the man and led him away.
   Everywhere, officials and rescuers pleaded for more cranes and
heavy equipment to drag slabs of concrete and twisted pillars off
trapped people.
   At one site, rescuers worked feverishly with saws, torches,
hammers and crowbars to free a family of seven discovered near the
top of what was a nine-story apartment building.
   Survivors who spoke about the tragedy described a series of three
or four quakes separated by brief pauses.
   Mayor Emil Kirokofyan told a group of foreign correspondents that
recently constructed apartment buildings were not built to withstand
such a severe temblor _ even though Leninakan is in an area of
frequent earthquakes.
   Choking back tears, the mayor told reporters he lost 15 relatives.
   Hundreds of bonfires fueled by cardboard, trash or debris
provided the only heat for people who had spent four nights on the
streets. They sent a pall of smoke over the city of 250,000 people.
   ``I don't have anywhere to live. I am homeless,'' cried an old
woman walking out of rescue headquarters, where officials had put
her on a list for new housing.
   Manoyan, a machinist who found his wife and relatives dead,
appealed to the foreign reporters, who were touring the disaster
area at the invitation of the Foreign Ministry.
   ``As a member of the Armenian nation, I ask you to give us
help,'' he said. ``We need equipment. The city is in ruins.''
   Some aid that was given proved useless. After people had been
digging through the rubble with their hands for three days, a crane
arrived Saturday. But the next day, it was parked beside the ruins,
motionless. Workers said it was too small.
</TEXT>
