<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HugATree     12-12 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hug A Tree,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Project Goal: Help Save Wilderness Trail</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAY, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Josh Farnsworth stood on a mountainside with snow
blowing around him and the wind cutting through his coat. He
reluctantly pulled off his mittens to write down the name of the
40-foot tree towering in front of him.
   ``I think I'm going to call it `Three Splits,''' said the
9-year-old, as he scrutinized the maple that split at its base into
three separate trunks. Then, he measured the base with his scarf and
paced off the distance from the tree to a trail marker 15 feet away.
   Josh and other pupils at Derby Elementary School in neary Derby
will use the information to find sponsors for dozens of trees along
the 265-mile Long Trail, a hiking trail that runs north-south from
Massachusetts to Canada.
   The proceeds will be used by the Green Mountain Club to buy some
of the 67 miles of unprotected, privately owned land along the trail.
   ``The Long Trail is one of the treasures of Vermont. This is one
of the few true wilderness experiences on the East Coast,'' said
teacher Doug Westin.
   The project also is introducing dozens of fourth, fifth and sixth
graders to a different way of learning science, history and math,
and a way to apply their skills to benefit their community, he said.
   The Long Trail program, which includes a pupil-produced history
book about the trail, began this fall at a school that has earned a
reputation for developing unusual, creative projects that extend
beyond its red brick borders and into the 4,200-member community on
the Vermont-Quebec border.
   The school just won an award from the American Association for
State and Local History for last year's project, a set of 109 short
stories the pupils prepared and read on a radio station.
   The school also was honored recently as a finalist for the
National Education Association's A+ award for its projects, Westin
said.
   The projects begin in Westin's ``Challenge Room,'' a classroom
where he was told five years ago to establish a program for gifted
pupils.
   But the program is ``really open to anybody in the school who has
a serious interest. It's not just for kids with high IQs,'' said Ed
Hartman, guidance counselor.
   Individual pupils participate for six weeks, three days a week,
about 45 minutes each day. Or the projects can involve entire
classes, like Josh's. Earlier this month, he and his classmates
boarded a bus for the half-hour drive to the Long Trail on Jay Peak.
   Up on the trail, the youngsters fanned out to pick a tree.
Ten-year-old Rebecca Jenness sat in the snow in front of her tree, a
gray birch with roots raised to form a hole above the soil.
   ``What does it look like?'' Westin asked.
   ``A troll's house,'' Rebecca answered.
   ``Oh, beautiful,'' he said in praise.
   Rebecca said the project helps her learn in a way that's more
enjoyable than sitting at a desk.
   ``You learn about nature,'' agreed classmate Shannon Castl.
   Hartman said the projects help develop an interest in the
outdoors. ``I don't think it's going to turn them all into
environmentalists, and that's not our goal. But I would like them to
be at least as aware as they are of video games or what's going on
in sports.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0049 </DOCNO>
