<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthKorea     12-12 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North Korea,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Announces Reshuffle Of Prominent Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea's premier was relieved of his position
today for health reasons and resigned from the ruling Politburo, the
country's official news agency said.
   The Korean Central News Agency report, monitored in Tokyo, said
Premier Li Gun Mo will be replaced by Yon Hyong Muk, a Politburo
member and secretary of the Korean Workers' (Communist) Party.
   It said the changes were approved at an extraordinary session of
the Supreme People's Assembly.
   Li had been premier since Dec. 29, 1986. Little is known about
him.
   On Saturday, KCNA reported that the communist party's 15-member
standing committee had requested an extraordinary meeting of the
assembly. That prompted speculation the party could have important
decisions to be approved by the congress.
   Another official report, from Radio Pyongyang, said a son of
party leader Kim Il Sung, Kim Pyong Il, was appointed ambassador to
Bulgaria.
   Kim Pyong Il became ambassador to Hungary in August but returned
to North Korea in September to protest Hungary's agreement with
South Korea to exchange permanent trade offices in their capital
cities.
   Kim Pyong Il was director-general of North Korea's People's Armed
Forces Bureau prior to his appointment as ambassador to Hungary.
   The appointment of a new ambassador to Hungary was not announced,
according to Radio Press, a Japanese news agency that monitors
communist bloc broadcasts.
   North Korea is believed to have downgraded its relations with
Hungary to one requiring the exchange of deputy ambassadors, Radio
Press said.
   The Supreme People's Assembly also approved the appointment of
Han Song Ryong to replace Yong Hyong Muk as secretary of the party's
central committee, KCNA said.
   Hyon Jun Guk was appointed editor-in-chief of the official
newspaper, the Rodong Sinmun, a position formerly held by Chu Chang
Jun. Chu Gyo Chang, a central committee member, was appointed to
Hyon's position as head of the party's international department.
   The assembly meeting came at a time when some of communist North
Korea's closest allies are improving their ties with South Korea.
   Since the Summer Olympics in South Korea, the Soviet Union and
China have increased their economic and cultural contacts with the
capitalist South. Hungary, Yugoslavia, Poland, Bulgaria and the
Soviet Union have agreed to exchange trade offices with South Korea.
   The two Koreas were divided in 1945 after World War II when U.S.
and Soviet troops ended the Japanese occupation of Korea.
</TEXT>
