<HEAD>Faye Dunaway, Sylvester Stallone Receive 1988 Rudy Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie tough guy Sylvester Stallone and sultry
screen actress Faye Dunaway were chosen to represent the spirit of
legendary silent film star Rudolph Valentino at the 1988 Rudy Awards.
   Stallone, who starred in the ``Rocky'' and ``Rambo'' action film
series, and Miss Dunaway, who won an Academy Award for best actress
in ``Network,'' received statuette images of ``The Sheik.''
   Celebrities such as Shirley MacLaine, Rita Moreno, Gary Collins
and Stallone's mother, Jacqueline, attended the 17th annual
presentation of the awards Sunday night.
   Italian vintner Carlo Apollonio created the awards in 1972
honoring career achievement in memory of the late Italian-born
silent-film actor and to foster better relation between Italy and
Hollywood.
   Dunaway, 47, has starred in such films as ``Chinatown,'' ``The
Thomas Crown Affair,'' ``Little Big Man,'' ``Three Days of the
Condor,'' ``The Champ,'' ``The Three Musketeers'' and ``Barfly.''
   Stallone, 42, also has appeared in ``The Lords of Flatbush,''
``F.I.S.T.,'' ``Paradise Alley'' and ``Death Race 2000.''
