<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marcos     12-12 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Philippine President to Undergo More Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposed Philippine president Ferdinand Marcos
faces more medical tests after being hospitalized for what his aides
have called congestive heart failure.
   Marcos, 71, remained in guarded but stable condition late Sunday
at St. Francis Medical Center, according to nursing supervisor
Mildred Kim.
   Marcos, who contends he is too ill to travel to New York for
arraignment on federal racketeering charges, was admitted to the
hospital Friday.
   Aides said Marcos suffered congestive heart failure after
learning his eldest daughter, Imee Manotoc, was experiencing
complications during childbirth in Morocco, where she lives.
   Cardiologist Dr. Calvin Wong said Marcos would remain in the
hospital ``for a few days'' while additional tests are performed.
More tests were scheduled for today, he said.
   Tests have established that Marcos has weakened heart muscles _
or cardiomyopathy, Wong said, adding that victims of the condition
``are prone to develop congestive heart failure.''
   Wong, however, declined to say whether Marcos had suffered
congestive heart failure, when the heart is not strong enough to
pump a sufficient amount of blood. He also would not elaborate on
the nature of the tests scheduled for today.
   ``It's not just because this is the former president of the
Philippines,'' Wong said. ``Any of my patients, I would answer in
the same noncommittal way.''
</TEXT>
