<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HijackAttempt     12-12 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack Attempt,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Exile Awaits Extradition After Hijacking Attempt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban exile tricked into thinking he had diverted
a jet with 128 people to Havana faces extradition from Grand Turk
for only the second hijacking attempt of a domestic U.S. airliner in
2{ years, officials said.
   Weary but unharmed, the 121 passengers and seven crew members
aboard the TWA Boeing 727 flight from San Juan arrived in Miami on
Sunday evening. They said the hijacker was not violent and was
shocked when he was arrested on Grand Turk, part of the British
colony of Turks and Caicos Islands southeast of the Bahamas.
   ``He was horrified to realize he had been tricked,'' said
passenger Willie Douglas of Montgomery, Ala.
   Robert Blattner, a spokesman at TWA headquarters in St. Louis,
identified the would-be hijacker as Felix Sanchez Rodriguez, 26, who
left Cuba during the 1980 Mariel boatlift.
   Larry Torrence of the FBI's Miami office said the suspect
remained in Grand Turk and extradition proceedings were scheduled to
begin today. A device that Rodriguez claimed to be a bomb proved to
be harmless, officials said.
   Blattner said Rodriguez apparently wanted to return to Cuba to
see his ailing mother.
   ``A couple of times he leaned over some people and told them
everything's going to be all right,'' said passenger Tom Patri.
   The pilot of the Flight 469 was able to get permission to land on
Grand Turk island where police were able to convince Rodriguez he
was in Havana, Miller said.
   Luis Carlos Motta of Cali, Colombia, who acted as an interpreter
during the hijacking, said Rodriguez tapped him on the shoulder and
gave him a letter that said in red ink ``This is a hijacking.'' He
told Motta he had a bomb and said it would be activated by his watch.
   ``He said `I want to stay in Cuba. Please tell the captain, we go
to Cuba,'' according to Motta. Motta said the man was very nervous,
and that the plane banked to land on the first island it approached.
   ``As they landed he saw a fire engine (and several cars) and said
`Really, we are not in Cuba. I know the cars in Cuba,''' Motta said.
   The pilot and the interpreter convinced him that a civilian would
have to greet him, and when he left the plane he was arrested, Motta
said.
   It was the first hijacking of a domestic U.S. flight since May 3,
1986, when a man hijacked a Horizon Air commuter jet with 11 other
passengers and two crewmembers en route to Medford, Ore., and
demanded to go to Phoenix. The plane landed at Hillsboro, Ore., and
the hijacker was arrested.
   Hijackings to Cuba were common in the late 1960s and early '70s,
prompting the security measures now commonplace at airports. The
only previous hijacking involving a U.S. commercial flight this year
occurred in October, when three soldiers in Haiti stormed aboard an
American Airlines jetliner for New York during a period of political
turmoil in their country.
   On May 25, a flight mechanic without a pilot's license stole a
private jet in Newport News, Va., and took it on a 1,600-mile
joyride to Denver, where he shot himself as authorities closed in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0543EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Scene 1stLd-Writethru a0468 12-12 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illegal Fireworks Strewn Amid Fire Debris</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf to UPDATE death toll.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strewn throughout the charred, water-soaked
debris of what hours before had been a thriving street market were
the fireworks that set the market and five buildings ablaze.
   It happened Sunday, the eve of the Day of Virgin of Guadalupe.
One of the ways Mexicans honor their patron saint is by shooting
skyrockets, Roman candles and other fireworks. They keep firing them
sporadically through New Year's.
   Though barred by a little-enforced law, fireworks abound in
markets like that on Corona Street, especially during national and
religious holidays.
   A woman of about 60 said authorities have sometimes confiscated
the fireworks.
   ``This year there was nobody. Nobody came to take the fireworks
away,'' she said. ``The street was completely full of fireworks. It
was full of people. The Day of Guadalupe. So many dead. My God.''
   Authorities early today didn't know what ignited the fireworks,
triggering the series of explosions and fire that killed at least 70
people.
   Some witnesses said a spilled gas tank was to blame, others a
carelessly tossed cigarette. But the fire scarred both sides of
Corona Street, whipping through the well-known Candy Market, an
apartment building, two other structures containing apartments and
shops, and yet another where fireworks were stored and sold.
   ``All these people, it took away part of their lives,'' said
Marcel Guera, who has a market stall and ran to the scene after the
first explosion. ``They lost everything, and they live from one day
to the next.''
   Red Cross rescue worker Antonio Guayaberra said 22 of the victims
died in one structure next to the apartment building.
   ``Most of those found dead there were huddled together. Burned,''
he said.
   Many of them were on upper floors and apparently had shut
themselves inside the building to escape the flames, dense curtain
of smoke and popping fireworks outside, Guayaberra said.
   The smoke lifted to reveal the remnants of a bustling marketplace.
   A child's pail lay on its side in the muck; nearby, a pair of
women's shoes. On a table sat blackened soot in the classic pyramid
shape that fruit sellers use. Red, yellow and blue berries and the
candy Corona street was known for were scattered about. Red and
silver Christmas rope draped across the remains of a food stand.
   Dozens of gasoline cans, like those used to cook tacos and other
typical Mexican fare at open-air stands, littered the street.
   And everywhere, in the grime of Corona street and an adjacent
alleyway, were Chinese firecrackers, skyrockets and Roman candles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
