<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChicagoMayoral     12-12 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Mayoral,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Announces Candidacy For 2-Year Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer launched a bid to stay in
office, saying he had ``kept our city together'' in troubled times
after the death of Mayor Harold Washington.
   Sawyer announced his candidacy Sunday for next year's special
election as a new poll showed him trailing Cook County State's
Attorney Richard M. Daley in a one-on-one race for the Democratic
nomination.
   ``I look forward to the contest. I know it won't be easy,''
Sawyer told about 700 supporters at a rally at a downtown hotel. ``I
need your help and your hard work and your prayers.''
   Sawyer, 54, enters a field of six other candidates who have
announced they are vying for his job. The election will be for a
two-year term, the remainder of Washington's second four-year term.
   ``In the past 12 months, I have been on the firing line day in an
day out,'' he told his supporters. ``I've taken some shots, fairly
and unfairly, but I have kept our city together and we've made great
progress through some very difficult times.''
   Sawyer was elected acting mayor by fellow aldermen during a
raucous City Council meeting last December after Washington, the
city's first black mayor, died of a heart attack.
   The new mayoral poll, published in Sunday's Chicago Tribune,
showed Daley beating Sawyer by a margin of 59 percent to 30 percent.
Daley is the son of legendary Mayor Richard J. Daley, who ruled
Chicago for more than 20 years until his death in 1976.
   The telephone survey of 1,038 registered Chicago voters showed
Daley beating Alderman Timothy Evans, Sawyer's chief rival for the
support of black voters, by a 56-34 margin. Sawyer and Evans are
black.
   Jesse Jackson would give Daley the toughest opposition in the
mayoral race, garnering 40 percent to Daley's 52 percent, according
to the poll, which was conducted Dec. 2-5 and has a margin of error
of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
   Jackson on Saturday said he was not a candidate.
   Political analysts said the survey was very early and did not
mean much.
   ``I don't put much stock in December polls when the election is
the last day of February, said Paul Green, a professor of political
science at Governors State University in suburban University Park.
   Last month, the Illinois Supreme Court set April 4 as the date
for a special election. The Democratic primary is scheduled for Feb.
28.
   Green said Sawyer has between $2 million and $3 million in a
campaign war chest. ``He's got a large kitty, so obviously he's
going to be able to get his message across,'' the analyst said.
   The Democratic primary has generally been tantamount to winning
the general election in Chicago's recent history. But that changed
somewhat in 1983 when a white Republican candidate made a strong
showing in a losing effort against Washington.
   The other announced Democratic candidates are Aldermen Lawrence
Bloom, Edward Burke and Danny Davis and former state Sen. James
Taylor.
   Former Chicago Parks Superintendent Edmund Kelly withdrew from
the Democratic field the day after Daley announced his candidacy and
the Chicago Sun-Times on Sunday said Burke also quit the race.
   Edward Howlett, son of a former Democratic secretary of state, is
the only announced GOP candidate.
</TEXT>
