<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frigid Air Hits Great Lakes States, Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An arctic air mass plunged temperatures below zero in the Great
Lakes states and the Northeast today, setting record lows in parts
of New York state.
   Readings were below zero this morning in northern New England,
much of New York state, Michigan and Minnesota, and only in the
single digits in eastern Minnesota, southern parts of the Great
Lakes, the northern Ohio Valley and southern New England.
   Record lows for today's date were set in Albany, N.Y. minus 7;
Binghamton, N.Y., minus 7; and Buffalo, N.Y., minus 5.
   The nation's high Sunday was 83 degrees in the Florida cities of
Fort Lauderdale and West Palm Beach.
   A weather system moving across the southern Plains was bringing
snow to eastern Oklahoma, where 1 to 2 inches were expected, and
Arkansas, where 2 to 4 inches were possible.
   A developing low pressure system off the Carolina coast may bring
winter weather there late tonight. Winter storm watches were posted
for tonight and Tuesday for eastern North Carolina and all of South
Carolina.
   Showers continued in the Florida peninsula, but were much weaker
than the Sunday thunderstorms that produced strong winds. The gusts
caused window damage and flipped over a boat in a yard at St.
Petersburg, and uprooted trees near Sarasota. A tornado damaged the
roofs of 15 homes at Treasure Island.
   Today's forecast called for snow showers in upper Michigan,
Wisconsin and northeast Minnesota; scattered rain in northwest
Montana and along the northern Pacific coast; rain and occasional
thunderstorms from eastern South Carolina across southern Georgia
and Florida.
   Temperatures were to be 15 or more degrees below normal for
mid-December from New England and the lower Great Lakes across the
central Gulf of Mexico coast and northern Florida. Montana was to
have temperatures up to 25 degrees higher than normal for the season.
   Predicted highs: single digits and teens in New England, inland
New York state and upper Michigan; 20s and 30s from Pennsylvania
across the Carolinas, from northern parts of the central Gulf of
Mexico states across the rest of the Great Lakes, the upper
two-thirds of the Mississippi Valley, the central Missouri Valley
and North Dakota; 60s in central Florida to near 80 across southern
Florida; 60s in southern Texas; 50s in western and central Montana;
60s and 70s from central and Southern California across southern
Arizona.
   The rest of the nation generally should reach the 40s and 50s.
   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from minus 17
degrees at Niagara Falls, N.Y., to 76 at Key West (Fla.) Naval Air
Station.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 32 fair; Boston 3 windy; Buffalo minus 8 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 34 fair; Cincinnati 12 fair; Cleveland 15 snow;
Detroit 1 fair; Miami 72 cloudy; New York 9 fair; Pittsburgh 8
cloudy; Portland, Maine, 1 fair; Washington 19 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 24 cloudy; Chicago 16 cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 41 cloudy; Denver 27 fair; Des Moines 17 cloudy; Indianapolis
14 fair; Kansas City 22 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 10 partly
cloudy; Nashville 21 fair; New Orleans 44 drizzle; St. Louis 19 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 28 fair; Anchorage 32 cloudy; Las Vegas 45
fair; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 50 fair; Salt Lake City 30 fair;
San Diego 53 fair; San Francisco 49 fair; Seattle 50 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal minus 7 fair; Toronto minus 3 fair.
</TEXT>
