<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Treason     12-12 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Treason,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prominent Union Leader Given Bail After 900 Days In Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unexpected move, a court
today granted bail to a prominent union leader and four other black
activists held for up to 30 months while on trial for treason.
   The Johannesburg Supreme Court granted bail to Moses Mayekiso,
head of the country's largest metalworkers union, and four
co-defendants charged with attempting a political takeover of
Alexandra, an inpoverished black township adjoining Johannesburg.
   Mayekiso was released on bail of 10,000 rand, or $4,200. The
others each paid $2,100. Four of the men, including Mayekiso, spent
more than 900 days in custody, while the fifth had been held almost
700 days.
   The case was adjourned last month and is to resume in February.
   The trial has attracted international attention due to Mayekiso's
position as general secretary of the National Union of Metalworkers
of South Africa and because many activists view the prosecution as
an attempt to stifle peaceful anti-apartheid activity.
   Conditions of bail bar the defendants from entering Alexandra,
addressing meetings or granting press interviews.
   The government alleges that the defendants organized rent and
consumer boycotts and sought to undermine the security forces in
1985 and 1986, the height of nationwide black unrest.
   Alexandra was one of the most militant townships at the time, and
dozens of people were killed in clashes with security forces.
   In several recent court cases, authorities have taken actions
designed to give the appearance of leniency toward anti-apartheid
activists.
   Last week, a judge in Pretoria sentenced four prominent activists
to prison terms of six to 12 years following their conviction on
treason in a three-year trial. Most observers expected the sentences
to be much harsher.
   In November, President P.W. Botha granted clemency to the
Sharpeville Six, a group of blacks convicted of murder in the mob
killing of a black township councilor. Their deaths sentences
provoked an international outcry, and Botha decided to give them
lengthy prison sentences instead.
   In the past two years, the government has sought to restore
control by detaining or restricting leaders of Mayekiso's Alexandra
Action Committee while undertaking a $38 million development program
in the township.
   Alexandra, wedged between affluent white suburbs, is one of the
country's most squalid urban townships. Many of the 120,000
residents lack electricity and toilets, and water comes from
communal taps.
</TEXT>
