<HEAD>Actor Castellano Dies Unexpectedly Of Heart Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH BERGEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Richard Castellano, nominated for
an Oscar and a Tony for his role in ``Lovers and Other Strangers,''
has died of heart failure. He was 55.
   Among his best-known roles were his portrayal of Mafia lieutenant
Clemenza in the film ``The Godfather'' and his part as co-star in
the television series ``The Super.''
   The New York City native, who died Saturday at his North Bergen,
N.J., home, gained an Academy Award nomination for best supporting
actor in 1970 for his role in the film ``Lovers and Other
Strangers.'' He was nominated for a Tony for the same role in the
theatrical version of the work in 1968.
   He also appeared on Broadway in Peter Weiss' ``The
Investigation,'' Frank Gilroy's ``That Summer, That Fall,'' and in
Art Buchwald's ``Sheep on the Runway.''
   A statement issued Sunday by his wife, actress and writer Ardell
Sheridan, 45, said the couple had been working on a book titled
``History of the Method,'' which chronicles the genesis of method
acting.
   ``It mas Mr. Castellano's dream to pass on his acting legacy to
aspiring actors, writers and directors in an easily understood and
applied formula,'' Mrs. Sheridan said.
   She said she planned to continue her husband's work.
   Castellano also is survived by his daughter, Margaret Castellano
Moller, his sister and an aunt.
   Funeral services are scheduled for Wednesday in North Bergen.
</TEXT>
