<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cocaine-Parents     12-12 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine-Parents,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Says Parents Taught Her To Use Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a teen-age girl were
arrested after she told authorities they taught her how to use
cocaine and how to cook it into the highly addictive drug ``crack.''
   Victor P. Hupman, 36, and his wife, Patricia, 34, were free on
bail Sunday. Their five children, ranging in age from 6 to 17, were
placed in the custody of grandparents.
   Hupman told authorities he figured his 17-year-old daughter,
Stephanie, would be exposed to cocaine and ``he wanted her to be
exposed to it at home,'' police Lt. Steve Gray said.
   The Hupmans were arrested after Stephanie told a school counselor
they had a drug problem and were openly using cocaine, police said.
The two were booked on four counts of furnishing cocaine to a minor
and released on $25,000 bail Saturday night.
   Miss Hupman told authorities she used cocaine four times, two of
those times in the form of crack, he said.
   The teen-ager said she saw her parents use cocaine for the first
time in the summer of 1986. Several months ago, she began asking
questions about the drug's effects and if she could try it, said
police officer Chris Lindholm.
   ``He said, `Here. Have some,''' Lindholm said about the father's
reaction.
   At first, Miss Hupman was disturbed by the police intervention
with the family, but state child abuse laws require school officials
to inform police when they receive such a report, Lindholm said.
   ``Her initial reasoning was not to throw them in jail or anything
but to get help for her or them,'' he said. ``She was worried the
family might crack up and her parents might die.''
   Hupman is a printer at Stanford University, and his wife works
there as a patient relations specialist.
   Mountain View is about 35 miles south of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
