<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Hampton     12-12 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hampton,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hampton Loses Bidding War, Buys Painting Anyway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz musician Lionel Hampton got into a bidding
war he didn't want _ and had to lose in order to win.
   Hampton, 74, was enjoying some jazz at a benefit art auction
given Sunday by the New York-based Arts and Entertainment Alliance.
   The Alliance was honoring six artists, including Hampton, the
late collage artist Romare Bearden and theatrical producer Vy
Higginsen.
   Hampton is a fan of Higginsen, whose ``Mama, I Want to Sing'' has
been billed as the longest running off-Broadway play produced by a
black.
   ``I was in her lobby and said she needs some pictures in here,''
Hampton recalled. So when the signature acrylic painting ``Piano
Man'' by Bearden protege Verna Hart came up for bid, Hampton was
ready.
   ``I'm going to get this picture for Vy,'' he thought.
   But Higginsen began bidding for ``Piano Man'' too. The price went
up and up, until Higginsen won at $2,500.
   Higginsen was elated at winning, but even more so a few minutes
later, when the auctioneer told her Hampton would pay for the
painting.
   ``That was the least I could do,'' Hampton said, adding that the
former magazine publisher had helped many black artists over the
years.
   ``I was absolutely thrilled. I was very interested in that
painting,'' Higginsen said.
</TEXT>
