<HEAD>Yugoslav Plane Crashes While Bringing Supplies to Armenia; Seven
Die</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts graf after 2nd with report pilot mistook highway for
runway. Pickup 3rd pvs, `The Soviet-built...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yugoslav military plane flying aid
to earthquake victims in Armenia crashed today while trying to land,
and all seven people on board were killed, the official Tanjug news
agency reported.
   The AN-12 cargo plane crashed about 10 miles from the airport at
Yerevan, the capital of Armenia, Tanjug said in a dispatch from
Moscow. It said the plane left the southern Yugoslav city of Skopje
late Sunday and that the crash occurred at 2:23 a.m. Moscow time.
   Local reporters said the pilot mistook a well-lit highway for a
runway.
   The Soviet-built aircraft crashed in front of a bridge and
practically fell into pieces, Tanjug said. There were no survivors,
the news agency reported. Seven crew members were said to be aboard.
   On Sunday, a Soviet plane carrying relief aid to the republic
crashed, and 78 people died.
   Tanjug said the Yugoslav plane was carrying medical equipment and
other supplies to Armenia, where at least 50,000 people were killed
and 500,000 left homeless by last Wednesday's earthquake.
   Tanjug said the cause of the crash was not known.
</TEXT>
