<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HighwayKillings     12-12 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway Killings,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Have Suspects as Sixth Body ID'd as Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hunters found the skeletal remains of a
sixth woman in woods near this old fishing port, and authorities
said they had developed a list of suspects in the slayings.
   Bristol County District Attorney Ronald Pina says at least five
murders were likely committed by the same killer or killers. At
least three victims were known to have ties to a seedy area known
for prostitution and drug sales.
   ``We have a list of potential suspects. There are people who are
known to do things like this and there are people who are giving us
some information,'' Pina said Sunday in a news conference at the
site where the sixth body was found.
   Nearby, police were still collecting parts of the badly
decomposed female body from a gravel pit in the wooded area near
Interstate 195.
   Douglas Ubelaker, an expert on forensics from the Smithsonian
Institution in Washington, D.C., was scheduled to perform an autopsy
today on the body.
   The skeletal remains, found Saturday afternoon, were the sixth
female body found since July in a six- to eight-mile square area
outside this town of 98,000 people in southeastern Massachusetts.
   The latest victim, who remained unidentified, could not
definitely be linked to the other five, Pina said. The woman was
``very similar'' to the others in that she was partially clad, he
said.
   The sixth body appeared to have been in the woods longer than any
of the others, possibly since spring, Pina said.
   ``This is the first one that wasn't found on the side of the
highway,'' State Trooper Thomas Medeiros said. ``But this one isn't
far from the highway.''
</TEXT>
