<DOCNO> AP881212-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0839EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Politics     12-12 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Politics,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor, Likud Tussle Over Guidelines For Joint Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Party and the Likud bloc renewed
negotiations today on forming a joint government, and officials said
a major point of conflict involved right-wing plans to build 40
Jewish settlements in the occupied territories.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of the right-wing Likud and Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres of the left-leaning Labor ordered talks
restarted Sunday night after a 10-day lull.
   The party chiefs set up three-member negotiating teams to
finalize a coalition agreement that would bring the country's two
largest political blocs back into a broad-based government.
   Israel radio said the two teams met in secret locations today and
focused on guidelines for a new government. The radio said there was
growing pressure for Peres to become finance minister, a less
prestigious post than his current position as foreign minister.
   The radio said the negotiators agreed to continue the 10-member
Inner Cabinet with equal representation from both parties. The body
decides major security and foreign policy issues.
   The liberal daily Haaretz said today the two parties have agreed
to set a timetable for dealing with electoral reform, which appeared
aimed at reducing the influence of small religious parties that
currently hold the balance of power.
   Shamir has been trying to forge a government since Likud won a
slight edge over Labor, 40 seats to 39, in the Nov. 1 election for
the 120-member parliament.
   In an apparent effort to avoid making concessions on religious
and political issues _ some of which deeply angered American Jews _
Shamir turned back to Labor after appearing close to an agreement
with small religious and nationalist parties.
   Likud's talks with the small parties continue, however, and
officials close to Shamir did not rule out the small parties joining
whatever government is formed.
   Yossi Ahimeir, a Shamir adviser, expressed the hope that talks
with Labor could be wrapped up in two or three days. But a Peres
aide who demanded anonymity predicted negotiations would go down to
the Dec. 26 deadline, when Shamir must present a new government.
   Ahimeir said the policy guidelines should be substantially the
same as those laid down for the current coalition government, which
was formed after stalemated elections in 1984.
   ``Some adjustments and additions are needed. For example, we
insist that more emphasis be given to building new Jewish villages
(in the West Bank and Gaza) as economic conditions allow,'' he said.
   However, Ahimeir said Shamir did not favor unlimited settlement
building. He indicated that if Labor joined the government, Likud
would not be obligated to carry out an agreement with Tehiya, a
pro-settlement party, to build 40 new settlements.
   An official close to Peres said Likud would have to break its
agreement with Tehiya. ``If Likud doesn't break the promise, there
is no way Labor can enter,'' he said.
   There are more than 130 Jewish settlements with about 70,000 Jews
living in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, occupied by Israel in the
1967 Middle East war. They are surrounded by 1.5 million
Palestinians.
   Ahimeir said Likud wanted to preserve existing policy guidelines
on the peace issue. Shamir demands direct talks between Israel and
the Arabs, whereas Peres supports an international conference as an
opening for those talks.
   An official close to Peres indicated one way to bridge the gap
might be to propose talks under joint Soviet-American sponsorship.
   ``The attitude towards the Soviets is different today, so maybe
this will help,'' he said.
   Shamir also will insist that any new policy initiatives be
cleared in advance with the prime minister. But Israeli newspapers
indicated Labor wanted freedom of maneuver to explore peace options
and other political policy issues.
   Labor officials indicated they would insist on the right to vote
against religious legislation such as the so-called ``who is a Jew''
bill, which proposes giving Israel's Orthodox rabbinate final say
over the sensitive issue of conversions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
