<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Walesa     12-12 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Walesa,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Says Poland Should Hasten Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said today his
outlawed trade union is ready for talks on reforming the Polish
system and strikes should be a last resort.
   The Nobel Peace Prize winner spoke before returning home from his
first trip abroad since martial law was imposed in Poland in 1981.
By allowing him to travel, authorities gave implicit recognition of
Walesa's importance as a public figure.
   President Francois Mitterrand invited Walesa to attend ceremonies
Saturday marking the 40th anniversary of the Universal Declaration
of Human Rights.
   ``There is a (reform) process that we want to speed up and the
fact that we are here is evidence of a quickening,'' said Walesa.
   On Nov. 30, Walesa debated the chief of Poland's communist-backed
official union in a live broadcast on national television. The
uncensored debate was the first time since 1983 that the Solidarity
leader has appeared on Polish television.
   Walesa said the Polish ``system is moving in a good direction.
But it is going by foot while the rest of the world is going by car.
It is necessary to accelerate the process.''
   ``Poland needs peace and pluralism. There is a place for both
(Prime Minister Mieczyslaw) Rakowski and Solidarity,'' he said.
   Walesa said he continued to favor negotiations to include the
government, church and opposition.
   The government offered to hold the talks following two waves of
strikes this year. But the talks reached an impasse after the
government refused to legalize the banned union and Solidarity
demanded a signal the government would consider the legalization
before it would enter talks.
   He said the discussion was still necessary. ``My union has wanted
it for a long time. But we should be considered free and
independent. Under this condition we are ready right away,'' he said.
   ``Poland doesn't need any more strikes now, because strikes are a
last resort,'' Walesa said.
   He said the union ``should struggle to get the most we can for
ourselves. But we also should remember to behave like good
microorganisms and not destroy the system that we live in.''
   During his visit, the smiling and ebullient Walesa met Soviet
dissident physicist Andrei Sakharov for the first time.
   The men, both Nobel laureates and leading dissidents, exchanged
impressions of the fight for human rights in Poland and the Soviet
Union. Walesa said today he hoped to maintain contact with Sakharov.
   ``He's a great thinker and a great, great man. But I don't know
what the possibilities will be for keeping in touch.''
   Solidarity adviser Bronsilaw Gemerek said Walesa earlier in the
day was at the departure of a truck loaded with supplies for victims
of the Armenian earthquake. He said Walesa sent a letter on the
truck to Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev ``to express his
Solidarity with the Soviet people.''
</TEXT>
