<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WhiteSupremacists     12-12 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-White Supremacists,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quiet End To Weekend Gathering By White Supremacists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Language in 9th graf, `Those arriving ...,' may offend some
readers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FREELAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quiet candlelight vigil by ``skinheads''
capped a day of demonstration and counterdemonstration by white
supremacists and those who oppose their racist beliefs.
   The vigil Saturday night at South Whidbey State Park marked the
slaying four years ago of white supremacist Robert J. Mathews. The
31-year-old founder of The Order died in a shootout with FBI
officers at a cabin near the park.
   Earlier Saturday, about 225 people chanted slogans and waved
signs in a parking lot in this Whidbey Island town, about 60 miles
northwest of Seattle. State police troopers and sheriff's deputies
kept the two groups apart, and there were no violent incidents or
arrests.
   A 17-year-old youth wearing a swastika button who wandered up to
the crowd was surrounded by 30-40 people, who shouted ``Scum go
home.'' Officers and protest organizers cooled things down, and the
youth was escorted away by a park ranger.
   The counterdemonstrators included union members, civil rights
activists, students, gay-rights activists and members of the Seattle
chapter of the Guardian Angels.
   They shouted slogans like ``We beat the fear by being here'' and
``Hey hey, ho ho, Nazi bigots got to go.''
   The Rev. Richard Butler, head of the Church of Jesus Christ
Christian (Aryan Nations), arrived shortly after most of the
counterdemonstrators left, followed shortly by Tom Metzger, founder
of White Aryan Resistance, based in Fallbrook, Calif.
   The vigil was organized largely by Metzger's son, John Metzger,
leader of White Aryan Resistance Youth.
   Those arriving for the vigil gave Nazi-like salutes, called
reporters ``scumbags'' and ``leeches,'' and hurled profanities at a
photographer of Japanese ancestry.
   Karl Herler of San Francisco brought his daughters, Kristina, 12,
and Eva, 10, for the memorial service.
   ``The skinheads, who everybody has this nightmare image of, it's
incredible how intelligent and knowledgeable they are, compared with
most people their age,'' he said.
   His younger daughter said she hoped to become a skinhead when she
got older, although women are not accepted as full-fledged members
of the movement.
   Skinheads, generally young, favor close-cropped hair,
military-style clothing and tattoos. Many are associated with the
white supremacist Aryan Youth Movement and White Aryan Resistance,
and have adopted Nazi beliefs.
   ``I'd die for my beliefs, so the least I could do is cut my
hair,'' Eva Herler said.
   About 60 people attended the vigil, said Jim Collins, state parks
assistant regional supervisor. He said law enforcement officers were
present but did not approach the group's campsite, and reporters and
others were kept away.
   After Mathews' death, 22 Order members were indicted on
racketeering charges stemming from murders, arson, counterfeiting
and armed robberies that netted more than $4 million to finance
their operations, authorities said.
   Ten were convicted in December 1985, and 12 others pleaded
guilty. Many were former members of Aryan Nations.
</TEXT>
