<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Tenure     12-12 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Tenure,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Study University Tenure Issue in University of
Pennsylvania Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case capturing the
attention of some leading universities, agreed today to study a
university's attempt to withhold confidential information from a
faculty member who says her denial of tenure was due to illegal
discrimination.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by University of
Pennsylvania officials accused of discriminating against a Chinese
woman denied promotion to full professor.
   But the justices indicated that they will be studying a very
narrow issue in the case _ one dealing with which trial court had
the authority to hear it.
   The university's appeal was supported by Princeton, Brown,
Stanford, Harvard and Yale. Lawyers for the other schools said that
forcing universities to reveal confidential statements about those
being considered for professorships will inhibit candor by those who
evaluate tenure candidates.
   The case began with a complaint by Rosalie Tung, an associate
professor of management at Penn, after she was denied tenure at the
university's Wharton School.
   Tenure is a lifetime appointment to the faculty.
   Ms. Tung filed a complaint with the federal Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission charging she was the victim of discrimination
against women and people of Asian race.
   The commission subpoenaed the university's confidential peer
review records for Ms. Tung and five other male candidates
considered for tenure.
   The university refused to provide the documents. It said
confidentiality is vital to the tenure review process, which in turn
is ``a critical component'' of the university's academic freedom
protected by the Constitution.
   University officials supported a balancing test, approved by
other federal appeals courts, that would allow the school to keep
the information secret unless it is shown to be essential to the
claim being made by the teacher denied tenure.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last June that the
university must not be allowed to shield possible discrimination
behind ``a wall of secrecy.''
   The appeals court said relevant information may not be concealed
from the commission. But the appeals court ordered further trial
court hearings to determine whether the university may be allowed to
delete from the peer review reports the names of professors who
evaluate tenure candidates.
   The Reagan administration urged the Supreme Court to allow the
appeals court ruling to stand.
   Justice Department lawyers noted that the high court in 1986
declined to review the issue in a similar case. They said there is
no more reason now for the court to enter the dispute.
   The case is University of Pennsylvania vs. EEOC, 88-493.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
