<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AbortionBan     12-12 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Ban,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clinics Swamped As Abortion Ban Goes Into Effect Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors and nurses worked double shifts over the
weekend as hundreds of poor women had abortions before a new state
ban on Medicaid funding for the procedure took effect today.
   It will be some time before the effect of the ban can be
evaluated, but some clinic operators say the measure, approved by
Michigan voters in the Nov. 8 election, won't decrease the number of
poor women having abortions.
   ``A lot of pro-lifers say this is going to hurt us, but I don't
think it will,'' said Dave Williams, a spokesman for Women's Health
Services of Detroit. ``I've had women tell me they've sold crack
(cocaine) to get the money. ... If they know they want to terminate
it, they'll get the money.''
   At Womancare clinics, which perform most of the Medicaid-funded
abortions in the state, doctors and nurses worked double shifts to
perform the operation during the weekend, owner Dr. Abraham Hodari
said.
   The clinics were prepared to perform 120 abortions Friday and
Saturday, about 50 percent more than the normal two-day total, he
said.
   Kim Evans, a woman answering calls at a Womancare office today,
was unable to say how many abortions were actually performed.
   Hodari said with the ban in effect, he would perform abortions
for $50 for Medicaid recipients.
   ``During the years I did this on Medicaid, I saved a lot of
money,'' he said. ``Now I want to help people with it.''
   Proponents of the ban said the state spent $6 million on Medicaid
abortions last year for about 18,000 poor women.
   Some forecasts show the state now will have to pay between $10
million and $50 million because of more Medicaid births and children
born into poverty, State Medicaid Director Kevin Seitz said.
   In states where Medicaid-funded abortions have ended, such as
Ohio and Georgia, studies show about 20 percent of Medicaid-eligible
women who carried pregnancies to term would probably have had
abortions had they been free.
   The cost to taxpayers for a Medicaid abortion averages $318 in
Michigan, state Medicaid administrator Esther Reagan said. The cost
for a Medicaid recipient who delivers a baby averages $3,100 for
health care and hospitalization.
   A 19-year-old who had an abortion Friday at the Womancare clinic
in Southfield said she would have terminated her pregnancy even
without Medicaid financing.
   ``I'd have found the money somewhere,'' said the woman, who
identified herself only as Lisa. ``I don't know where, though.''
</TEXT>
