<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1028EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Garbage     12-12 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Garbage,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules on Garbage-Privacy Issue in Nebraska Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, already having ruled that
privacy rights do not extend to garbage left at curbside for
pick-up, today refused to treat differently garbage discarded closer
to home.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a
convicted Fremont, Neb., man had no privacy right in garbage cans
left outside for collection four feet from his home's back door.
   Unlike the court's decision last May in a case from California,
today's order sets no national precedent.
   But it defeats Randall Trahan's challenge to his conviction for
possession of cocaine and gambling records and for promoting
gambling.
   Fremont police and Dodge County Sheriff's deputies, without
obtaining a court warrant, searched through the contents of garbage
left outside Trahan's trailer home and outside the tavern he and his
roommate owned.
   They found ``bet sheets'' used by bookmakers.
   Police previously had been tipped that Trahan was involved in
bookmaking.
   After obtaining a search warrant, law enforcement officers raided
Trahan's home. They found gambling materials and some cocaine inside.
   Trahan was sentenced to three years probation.
   The Nebraska Supreme Court upheld Trahan's conviction and
sentence last Sept. 2, rejecting arguments that the warrantless
search of the garbage left for collection on his property violated
his privacy rights.
   The nation's highest court voted 6-2 last May 16 in ruling that
police do not need a warrant before sifting through garbage left in
plastic bags at curbside.
   ``It is common knowledge that plastic garbage bags left on or at
the side of a public street are readily accessible to animals,
children, scavengers, snoops or other members of the public,''
Justice Byron R. White wrote for the court then.
   ``The police cannot reasonably be expected to avert their eyes
from evidence of criminal activity that could have been observed by
any member of the public,'' he said.
   The Nebraska court said Trahan's challenge must fail in light of
the May decision.
   ``Garbage left for collection at a designated location and
accessible to the public shall not be accorded constitutional
protection'' whether it is on or off someone's private property, the
state court ruled.
   The case is Trahan vs. Nebraska, 88-697.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1032EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ThanksgivingCharity     12-12 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thanksgiving Charity,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Questions Raised About Charitable Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose annual Thanksgiving-eve dinners
for the elderly have attracted thousands of dollars in donations and
praise from President Reagan has been ordered by the state to halt
fund-raising.
   And The Philadelphia Inquirer reported Sunday that a detailed
examination raises questions about most aspects of her operation,
including her claims to feeding thousands, her record-keeping and
fund-raising.
   Minnie Bolds Moore has claimed to feed up to 25,000 people each
year. Far fewer than that showed up this year, and while she said
her charity was deep in debt, much of the food was donated.
   Moore gave inconsistent and sometimes contradictory answers while
defending the charity she heads, Concerned Parents Inc., its records
and the scope of the operation, the newspaper reported.
   Moore did not return phone messages left by The Associated Press.
   Moore was unable to say how much Concerned Parents Inc. has
raised or spent in recent years. She has kept no ledger. She has no
checking account. She makes most of her purchases with cash, she
told the newspaper.
   ``I'm just terrible with record-keeping and stuff like that,''
she explained, adding that she runs essentially a one-woman
operation.
   Concerned Parents Inc. has failed to file annual reports required
by state law and pay its $10 registration fee since 1986, according
to the Commission on Charitable Organizations, which regulates
charities' fund-raising.
   In March the commission ordered Concerned Parents to halt
fund-raising until it filed updated reports and renewed its
registration to operate as a charity.
   Moore told the Inquirer she complied with the letter almost
immediately, but commission officials said they have no reply from
Moore on file.
   Moore, 47, says her annual Thanksgiving-eve dinners began
modestly in 1968, when she invited elderly neighbors to share
Thanksgiving dinner with her family.
   It has gotten more publicity as it has grown. Publicity helped
the charity raise thousands of dollars from hundreds of givers _
Moore has two index-card file boxes filled with their names and
addresses. President Reagan has written a letter of praise.
   In interviews, Moore always stresses the financial and logistical
burden of feeding 25,000 people a dinner that includes turkey, ham,
roast beef, macaroni salad, sweet potatoes, collard greens and baked
beans.
   This year, as in the past, she said her menu would include 500
turkeys, 200 hams and 400 ``steamship rounds'' of roast beef.
   In fact, no turkey was served at the dinner _ although there were
450 chickens. There were only nine canned hams and a dozen rounds of
roast beef, according to a check of the kitchen that day at the
Civic Center site of the dinner and interviews with Army cooks who
volunteered to prepare the meal.
   There was still more than enough food because far fewer than
25,000 showed up for the dinner.
   In an interview the day of the dinner, Moore said she had raised
about $23,000 for this year's meal, but was $70,000 in debt. She
used identical figures in interviews before the 1987 dinner.
   Much of the food served this year was donated, according to local
corporations and Moore.
   ``The money that we have raised has never covered the cost of the
meal,'' Moore said. ``When we were doing it on our own, we were
always in the hole doing it. And we've been in the hole ever since.''
   Moore has two criminal convictions: one in 1968 for passing
worthless checks; another in 1979 for her part in a scheme to steal
$158,000 in emergency checks from the state Public Welfare
Department.
   She insisted that she got into trouble while trying to help
others.
   ``I have never done anything to benefit myself personally. When
they investigated it ... they found it was done to help others,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
