<DOCNO> AP881212-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1033EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Opera     12-12 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Opera,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Director Quits Royal Opera House In Wagner Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yuri Lyubimov, the maverick Soviet-born theater
director, has left the Royal Opera House after a dispute over his
staging of Richard Wagner's ``The Ring of the Nibelungs.''
   Jeremy Isaacs, general director of the opera house in London's
Covent Garden, said Sunday that the 70-year-old Russian had been
released from his contract.
   Isaacs said Lyubimov was leaving after ``intellectual differences
in artistic interpretation'' with the Royal Opera's Dutch-born music
director, Bernard Haitink. The collaboration could only have
proceeded if there was ``absolute confidence between them,'' Isaacs
said.
   ``The Ring'' is a German myth about power struggles among ancient
gods over a hoard of gold, and discord over how to present the work
is nothing new in the operatic world.
   Haitink, who doesn't like displays of temperament, clashed with
Lyubimov over the director's emotive staging ideas and dislike of
detailed advance planning.
   Lyubimov and Haitink argued interminably during rehearsals
earlier this year over the staging of the first part of the cycle,
``The Rhine Gold.''
   The opera opened Sept. 29 to general acclaim from critics and
public and every seat was sold for the six performances.
   But the crunch came over how ``The Valkyrie,'' the second part of
the four-opera ``Ring'' cycle, should be presented next year.
   ``They had very different ideas ... and despite making every
effort, no consensus could be reached,'' said an opera house
official who asked not to be identified.
   ``That's not uncommon with `The Ring,' which is the most
demanding work in the whole of opera. There have been many
resignations over it in many opera houses in the past,'' the
official added.
   Isaacs told a reporter: ``I regret this parting of the ways since
I admire Yuri Lyubimov's work very much. But I am sure this decision
is for the best.''
   Lybimov will be replaced by a German director, Goetz Friedrich,
58, said Isaacs. Friedrich staged the ``The Ring'' at Covent Garden
in 1974-1976. He works for the Deutsche Oper, based in the West
German cities of Duesseldorf and Duisburg.
   Haitink, 59, had chosen Lyubimov to produce the cycle over a
four-year period. ``The Valkyrie'' is scheduled for September 1989,
followed by ``Siegfried'' and ``The Twilight of the Gods'' in the
1990-91 season.
   Lyubimov scored a hit at the Royal Opera in 1986 with an
innovative staging of the Czechoslovak opera ``Jenufa,'' by Leos
Janacek. He is to stage William Shakespeare's ``Hamlet'' in 1989 in
Leicester.
   Lyubimov made his name at Moscow's avant-garde Taganka Theater,
which he founded. His productions often ran into trouble with
Communist Party officials. In 1983, Lyubimov went to London to stage
Fyodor Dostoyevsky's ``Crime and Punishment'' and extended his stay,
demanding assurances he would be allowed artistic freedom in the
Soviet Union. But in 1984 he was fired from his job and expelled
from the Communist Party. Four months later, he was stripped of his
citizenship.
   Lyubimov later became an Israeli citizen. In May, he visited
Moscow and was given an ovation when he saw a performance at the
Taganka of his play about a rebel Soviet poet and singer. He is to
return to Moscow in January to direct two plays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
