<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Sprague 1stLd-Writethru a0559 12-12 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Sprague, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0559,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Reinstate Libel Award Against Philadelphia
Inquirer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 6-7, The second, to CORRECT spelling of homicide</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate a
$4.5 million libel award won by a former prosecutor against the
Philadelphia Inquirer.
   The justices, citing the lack of ``a properly presented federal
question,'' let stand a Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruling that
requires a new trial for Richard Sprague's lawsuit against the
newspaper.
   Sprague, now a Philadelphia lawyer in private practice, formerly
served as an assistant district attorney in that city.
   He sued the Inquirer and several of its reporters and editors 15
years ago over two series of articles published in late March and
early April of 1973.
   The first series of articles indicated that Sprague had
participated in an illegal wiretapping scheme.
   The second series reported that Sprague, at a time when he headed
the district attorney office's homocide division, had prevented the
bringing of homicide charges against the son of a Pennsylvania State
Police official. The series implied that Sprague's treatment of the
case was motivated by personal favoritism.
   At trial, reporter Kent Pollock testified that information for
one of the articles about the homicide case came from a confidential
source. He refused to identify the source when Sprague's lawyers
demanded he do so.
   The trial judge, noting that Pollock was legally entitled to
withhold the name under Pennsylvania's ``shield law,'' told jurors
they should not consider any evidence derived from such sources.
   The state's shield law, similar to those in many states, says no
one connected with a news-gathering organization can be forced to
disclose confidential sources to any court or government
investigation.
   The jury ruled for Sprague, awarding him $1.5 million in
compensatory damages and $3 million in punitive damages.
   A state appeals court threw out the award and ordered a new
trial, and the Pennsylvania Supreme Court upheld that ruling last
May 31.
   ``The reporter's information is properly admitted and no adverse
inference may be drawn from the invocation of the shield law,'' the
state court said.
   It said jurors should be told that invocation of the shield law
``does not establish an affirmative inference either as to the
reliability of the source or as to the validity of the information
received.''
   Plaintiffs and defendants are free to offer evidence or arguments
about reliability and validity, the state court said.
   The state Supreme Court concluded, ``If the shield law is invoked
by the defendant to avoid disclosing a source, no inference either
favorable or adverse may be drawn ... as to the reliability of the
unidentified source or as to the accuracy of the information
supplied.''
   The case is Sprague vs. Walter, 88-671.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
