<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Contractors     12-12 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Contractors,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal in Death of Marine in Virginia Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case it previously used
to give military contractors sweeping immunity from being sued,
today rejected an appeal by a family seeking damages for the death
of a Marine helicopter co-pilot.
   The court, without comment, refused to order a new trial in a
lawsuit stemming from a 1983 helicopter crash in the Atlantic Ocean
near Virginia Beach, Va.
   A federal jury in 1985 ordered helicopter manufacturer Sikorsky
Aircraft to pay $725,000 to the family of David Boyle, who drowned
April 27, 1983, when his CH-53 helicopter crashed.
   Boyle and the three other crew members survived the crash impact.
The three others escaped through emergency hatches, but Boyle was
unable to open his hatch against the pressure of the water.
   His family said the design was defective, arguing the hatch
should have opened inward to permit escape.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in May 1986 threw out the
jury award against Sikorsky and its parent company, United
Technologies Corp.
   The Supreme Court, in an important 5-4 ruling last June,
substantially upheld the appeals court decision. The high court said
a military contractor is protected from suit when it makes equipment
conforming to ``reasonably precise'' Pentagon specifications and the
company warns the government about any potential dangers of which
the company is aware.
   But the justices sent the case back to the 4th Circuit court to
determine whether the appeals court improperly acted as a trial
court and decided factual issues.
   The 4th Circuit court said in August it did not usurp the jury's
function.
   ``No reasonable jury could have found for (the Boyle family) on
the facts presented,'' the appeals court said. ``It is clear in this
case that the military contractor defense was established as a
matter of law.''
   In its latest appeal to the Supreme Court, the Boyle family
argued there are factual issues that should be submitted to a jury.
The family said, for example, there is a question whether the
government actually approved Sikorsky's design and whether the
government's specifications for the escape hatch were reasonably
precise.
   The case is Boyle vs. United Technologies, 88-677.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
