<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Pollute     12-12 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Pollute,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Asks Administration Viet of Fine Against Maryland Paper Mill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today asked the Reagan
administration for its view of a fine of nearly $1 million against a
Maryland paper mill operator for failing to comply with a federal
clean water law's reporting requirements.
   The court said it wants to hear from Justice Department lawyers
before acting on a challenge to a key provision of the act
authorizing citizens and environmental groups to sue alleged
polluters.
   The court is not expected to say whether it will grant full
review to the case before hearing from the administration, which
could take months.
   Simkins Industries Inc. runs a paper mill in Catonsville, Md., on
the banks of the Patapsco River.
   The Sierra Club sued the company for failing to monitor and file
quarterly reports on discharges into the river from Aug. 1, 1981, to
March 31, 1984.
   Under the federal Clean Water Act, the company's permit to
operate the mill required it to monitor discharges and report them.
   Simkins faced fines of up to $10,000 a day, or a total of $9.77
million. A federal judge assessed penalties of one-tenth that
amount, $977,000, payable to the U.S. Treasury.
   There was testimony that the company's plant supervisor did not
regard sampling of its discharges as a priority.
   The Sierra Club, based in California with members nationwide,
charged that Simkins had discharged copper into the Patapso at
10,000 times the safe levels for fresh water, and that oil and
grease in the river from the mill were twice the allowable limit.
   The company said the Sierra Club did not have the legal authority
to sue it because the club suffered no direct injury, and also that
the suit should be dismissed because it was filed after Simkins
stopped violating the law's reporting requirements.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last May upheld the fine.
   The appeals court said the Sierra Club established that at least
one of its members who uses the Patapsco River for recreation was
injured by Simkins' violations.
   Fines for failure to monitor and report possible pollution ``can
be an important deterrence against future violations,'' the appeals
court added.
   The appeals court, citing a 1987 Supreme Court decision, said
such private citizen suits under the clean water law may not be
``based upon wholly past violations.''
   The appeals court added that Simkins was violating the law at the
time the suit was filed in late 1984. The company did not file a
complete quarterly report until January 1985, nearly three months
after the Sierra Club filed suit.
   ``It is true that Simkins' failure to sample occurred solely
before Sierra Club filed suit,'' the appeals court said. ``But
Simkins' monitoring obgligations were not designed to be a mere
academic exercise.''
   ``Unless a permit holder monitors as required, it will be
difficult if not impossible for state and federal officials...to
know whether or not the permit holder is discharging effluents in
excess of the permit's maximum levels.''
   The appeals court also noted that Simkins began monitoring its
discharges after it was alerted by the Sierra Club that it was about
to be sued.
   The case is Simkins vs. Sierra Club, 88-660.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0083 </DOCNO>
