<2ND_LINE>PM-Meteor Shower, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0523,130</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lede to note that meteors visible worldwide</NOTE>
<HEAD>Meteor Shower Coming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shooting stars will brighten skies around the
world tonight and tomorrow night, offering viewers plenty of chance
to make a wish in areas with clear skies.
   The Geminid Meteor Shower is one of the year's most spectacular
examples of shooting stars, according to the U.S. Naval Observatory,
with the best show coming in the hours after midnight on Tuesday and
Wednesday mornings.
   Up to 50 meteors per hour will be visible if skies are clear,
according to the Smithsonian Institution.
   Meteors are caused when tiny chunks of space debris, usually no
larger than a grain of sand, enter the Earth's atmosphere and burn
up. This shower is caused by bits of an extinct comet and will be
visible all over the sky.
</TEXT>
