<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--Medals-Survivors     12-12 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Medals-Survivors,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>16 Filipino Survivors of Bataan Death March Get Medals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen Filipinos who survived the
infamous Bataan Death March while serving in the U.S. Army during
World War II have been awarded medals 46 years after their ordeal.
   Army Maj. Gen. Theodore W. Paulson recognized the veterans'
sacrifice at a ceremony Sunday featuring a flyover by five World War
II vintage aircraft.
   The 16 honorees, many infirm with age, received the Bronze Star
and Prisoner of War medals for their internment by the Japanese
following the 65-mile forced march blamed for the death of 10,000
abused, ill and undernourished prisoners.
   The Japanese forced about 78,000 U.S. and Filipino soldiers to
make the five-day walk in strong tropical heat after surrendering
following heavy fighting in 1942.
   ``The brutality was incredible. I saw people decapitated for
falling behind,'' said march survivor and author Mariano Villarin.
   The veterans, who settled in Southern California after the war,
were honored with the medals after Congress recently passed a bill
recognizing them as U.S. servicemen and acknowledging the trials
they endured.
</TEXT>
