<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--CubanExiles     12-12 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cuban Exiles,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Third-Country' Cubans Arriving In Miami</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 ``third-country'' Cubans flew into
Miami over the weekend as part of a program to reunite
Cuban-Americans with relatives who have been stranded, sometimes for
years, in other countries.
   A jet carrying 183 Cubans who had been living in Spain arrived
Saturday, and 27 more arrived Sunday from Madrid. They are expected
to be joined by 370 more from Spain on Tuesday and Thursday.
   The exiles, sponsored by the Cuban American National Foundation,
were greeted with cheers as they arrived.
   Since the program began Sept. 11, 805 former Cubans have arrived
in the United States from Panama and Costa Rica.
   Under the program, relatives or friends of the refugees promise
to pay travel costs and provide financial support for two years. The
foundation can bring up to 1,500 refugees into the country this year.
