<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Switzerland-Kopp     12-12 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Switzerland-Kopp,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Resigns Over Advice To Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice Minister Elisabeth Kopp
announced today she is resigning because of controversy over a
telephone call in which she advised her husband to break with a
company accused in a drug money laundering scandal.
   The 52-year-old Kopp, first woman to join the federal executive,
only last Wednesday was elected vice president, a post that rotates
annually and would have made her eligible to become president in
1990.
   She announced she will step down as head of the Justice and
Police Ministry by the end of February because she has come under
``unbearable pressure.''
   ``I am not morally and legally guilty of any wrongdoing,'' she
said in a statement, adding that a brief Oct. 27 telephone
conversation with her husband had gained ``disproportionate
importance.''
   In the telephone call, she disclosed Friday, she warned her
husband, Hans W. Kopp, to give up his seat on the board of the
Lebanese-controlled Zurich-based Shakarchi Trading A.G.
   A few days later, prosecutors announced they had opened an
inquiry into a $1-billion money laundering operation and accused
Shakarchi of involvement. The company denies the charge.
   Kopp, who resigned from the board a week before news of the
inquiry broke, said he did so for personal reasons and that he had
no knowledge of any illegal activities by the company.
   Mrs. Kopp said she warned her husband after her personal
assistant told her privately of the suspicions about Shakarchi. She
maintained she had no official information and did not violate the
trust of her office.
   A public opinion poll three months ago named her the most popular
Cabinet member. But her revelation caused an uproar believed without
precedent in Switzerland. Even members of her own conservative
Radical Democratic Party urged Mrs. Kopp to step down.
   A government spokesman said President Otto Stich thanked Mrs.
Kopp for her work and said she continued to command the confidence
of her Cabinet colleagues.
   Government spokesman Achille Casanova quoted Interior Minister
Flavio Cotti as saying Mrs. Kopp did ``not resign because of the
case but because of the climate.''
</TEXT>
