<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-AgeSuit     12-12 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Age Suit,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Avoids Decision on Pennsylvania Age-Bias Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, avoiding a decision on an
important issue for all lawsuits alleging age bias in employment,
today dismissed the case of a laid-off Pennsylvania man.
   By an 8-1 vote, the justices said in effect that they had made a
mistake when agreeing to decide whether Eugene F. Brieck's lawsuit
against his former employer, Harbison-Walker Refractories, should
proceed to trial.
   The court's action was carried in a one-sentence, unsigned
decision dismissing the case as ``improvidently granted.'' Justice
Byron R. White dissented.
   The effect is to leave intact an appeals court victory for Brieck
that clears the way for further trial court proceedings in his case.
   Harbison-Walker, a division of Dresser Industries, sells
specialized ceramic brick products primarily to steel producers.
Brieck worked as an installation specialist for Harbison-Walker from
1965 to 1982.
   In July 1982, several employees of Harbison-Walker's Iron and
Steel Marketing Support Group were laid off, including Brieck. He
then was 55.
   Brieck sued in Pittsburgh in 1984, contending that he was laid
off and not recalled to work because of his age. His lawsuit pointed
to a 39-year-old installation specialist with less seniority who was
not laid off until November 1982 and then recalled eight months
later.
   Lawyers for Harbison-Walker contended that the other employee,
Hugh Faust, was retained because of his more diverse work experience.
   A federal judge threw out Brieck's suit, ruling that
Harbison-Walker had articulated legitimate, non-discriminatory
business reasons for laying off Brieck while retaining a younger man
with less seniority.
   But the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the suit
last year.
   The appeals court ruled that an employer charged with violating
the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act cannot avoid trial
by articulating legitimate business reasons if the suing employee
presents ``a reasonable inference that the employer's proffered
explanation ... is unworthy of credence.''
   The appeals court added: ``The question is not whether the
employer's asserted reason is plausible, but whether there is also
evidence of record which, if credited, could render the reason
implausible.''
   Lawyers for Harbison-Walker had argued in a session before the
justices Oct. 31 that the appeals court ruling would virtually
eliminate pretrial dismissals in employment discrimination cases.
   The case is Harbison-Walker vs. Brieck, 87-271.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
