<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan-President 1stLd-Writethru a0528 12-12 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-President, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Incumbent Elected President In Pakistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throuhgout with final vote count, Bhutto winning
confidence vote. Edits to conform. No pickup. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incumbent Ghulam Ishaq Khan easily won
a five-year term as Pakistan's president today and Prime Minister
Benazir Bhutto scored a victory in her first parliamentary vote of
confidence.
   Federal Election Commissioner S.A. Nusrat said on television that
Ishaq Khan swept 78 percent of the presidential vote.
   Of 446 valid votes, Ishaq Khan polled 348 compared with 91 to his
nearest rival, veteran politican Nawabzada Nasrullah Khan, Nusrat
said.
   Ms. Bhutto won her first test of strength in the National
Assembly, the country's lower house of parliament.
   Of 203 members voting on the confidence motion, 148 said ``yes''
and 55 said ``no.''
   Her Pakistan People's Party party emerged as the largest single
party Nov. 16 in the country's first free elections in more than a
decade. But with 105 seats, it fell short of an outright majority in
the 237-seat legislature. The party since gained support from
several independents and minor parties.
   The constitution dictates that the governing party pass a
parliamentary test of confidence within 60 days of forming a
government.
   The Senate, National Assembly and four provincial assemblies
functioned as an electoral college for the president.
   Provincial assemblies were restricted to 45 votes each to put
them on equal footing. The populous eastern Punjab assembly has 260
members, for example, compared to western Baluchistan's 45
legislators.
   Of the four presidential candidates, only Ishaq Khan, 73, of the
conservative Pakistan Muslim League, had the support both of Ms.
Bhutto's party and the right-wing opposition alliance, headed by the
Muslim League.
   Ishaq Khan has been credited with guiding Pakistan back to
democracy after 11 years of autocratic rule, eight of them under
martial law by President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   Zia died in an Aug. 17 plane crash investigators said was
probably caused by sabotage.
   Because he was Senate chairman, the presidency was passed to
Ishaq Khan, a venerable technocrat and constitutional scholar with
nearly 40 years' experience in senior administrative posts, six of
them as finance and commerce minister.
   Pakistan's president holds a largely ceremonial post, but the
roles of both president and prime minister are under debate here.
   A 1985 constitutional amendment authored by Zia gave the
president broad but vague discretionary powers.
   Ms. Bhutto has called for a repeal of that amendment, which would
restore supreme political powers to the prime minister as they
existed during her father's government of the 1970s.
   Zia ousted Ms. Bhutto's father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in 1977. He
had Bhutto executed two years later allegedly for plotting to
overthrow a political foe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
