<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LandryExecution     12-12 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Landry Execution,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Considering Appeal To Halt Early Tuesday Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man facing execution after midnight
for a 1982 robbery-murder sought a stay from the U.S. Supreme Court
today, while a second execution that had been scheduled for the same
time already was postponed.
   Raymond Landry, 39, faces lethal injection for the shooting death
of Houston restaurant owner Kosmas Prittis. Prittis, 33, a Greek
immigrant, was robbed of more than $2,300 and fatally shot in the
head.
   Last January, Landry came within three hours of execution before
the Supreme Court issued a stay in his case.
   Texas Attorney General Jim Mattox has labeled Landry the most
likely of the nine Texas death row inmates with execution dates to
be put to death.
   Landry's attorney, Michael Charlton, bypassed lower federal
courts and appealed directly to the high court.
   If his execution, scheduled for early Tuesday, goes ahead, Landry
would be the third inmate to be put to death in Texas this year and
the 29th _ more than any other state _ since the Supreme Court ruled
in 1976 that capital punishment in the United States could be
resumed.
   Another convicted killer, Samuel Hawkins, known as the
``traveling rapist,'' was granted a stay of execution from a federal
judge Friday. Hawkins had also faced execution early Tuesday.
</TEXT>
