<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Relief Planes Return After Taking Off For Armenia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to clarify circumstances of planes turning
back. Pick up 6th pvs, `The Israeli...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two air force planes loaded with supplies and
medical teams left for a city in earthquake-stricken Armenia today
but returned after an Israeli general there said their help would be
more useful elsewhere, officials said.
   Officials said Maj. Gen. Aharon Vardi, head of Israel's Civil
Defense, radioed the pilots that no additional medical assistance
was needed in Leninakan, the Soviet republic's second-largest city
which has been devastated by the quake.
   The U.S.-made Hercules transports had been sent to reinforce
Israeli experts who went to Leninakan on Sunday.
   A military spokesman said Vardi ordered the planes to return
because he decided ``they could not be used effectively at the
scene'' and would be more useful elsewhere, the spokesman said. He
said the planes were not turned back by the Soviet government.
   The Israeli participation in the rescue effort was seen as part
of a warming trend between Israel and the Soviet Union, which have
not had diplomatic relations since the Soviets cut ties after the
1967 Middle East War.
   On board the aircraft that left today were 46 doctors, medics,
vehicles, an electric generator, field hospital, blood and medicine,
the military said.
   Israel began sending aid to the Armenians on Sunday with a
planeload of supplies including cranes, medicines and a specially
trained rescue dog.
   As the planes took off today, Moscow's top diplomat in Tel Aviv
said this assistance would bring Israelis and Soviets closer.
   ``We are greatly moved by this,'' Georgy Martirosov, who heads
the Soviet consular delegation in Tel Aviv, said on Israel army
radio. ``This help by the Israeli people will bring us closer
emotionally.''
   The earthquake relief was the second time Israel has given
humanitarian aid to the Soviets this month and some officials have
said they hoped the Jewish state would reap diplomatic benefits.
   On Dec. 2, Israel allowed a hijacked Soviet jet to land at
Ben-Gurion International Airport near Tel Aviv and subsequently
granted a Soviet request by deporting the four hijackers.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze thanked Israel for
that help in an unprecedented meeting in Moscow with Israeli
consular representative, Aryeh Levine.
   Concerning the aid to Soviet Armenia, Foreign Ministry spokesman
Allon Liel said Sunday, ``we have no intention of building political
achievements on such tragic events. I must state, though, that the
atmosphere created following this and the hijack incident last week,
is a warm and friendly one.''
</TEXT>
