<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WilliamsTestimony     12-12 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Williams Testimony,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deposition Reveals Roy Williams' Impressions of Mob</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Teamsters leader Jimmy Hoffa
once warned his protege Roy Williams to go along with mob associates
who had infiltrated the union, according to a court deposition
obtained by a newspaper.
   ``They've infiltrated every big local, every conference, every
pension fund, and they're even into the AFL-CIO,'' Hoffa told
Williams in 1958. ``They're bad and I certainly think you should go
along with them. I'm tied as tight as I can be.''
   Williams' recollection of that conversation with Hoffa was part
of a federal court deposition, according to a story in Sunday's
editions of The Kansas City Star.
   During two days last week, Williams described his rise and fall
in the union, his relationship with the late Kansas City crime boss
Nick Civella, Hoffa and several of their Teamster and mob associates.
   The deposition will be used at the trial of a civil lawsuit
brought by the Justice Department in New York aimed at removing
Teamsters officials and mobsters who allegedly have corrupted the
union.
   Williams also said he had agreed to cooperate with the government
after he was sentenced to 10 years on the attempted bribery charge.
   He said his release from prison in September after serving about
three years was contingent upon his continued cooperation with the
authorities. He gave the deposition on the advice of his attorneys.
   Most of the questions asked by Randy Mastro, an assistant U.S.
attorney from the Southern District of New York, and other attorneys
participating in the deposition focused on Williams' association
with Civella and other organized crime leaders.
   Williams joined the Teamsters in 1938 and later, as a protege of
Hoffa, rose through the ranks as president of Local 41 in Kansas
City and finally became international president in 1981. Hoffa
disappeared in 1975 and has been presumed slain.
   Civella once told Williams that ``Kansas City was his territory
and that he had a working relation with other areas including
Milwaukee, Chicago, Cleveland and New Orleans.''
   He said he agreed with Civella's request to find work for some of
Civella's associates. He appointed George Chiavola, Civella's
nephew, as a Teamsters health and safety director, and Sam Ancona as
a general organizer. Both have been subjects of investigations by
police and federal agents.
   Williams said he met with Civella about once a month.
   Williams told the Star on Saturday, through one of his attorneys,
that he has not been threatened because of his testimony and that he
does not fear for his safety because of his disclosures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
