<DOCNO> AP881212-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1154EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-TrainSurvivors     12-12 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Train Survivors,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivor: Car Split Like a `Ripe Tomato'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Train Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One moment Chris Reeves was heading toward London's
Waterloo Station aboard a commuter train, and the next he was
scrambling through a rail car roof that had ``split open like a ripe
tomato.''
   ``We were sitting next to the aisle in the buffet and when the
crash happened we were thrown down the train,'' Reeves said today as
he awaited treatment for a head injury at St. George's Hospital.
``All I can remember is dust and debris as you've never experienced
it in your life.''
   Reeves, 38, of Southampton, was among more than 100 people
injured when a British Rail commuter train slammed into a stopped
train at Clapham Junction during this morning's rush hour and then a
freight train on an adjoining track rammed into the wreckage. Dozens
were killed.
   ``There was furniture and enormous lumps of metal flying
everywhere,'' Reeves said. ``You see pictures of things like this
but when you're in the middle of it, your life goes in front of your
eyes.
   ``The whole of the buffet car disintegrated,'' Reeves said. ``The
roof split open like a ripe tomato and that's how we got out. We
tried to find people underneath the rubble but there was so much
debris, there was nothing we could do.
   ``I think the woman who was in there was dead _ and there was a
man lying dead on the tracks we we got out,'' Reeves said.
   Ian Underhill, 41, of Farnborough, said there was ``a hell of a
bang'' as his train approached Clapham.
   ``The train seemed to shoot backwards and the guy opposite me
flew into my face,'' said Underhill, who also was taken to St.
George's. ``Amazingly enough, there was not a lot of panic. It was
fairly calm and people were helping one another to get out. I saw
one man helped out who had lost his foot and there were many others
with terrible injuries.''
   Bob Mintram, 37, of Bournemouth, received 20 stitches at the
scene for a head wound. ``It seemed to me, the coach I was on, half
(the people) were OK and half were bad news,'' he said. He said the
woman sitting next to him was killed.
   ``There was no panic. None whatsoever, no screaming,'' Mintram
said. ``We were out in 30 seconds. We climbed out through the roof.
There were no seats left. It was a rubbish heap.''
   David Crump, 40, from King's Somborne, was in the back car of the
train that hit the stopped commuter train.
   ``Surprisingly there was no panic whatsoever. I suppose we were
in the most fortunate part of the train. We had heard the bang and a
terrible screeching sound,'' Crump said at the crash scene.
   Alun Hughes, an ambulance worker, was in the same train.
   ``There was a school on the other side of the track and the
people there started taking in the injured. They reacted remarkably
quickly and efficiently,'' Hughes said. ``There was a doctor on the
train and we both rendered first aid where we could.''
   Keith Larner, 36, from Southampton, said he saw people with metal
in their bodies.
   ``A woman was trapped with metal which was in her chest and we
just started to get people out immediately,'' he said. ``It was the
most horrible sight I have ever seen.''
</TEXT>
