<DOCNO> AP881212-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1206EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OldestSynagogue     12-12 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oldest Synagogue,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Oldest Synagogue Celebrates 225th Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's oldest synagogue celebrated its
225th anniversary by expressing gratitude for the religious freedom
it has enjoyed.
   ``We have been a symbol (of religious tolerance) for both the
Jewish world and the gentile community,'' Rabbi Chaim Shapiro said
Sunday.
   Almost 300 people of differing faiths crammed into the Touro
Synagogue for a traditional Friday night Sabbath service that was
seasoned with references to the holiday of Hanukkah.
   Hanukkah, which means dedication, commemorates the cleansing and
resanctification of the Temple in Jerusalem by the Maccabees
following their victory over the pagan Greco-Syrians in 165 B.C.
   The Maccabees' struggle, said temple President Bernard Kusinitz,
is ``the first recorded battle for religious freedom in history.''
   This year, he also noted, the dedication celebrated by the
holiday parallels the rededication of the landmark synagogue.
   Participants in the Sabbath service and various parties this
weekend felt ``a combination of pride and at the same time a certain
gratitude to the Jewish and gentile communities that welcomed us,''
Shapiro said.
   In 1759, 100 years after the first Jewish families sailed into
Newport, the community decided to build a synagogue.
   The congregants, who by this time numbered 35 families, hired
architect Peter Harrison.
   It is assumed that Harrison, a Quaker who had never seen a
synagogue, based his design on Isaac Abraham Touro's description of
his childhood synagogue in Amsterdam. Touro was the temple's cantor.
   ``There are enough similarities between the two that we feel they
have to be related,'' Kusinitz said.
   The brick building, which stands 95 percent intact, ``is a
mixture of Colonial architecture with traditional Jewish motifs,''
Shapiro said.
   ``As simple as it is on the outside, it is as beautiful on the
inside,'' Kusinitz said.
   In 1790, two years before the enactment of the Bill of Rights,
George Washington issued a letter from the synagogue promising the
new government of the United States would give ``to bigotry no
sanction, to persecution no assistance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
