<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1207EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BurningChurch     12-12 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burning Church,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People From Six States Gather at Arson-Plagued Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GODFREY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beside the graves of former slaves and the
work of a modern arsonist, people from six states proclaimed that
the burned New Bethel AME Church of Rocky Fork would once again
serve its tiny congregation.
   Frequently vandalized through the years, the church was rebuilt
after it was destroyed by arson in April, only to be torched again
in October. A suspect in the second fire is awaiting trial.
   ``It's like when you lose a loved one,'' said Frank Bennet of the
200 people who attended the gathering Saturday in this southern
Illinois town about 25 miles north of St. Louis. ``People come and
you didn't even know they cared.''
   Bennett, who lives in nearby Alton and is not a member of the
congregation, said he attended out of respect for those who lost
their church.
   Morris M. Ewing of Los Angeles heard about the rally while
attending a stamp collecting convention in Chicago. He stopped by on
his way home and wrote a check for $300.
   Ewing urged others in the audience not to become bitter about the
fires. ``It takes only one or two individuals to upset the
progress,'' he said.
   Last year, racial epithets were carved into the walls of the
church, which serves a predominantly black congregation, and
swastikas were spray-painted on the building.
   ``People feel that after the civil rights movement of the '60s
that racism died. It didn't. But if we work together, we can kill
it,'' said Dennis L. Roach of the Rainbow Coalition of St. Louis.
   The Rev. Steven A. Jackson, pastor of the 25-member congregation,
estimated that Saturday's donations would amount to $10,000 to
$12,000. Rebuilding the church is expected to cost about $65,000.
   The church in this town of 2,600 residents was founded in 1863.
Its yard is adorned with headstones, both recent and decades old. In
some cases only jagged hunks of rock mark the graves.
   Jackson said many of the former slaves who founded the church are
buried there.
   Authorities said James Russell Calvin, 19, of Alton confessed to
setting the October fire and is awaiting trial on one count of
arson. He has not been linked to the earlier blaze.
   Calvin, who is white, said he was not motivated by racism but by
rumors from friends that the building was used by devil worshipers.
</TEXT>
