<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Quake,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>White House Has Line Open to Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan White House is keeping a line open
to the Soviet Embassy to see what further assistance the United
States might provide to earthquake victims, White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said today.
   A day after President Reagan and his wife, Nancy, paid their
respects at the embassy here, Fitzwater said there have been so many
offers of help that the switchboard at the mission has been jammed.
For this reason, he said:
   ``We have lines open on a continuing basis to receive their needs
and find out what they're looking for. They're trying to define
better the need at this point.''
   Fitzwater said that the United States has spent roughly $825,000
to ferry experts and supplies to the ravaged region in Armenia. He
said that one Defense Department C-141 cargo plane had arrived there
and that a second was en route.
   The spokesman estimated that a total of about $2.47 million had
been raised through the weekend, through private means, to aid the
earthquake victims. An additional $3 million was raised during a Los
Angeles telethon Sunday.
   Fitzwater also estimated that roughly $22.9 million has been
collected through international means for assistance to the
earthquake region.
   ``The process at the moment is to continue what we have been
doing,'' he said, which for the most part involves helping to see to
it that donated food, medicine and other supplies get to the
stricken region.
</TEXT>
