<HEAD>Kennedy Named AP Business News Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James M. Kennedy, business enterprise editor for
The Associated Press, has been named head of the AP's national
business news department.
   Louis D. Boccardi, AP president, announced the appointment
Monday. As business news editor, Kennedy succeeds Michael W.
Millican in directing the news cooperative's national and
international coverage of business news.
   Kennedy, 35, was business editor of the Tampa (Fla.) Tribune
before joining the AP in March 1987. As business enterprise editor,
he has been responsible for working with AP's domestic and foreign
staff in developing aggressive coverage of business, economics and
finance.
   Kennedy is a native of Watertown, N.Y., and a graduate of Amherst
College. He began his journalism career at The Journal in
Ogdensburg, N.Y., where he became managing editor before moving to
Tampa.
   Millican left the AP to join a New York public relations firm.
