<1ST_LINE>u p PM-IndianaSenate 2ndLd-Writethru a0594 12-12 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indiana Senate, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0594,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indiana Governor to Name Rep. Coats to Quayle's Seat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 2nd graf to update with Quayle, Lugar
statement on Senate seat planned this afternoon.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle will be
replaced in the Senate by conservative Republican Rep. Dan Coats, a
former aide recently elected to a fifth term as an Indiana
congressman, a party source said today.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Indiana Gov.
Robert Orr would make a formal announcement of the appointment later
in the day.
   Quayle and Indiana's other senator, Republican Richard Lugar,
also were scheduled to make a statement on the subject this
afternoon, according to a Quayle spokesman who declined to divulge
any other information.
   Coats, 45, was elected in 1980 to fill the 4th Congressional
District seat Quayle vacated to run for the Senate. He worked in
Quayle's congressional office in Fort Wayne, Ind., from 1976 to
1980, and was known to have Quayle's backing in the jockeying to
pick a new senator for Indiana.
   In the House, Coats has compiled a staunchly conservative record.
His rating for 1986 from the American Conservative Union was 82
percent. His rating the same year from the liberal Americans for
Democratic Action was 10 percent.
   He is a supporter of aid to the Nicaraguan Contras and to the
Angolan rebels. In 1984, he attempted to attach an amendment to an
omnibus education bill that would have cut off federal aid to
schools and states banning voluntary school prayer. The amendment
was defeated.
   Calls to Coats' office were unreturned today. Orr brushed aside
questions as he attended a Christmas-tree trimming ceremony in the
Statehouse in Indianapolis, instead telling reporters to talk to
Santa Claus.
   Coats will serve as an appointed senator until a special election
is held in 1990 for the remaining two years of Quayle's term. An
election for a full six-year Senate term will be held in 1992.
   Coats' selection also means a special election will be held to
fill his House seat, probably in March.
   His selection will leave the total of Senate Republicans in the
incoming, 101st Congress at 45. The Democrats will be in the
majority with 55 seats.
   Quayle has announced his intention to resign from his Senate seat
by Jan. 2. That would permit Coats to be sworn in a day ahead of the
senators elected in November, thus gaining an advantage over the
rest of the class in seniority.
   Party sources said that in selecting Coats, Orr was hoping to
find a politician capable of building a strong political and
financial base to withstand a Democratic challenge for his seat in
either 1990 or 1992.
   Several other names had been mentioned as potential candidates
for Quayle's seat, including former White House political director
Mitchell Daniels, who is a political protege of Lugar. Daniels took
himself out of contention several weeks ago, as did Marilyn Quayle,
wife of the vice president-elect.
   Others who had meen mentioned as contenders included Rep. Dan
Burton, Indianapolis Mayor William Hudnut, Marion County Prosecutor
Stephen Goldsmith and Lt. Gov. John Mutz, who was defeated last
month in a bid for the governor's office.
   Orr was moving to fill the Senate vacancy before his own term
ends early next month, to prevent Indiana's incoming Democratic
governor, Evan Bayh, from naming a Democrat to the post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CoatsProfile     12-12 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coats Profile,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coats One of `Two Dans' in Northeast Indiana District</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Indiana Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Coats has made a career of following Dan
Quayle _ first as his aide, later as a congressman and now as the
vice president-elect's apparent successor in the U.S. Senate.
   ``We call them the two Dans because Dan Coats worked for him and
followed him to Congress,'' said Robert E. Gates, the 4th District
Republican chairman.
   Coats, 45, was expected to be formally named by Gov. Robert D.
Orr this afternoon to fill Quayle's Senate seat for the next two
years, according to a source in the Republican Party.
   Coats' rise to the Senate marks the second time in his career he
has filled a vacancy left by Quayle. In 1980, Coats, then Quayle's
district representative, won his first term in the U.S. House in the
same year his boss won the Senate seat.
   Although their careers have followed similar paths, the two men
are different in background and style, friends say.
   Coats was born in Jackson, Mich., graduated from Wheaton College
and then served in the Army. He received his law degree by attending
night classes at Indiana University in Indianapolis.
   Quayle, a native Hoosier, also attended the Indianapolis law
school while serving in the National Guard during the Vietnam War.
   Four years older than Quayle, Coats joined Quayle's staff in 1976
after working as an assistant vice president and legal counsel for
Mutual Security Life Insurance Co.
   In contrast to Quayle, an exuberant campaigner, Coats is ``very
low-key,'' said former Secretary of State Edwin J. Simcox, who went
to law school with Coats.
   Simcox, who had been in the running for Quayle's seat, said of
Coats: ``I think a great deal of him. He's an outstanding person.''
   Gates called Coats, a Fort Wayne resident, especially attentive
to his constituents' wishes.
   ``He's not ultra-conservative. He really studies what the people
want and votes that way. He takes a lot of surveys,'' said Gates.
``He really cares for his people.''
   That attentiveness has translated into significant vote-getting
appeal, the party official noted.
   In fact, Coats has never received less than 61 percent of the
vote in the northeastern Indiana district.
   On Nov. 8, he won 62 percent of the vote in defeating Jill L.
Long, a Democrat who lost to Quayle in the 1986 Senate race.
</TEXT>
