<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TreasureShip     12-12 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasure Ship,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Grants Treasure Hunter Right to Salvage Pirate Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Massachusetts Supreme Court ruled today that a
treasure hunter has the right to recover cargo and artifacts from
the submerged 18th century pirate ship ``Whydah.''
   In a unanimous opinion, Massachusetts' highest court rejected the
state's claim of sovereignty over the wrecked wooden sailing vessel,
lying beneath the sand in the waters off Wellfleet on Cape Cod where
the it foundered in April 1717.
   ``The ill-fated Whydah, nearly three centuries later, has sailed
into this court's jurisdiction as the subject of a dispute between
contemporary treasure seekers and the would-be modern sovereign of
the coastal waters,'' Justice Neil Lynch wrote for the high court.
   He described the case as ``a conflict mired in competing claims
of title to the shipwreck and its cargo, involving issues of federal
maritime and admiralty law, and disputed dominion over submerged
lands in the marginal sea.''
   In November 1982, Barry Clifford and his salvage company,
Maritime Underwater Surveys Inc., found ``an unidentified, wrecked
and abandoned vessel'' one mile off Wellfleet under about 14 feet of
water and 5 feet of sand.
   Since 1983, Maritime Surveys, using sophisticated sensing and
recovery technology, has recovered numerous artifacts from the site,
while waging legal battles with the state, the federal government
and rival treasure hunters over who owns the wreck of the
commandeered English merchant ship.
   Gold, silver, cannons and pistols recovered from the ship have
been valued at $14 million to $25 million, and the total bounty is
estimated in the hundreds of millions of dollars.
   After winning his claim of ownership to the Whydah in U.S.
District Court, Clifford was sued by the state, which asked a state
Superior Court to confirm its claim of title to the vessel and its
cargo.
   The Superior Court appointed Clifford temporary custodian of the
wreck, and on that basis, he won a permit from the state Board of
Underwater Archaeological Resources to salvage the ship.
   Later, faced with claims from Clifford, the state and other
searchers, the state court granted Clifford's company title to the
vessel.
</TEXT>
