<1ST_LINE>u a PM-OakdaleDedication 1stLd-Writethru a0476 12-12 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oakdale Dedication, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detention Center Destroyed In Cuban Uprising To Be Rededicated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with dedication. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKDALE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new $17 million federal prison was
dedicated today in this western Louisiana town, replacing the
detention center that rioting Cubans burned in a night of terror 13
months ago.
   The new beginning gives townspeople the chance to look to the
future, but they should not forget the rioting, U.S. District Judge
Earl Veron warned in his dedication speech.
   Veron recalled watching the television coverage of the prison
going up in flames as Cuban detainees rampaged through the Oakdale
Federal Detention Center.
   ``I cannot understand how these defendants wanted to burn down
these excellent facilities they had, and think by burning them down
and taking hostages they would gain their freedom,'' said Veron.
   ``It is not up to me, and I express no opinion on the conduct the
United States should take against those that destroyed $15 million
in taxpayers' property.''
   More than 1,000 Cuban inmates awaiting decisions on whether they
would be freed or sent back to Cuba rioted and took 28 employees
hostage on Nov. 21, 1987, at the Oakdale center. The siege lasted
eight days, and the hostages were released unharmed.
   Although Bureau of Prison officials do not want to answer
specific questions about security, the new facility has some obvious
differences from the old one. Within the 40-acre prison, two of the
four dormitories are isolated by a high chain-link fence and a guard
post.
   Also added is a maximum security building, which has over 50
individual cells. Each cell door has a small hole and each inmate
must put his hands through that hole to be handcuffed before the
door is opened.
   The showers also have bars.
   The new Oakdale facility will handle prisoners who have been
sentenced by federal judges to prison terms. Under construction at
the site is a $14 million federal deportation center, which will
open in November 1989 to handle detainees.
   The rebuilt prison has 265 inmates at this time and can
accommodate 1,300, prison officials said. There are 400 guards.
   The deportation center will have 1,000 beds and perhaps as many
as another 400 guards, said a spokesman for Warden O.C. Jenkins.
   About 200 people shivered through the rededication ceremonies in
the open-air basketball court on the prison grounds. None of the
inmates was in sight and the prison looked empty.
   Despite last year's riot, Mayor George Mowad said he looked
forward to reopening the prison the community worked so hard to
secure and was so proud of when it opened in 1986.
   ``If someone had been killed there probably would have been more
bad feelings,'' he said recently. ``We're ready to get on with the
program.''
   The town's economy has fluctuated since the riot, and
unemployment in Allen Parish is about 11 percent, Mowad said.
   ``It was 31 percent back in January 1982 when we first started
this thing. It was the highest in the country,'' Mowad said. ``It
wasn't all the prison, but it certainly has been a major reason why
unemployment (went) down.''
   Rioting at the federal prisons in Oakdale and in Atlanta two days
later erupted shortly after the State Department announced that Cuba
had agreed to take back more than 2,500 of the 3,800 Mariel refugees
who were locked up nationwide at the time. More than half were in
the federal detention center in Oakdale.
   The takeovers ended after the government agreed to a moratorium
on deportations and a one-time-only Justice Department review of
each U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service decision.
</TEXT>
