<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     12-12 0929</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,850</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court.
   
   NCAA-Discipline
   
   The court, in a setback for college basketball coach Jerry
Tarkanian, bolstered the power of the NCAA to discipline its member
schools.
   The 5-4 ruling also could help the National Collegiate Athletic
Association in its effort to police drug use by athletes at
state-run member schools.
   The court said the NCAA, in disciplining Tarkanian, did not
violate the constitutional rights of the University of Nevada-Las
Vegas coach because the athletic body acted as a private
organization, not one operating with governmental authority.
   The case is NCAA vs. Tarkanian, 87-1061.
   
   MEDICARE
   
   The court barred the government from retroactively applying rules
limiting reimbursement paid to hospitals treating Medicare patients.
   The court, in a 9-0 ruling likely to mean millions of additional
dollars for some hospitals, rejected Reagan administration arguments
that some hospitals could reap a windfall from a ban on retroactive
application of the government's reimbursement formula.
   The case is Bowen vs. Georgetown University Hospital, 87-1097.
   
   EVIDENCE
   
   The court ruled that a government investigator's conclusions and
opinions are not ``hearsay'' and may be used as evidence in federal
trials.
   The justices reversed a federal appeals court ruling that had
ordered a new trial in a wrongful-death lawsuit against the makers
of a Navy airplane in which two people crashed six years ago.
   But today's 7-2 vote appeared to make a new trial necessary,
because the justices also ruled that the plaintiffs' lawyers wrongly
were limited in presenting their case.
   The case is Beech Aircraft vs. Rainey, 87-981.
   
   GARBAGE
   
   The court, having already ruled that privacy rights do not extend
to garbage left at curbside for pick-up, refused to treat
differently garbage discarded closer to home.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a
convicted Fremont, Neb., man had no privacy right in garbage cans
left outside for collection four feet from his home's back door.
   Unlike the court's decision last May in a case from California,
today's order sets no national precedent.
   The case is Trahan vs. Nebraska, 88-697.
   
   TENURE
   
   The court agreed to study a university's attempt to withhold
confidential information from a faculty member who says her denial
of tenure was due to illegal discrimination.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by University of
Pennsylvania officials accused of discriminating against a Chinese
woman denied promotion to full professor.
   But the justices indicated that they will be studying a very
narrow issue in the case _ one dealing with which trial court had
the authority to hear it.
   The case is University of Pennsylvania vs. EEOC, 88-493.
   
   LIBEL AWARD
   
   The court refused to reinstate a $4.5 million libel award won by
a former prosecutor against the Philadelphia Inquirer.
   The justices, citing the lack of ``a properly presented federal
question,'' let stand a Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruling that
requires a new trial for Richard Sprague's lawsuit against the
newspaper.
   The case is Sprague vs. Walter, 88-671.
   
   HELICOPTER CRASH
   
   The court rejected an appeal by a family seeking damages for the
death of a Marine helicopter co-pilot.
   The court, without comment, refused to order a new trial in a
lawsuit stemming from a 1983 helicopter crash in the Atlantic Ocean
near Virginia Beach, Va. The court previously used the case to give
military contractors sweeping immunity from being sued.
   The case is Boyle vs. United Technologies, 88-677.
   
   SODOMY
   
   The court threw out a Kentucky man's sodomy conviction because he
was barred at his trial from questioning the alleged victim, a white
woman, about her living with a black man.
   By a 7-1 vote, the justices overturned the conviction and 10-year
prison sentence of James Olden. The court expressed skepticism about
the alleged victim's testimony that she did not consent to have sex
with Olden.
   At the trial, the defendants' lawyers sought to introduce
evidence that the woman was living with another man, Bill Russell,
who is black and a half-brother of Olden.
   The trial judge refused to let the defense lawyers question the
woman about whether she was living with Russell. The judge said
allowing evidence of an inter-racial living arragnment would have
created ``extreme prejudice'' against the woman.
   The case is Olden vs. Kentucky, 88-5223.
   
   VOTING RIGHTS
   
   The court upheld a voting rights ruling that led to the election
of a black Arkansas House member from Crittenden County.
   The court, by an 8-0 vote, ruled against an appeal by Gov. Bill
Clinton and other Arkansas officials that had challenged the
election of Ben McGee as a state legislator.
   
   CLEAN WATER
   
   The court asked the Reagan administration for its view of a fine
of nearly $1 million against a Maryland paper mill operator for
failing to comply with a federal clean water law's reporting
requirements.
   The court said it wants to hear from Justice Department lawyers
before acting on a challenge to a key provision of the act
authorizing citizens and environmental groups to sue alleged
polluters.
  feet away, even under mounds of concrete.
   Orange-clad German Red Cross volunteers follow their search dogs,
telling the exhausted Soviets where they should dig first. They work
around the clock, aided by the campfires after dark.
   The volunteers had a moment of joy Sunday when a 33-year-old man
was found alive after more than four days under a collapsed,
three-story building.
   Hundreds of onlookers stood on the rubble as rescuer Peter
Schaefer of Hamburg slowly extracted the survivor. He said his name
was Ruben as he was carried away on a stretcher, with jubilant
Armenians feeding him water and pressing a cigarette into his
trembling hand.
   Reflecting the chaos in Spitak, there was no ambulance to take
him to a makeshift hospital outside the city center. After a few
frantic minutes, the rescuers commandeered the van used to transport
the German search dogs.
   The scene kindled little hope in despairing relatives like Gegush
Aganyan, a 50-year-old woman who stood a tearful vigil by her son's
wrecked apartment. She came from a mountain village in hopes her
son, Tateus, and his pregnant wife had somehow survived.
   ``It was to be my first grandchild,'' she said. ``But I think
there is no chance for them to be found alive.''
   Others searchers reported miraculous tales of survival amid the
more common discoveries of entombed families.
   ``We still have hope, although not much,'' said Artur Tovmasyan,
a volunteer directing the cranes lifting concrete slabs and
corrugated metal roofing. He said he had helped dig out 12 survivors
in the past three days.
   A list of fewer than 2,000 survivors has been written on green
sheets of paper at a shack marked with a hand-lettered sign:
``Regional Communist Party.'' Hundreds clamor around it, shouting
the names of those they seek.
   ``We already know who is missing from here,'' said Zori Zayakan
of Martuni, a village about 100 miles from Spitak. ``The
reunification effort is disorderly, but people know they can find
out if they ask at enough places.''
   Another survivor, Mayor Arzumanyan, said outside his obliterated
apartment that he ran home from the factory as soon as the main
earthquake stopped. At first he was shocked that the seven stories
above his second-floor home were spread like gray boxes in front of
the foundation, then noticed his rear apartment had been exposed by
the collapse.
   ``I pulled my two granddaughters and my younger daughter out
myself,'' said Arzumanyan, 54. ``My wife and my older daughter were
in the city to buy groceries. I didn't know what happened to them
until yesterday (Saturday).''
   His wife survived, but his 27-year-old daughter was flown to
Moscow in critical condition and he did not know her fate.
   Like others remaining in Spitak, Arzumanyan has been camping in
the near-freezing weather with bedding salvaged from the wreckage,
waiting for debris to be cleared away. He says he must find
documents and a stash of money to help his family resettle.
   Most of the homeless have been taken to undamaged areas of the
mountainous republic or bused to Yerevan, where they wait for
flights or other transport to stay with relatives elsewhere.
   The discomfort of waiting without lodging, food or access to
toilets is mostly taken in stride by Armenians who see the
earthquake as another chapter in their tragic history.
   ``We lost 1.5 million people in 1915,'' said Varchik Azaryan,
resurrecting the bloody Turkish invasion of 73 years ago. ``We have
survived that as a nation and we will survive whatever fate we
meet.''
