<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nitze-SovietRadar     12-12 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nitze-Soviet Radar,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Adviser Calls Gorbachev Plan Unsatisfactory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Nitze, President Reagan's principal arms
control adviser, said Monday that Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's plan to turn a controversial radar installation in
Siberia over to civilian and eventually international control does
not satisfy U.S. concerns.
   The United States has long maintained that the radar at
Krasnoyarsk should be torn down because it violates the 1972
Anti-Ballistc Missile treaty.
   The treaty permits radars on national borders pointed outward to
detect incoming missiles. The United States says the Krasnoyarsk
radar is a violation because it is in the middle of Soviet territory
facing inward where it might be used in an early-warning battle
management system.
   ``Turning it over to Soviet and international scientists isn't
satisfactory to us,'' Nitze said.
   ``There is no way we can be certain these civilian scientsts will
remain in charge,'' he said. ``They could convert it to an
early-warning radar in no time at all.''
   Nitze commented in an interview by international journalists and
others on Worldnet, a television production of the U.S. Information
Agency beamed overseas.
   In his address beferson ended with more
than 17,000 messages of support for the journalist, organizers say.
   ``We have encouraged prayers, we have encouraged letters ...
we're getting letters from all over the United States,'' Jack
LaVriha of the Free Terry Anderson Committee said Dec. 8.
   LaVriha said that although some people think Anderson will not
see the letters, he believes they will be given to him.
   ``The world will be watching,'' LaVriha said. ``I think there's
going to be some compassion shown.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BROADCAST NEWS</HEAD>
<HEAD>NBC's Chris Wallace Moving to ABC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC White House correspondent Chris Wallace is
moving to ABC next month to help develop a new prime-time news
program for the network on which he will be chief correspondent.
   Wallace had recently served as moderator of NBC's ``Meet the
Press.'' He is being replaced on that program by Garrick Utley, host
of NBC's ``Sunday Today,'' which is moving to Washington from New
York.
   Wallace's contract with NBC is up in January. ABC spokeswoman
Joanne Berg said ABC had reached an agreement with Wallace ``in
principle'' and hoped he would be at his new job in January.
   No details of the new news program are available yet. It is
slated to premiere in the spring of 1989.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CNN Announces Management Reorganization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable News Network has reorganized several senior
management positions to accommodate the growth of the network, which
will have 27 bureaus worldwide by next year.
   Ed Turner was appointed executive vice president for
newsgathering; Paul Amos, executive vice president for news
programming; and Jon Petrovich, executive vice president for
Headline News, CNN's second 24-hour news network.
   The changes are effective Jan. 1.
   CNN, based in Atlanta, currently has 20 bureaus worldwide, and
plans to add seven international bureaus in 1989.
