<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Sonja'sHeart Bjt   12-12 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sonja's Heart, Bjt,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sonja Henie's Frozen Heart Sculpture Finds New Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sonja Henie's icy heart won't be left out in
the cold when the warehouse where it has been stored for nearly 48
years is demolished to make room for a frozen foods plant.
   The blue-green ice sculpture was presented to the famous
Norweigian skater and movie star during a Valentine's Day 1941
performance at the Ak-Sar-Ben Coliseum _ the star's one and only
appearance in Omaha.
   Miss Henie said she would return for it some day. But she died in
1969 without ever claiming what CBS newsman Charles Kuralt once
called ``the longest-running, open-ended, most enduring publicity
stunt of all time.''
   Barney Oldfield, who was an Army publicist when he carved the
heart, said Miss Henie found her appearance in Omaha less than
heart-warming. Among other things, he said, she was upset that high
costs cut into her profits.
   ``All she was really interested in that night was to get it ...
out of the dressing room because it had green-blue dye and it was
dripping on her dressing room floor,'' Oldfield, now an executive
for Litton Industries, said in a telephone interview from his
Beverly Hills, Calif., office.
   So the heart was taken to the Omaha Cold Storage Co. warehouse
near the Mississippi River, and there it has remained over the
years, gaining in notoriety as it shrunk from its original 100
pounds to about 60 pounds.
   ``It is highly flattering that something made 45 years ago out of
the most perishable substance on earth _ frozen water _ would still
be in existence in a cold storage warehouse in Omaha,'' Oldfield
said.
   When plans were announced to tear down the warehouse to make way
for a new ConAgra frozen foods complex, there was some concern about
the fate of the heart. But Roy Mattson, owner of Omaha Cold Storage,
said he has moved the sculpture to his company's new warehouse in a
converted meat-packing plant.
   ``It's in a box in a room with a lot of raw materials for making
pet food _ liver, salisbury glands, items like that,'' Mattson said.
``I'd hate to throw it away. I'd probably get in trouble.''
   ``I suppose some good-hearted guy will continue to take care of
it,'' Oldfield said. ``It has been kind of like a relay race. There
have been 10 or 12 people who had custody of it from one time to
another.''
   Oldfield, born in Elk Creek, Neb., said he hoped to visit the
heart during a trip to Omaha later this month. He recalled how the
ice show's promoter approached him in 1941 about a publicity stunt,
but warned Oldfield that Miss Henie wasn't always friendly.
   Oldfield carved the heart out of a keg of ice and presented it to
Miss Henie at the Valentine show. As the promoter had warned,
however, she gave Oldfield the cold shoulder.
   ``As kind of an exit line, I said we would keep it until she came
back to Omaha again,'' Oldfield said.
   ``We put it in the back of a pickup _ it was 10 degrees below
zero that night. After the show we took it to Omaha Cold Storage and
stored it there. It was forgotton until I came back after World War
II and was in Omaha for Christmas before the victory march in New
York.''
   Oldfield said no one has tried to buy the heart but that the
Guinness Book of World Records has called about it.
   ``They found somebody with a 36-year-old cake in storage and they
were toying with the idea of a strange category that would include
such things, but nothing came of it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
