<DOCNO> AP881212-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1336EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-Tarkanian 2ndLd-Writethru a0590 12-12 1178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Tarkanian, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0590,1100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Backs NCAA Censure of UNLV Coach</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 9-13, I can't say, with reaction</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a setback for college
basketball coach Jerry Tarkanian, today bolstered the power of the
NCAA to discipline its member schools.
   The 5-4 ruling also could help the National Collegiate Athletic
Association in its effort to police drug use by athletes at
state-run member schools.
   The court said the NCAA, in disciplining Tarkanian, did not
violate the constitutional rights of the University of Nevada-Las
Vegas coach because the athletic body acted as a private
organization, not one operating with governmental authority.
   Justice John Paul Stevens, writing for the court, said the
university does have governmental power because it is a state-run
school.
   But Stevens said the NCAA, in seeking to discipline Tarkanian,
was acting independently from UNLV.
   ``The NCAA and UNLV acted much more like adversaries than like
partners engaged in a dispassionate search for the truth'' in
investigating Tarkanian, Stevens said.
   The NCAA ``is more correctly characterized as an agent of its
remaining members, which, as competitors of UNLV, had an interest in
the effective and evenhanded enforcement of NCAA's recruitment
standards,'' he said.
   The ruling's impact on Tarkanian's career at UNLV _ or the
school's big-time basketball program _ was not immediately apparent.
   ``I can't say at this point what will happen to Mr. Tarkanian,''
said Jack Kitchen, one of the NCAA's lawyers in the case. ``That's a
matter the committee on infractions will have to take a look at,''
he said.
   ``As far as the impact on the NCAA itself, this is a good
decision,'' Kitchen added.
   Tarkanian, when told about the decision, said, ``Naturally, I'm
disappointed.''
   He refused to discuss what action UNLV might take in his case,
saying, ``I don't want to get into that right now. I'm going to let
my lawyer talk for me.''
   But Sam Lionel, Tarkanian's lawyer, said he did not want to
discuss the decision until he had a chance to read the court's
opinions.
   Tarkanian, a highly successful coach who has been at UNLV since
1973, was accused in 1976 of numerous rule violations by the NCAA.
   NCAA officials said he arranged for a student to bet a ``B''
grade without attending class, provided free air fare to a
student-athlete, encouraged individuals to give the NCAA false
information to impede its probe, falsely certified UNLV's program as
being in compliance with NCAA rules and failed to comply with high
ethical standards.
   The NCAA placed the UNLV basketball program on two years'
probation in 1977 for recruiting violations and ordered the
university to suspend Tarkanian from coaching for two years.
   But Tarkanian obtained a court order blocking the suspension and
continued coaching.
   The Nevada Supreme Court said the NCAA had violated Tarkanian's
constitutional rights by failing to afford him due process during
its lengthy investigation.
   Today, however, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the lower court
order in ruling that the athltic organization, lacking governmental
authority, was not required to adhere to constitutional standards in
its probe.
   Tarkanian's lawyers had warned that lifting the court order
against the NCAA could mean the NCAA may throw UNLV out as a member
if the university refuses to suspend Tarkanian.
   Individuals and private organizations generally cannot violate
someone's constitutional rights. Only a government and its agents
can do that because the Constitution protects against governmental,
but not private, wrongdoing.
   The NCAA is a private organization representing nearly 1,000
colleges and universities, more than half of them state-run.
   Today's ruling could enhance the organization's power to
investigate drug abuse by athletes by not requiring it to observe
constitutional restrictions in probing for abuses.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Barred the government from retroactively applying rules
limiting reimbursement paid to hospitals treating Medicare patients.
   The court, in a 9-0 ruling likely to mean millions of additional
dollars for some hospitals, rejected Reagan administration arguments
that some hospitals could reap a windfall from a ban on retroactive
application of the government's reimbursement formula.
   _ Ruled that a governfment investigator's conclusions and
opinions are not ``hearsay'' and may be used as evidence in federal
trials.
   The justices reversed a federal appeals court ruling that had
ordered a new trial in a wrongful-death lawsuit against the makers
of a Navy airplane in which two people crashed six years ago.
   _ Having already ruled that privacy rights do not extend to
garbage left at curbside for pick-up, refused to treat differently
garbage discarded closer to home.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a
convicted Fremont, Neb., man had no privacy right in garbage cans
left outside for collection four feet from his home's back door.
   Unlike the court's decision last May in a case from California,
today's order sets no national precedent.
   _ Agreed to study a university's attempt to withhold confidential
information from a faculty member who says her denial of tenure was
due to illegal discrimination.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by University of
Pennsylvania officials accused of discriminating against a Chinese
woman denied promotion to full professor.
   But the justices indicated that they will be studying a very
narrow issue in the case _ one dealing with which trial court had
the authority to hear it.
   _ Refused to reinstate a $4.5 million libel award won by a former
prosecutor against the Philadelphia Inquirer.
   The justices, citing the lack of ``a properly presented federal
question,'' let stand a Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruling that
requires a new trial for Richard Sprague's lawsuit against the
newspaper.
   _ Rejected an appeal by a family seeking damages for the death of
a Marine helicopter co-pilot.
   The court, without comment, refused to order a new trial in a
lawsuit stemming from a 1983 helicopter crash in the Atlantic Ocean
near Virginia Beach, Va. The court previously used the case to give
military contractors sweeping immunity from being sued.
   In today's high court opinion in the Tarkanian case, Stevens
said, ``The NCAA is properly viewed as a private actor at odds with
the state when it represents the interests of its entire membership
in an investigation of one public university.''
   Stevens said the fact that UNLV could forfeit its standing as a
basketball ``powerhouse'' if it is kicked out of the NCAA does not
mean the university was forced to fire Tarkanian.
   ``That UNLV's options were unpalatable does not mean that they
were nonexistent,'' he said.
   Stevens was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Harry A. Blackmun, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
   Dissenting were Justices Byron R. White, William J. Brennan,
Thurgood Marshall and Sandra Day O'Connor.
   White, in an opinion joined by the others, said UNLV's agreement
to abide by NCAA rules governing conduct of its athletic program
made the NCAA a partner with the university in disciplining
Tarkanian. ``I would find that the NCAA acted jointly with UNLV and
therefore is a state actor,'' White said.
   The case is NCAA vs. Tarkanian, 87-1061.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
