<HEAD>6 Injured In Firebomb Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs, hospital officials say six injured, not
eight. Picks up 6th graf pvs ``Earlier, riot police...'' Kanana's
hometown is not known.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six people, including a young American woman,
were injured today when a firebomb was thrown at a passenger bus in
Arab east Jerusalem, causing the bus to crash into a wall and a
parked car, police said.
   Among the injured was Salwa Kanana, an American citizen from
Wisconsin, who was seen lying in an ambulance wearing a neck brace.
Hospital officials said five other bus passengers received light
injuries.
   Police closed off Saladin Street, east Jerusalem's main
commercial street where the crash occurred, to search for the
assailant.
   ``The moment the bottle was thrown, the front windshield of the
bus was covered in fire and smoke,'' Deputy Police Chief Maod Halevi
said. ``The driver kept going until he slammed into a wall and a
Subaru nearby.''
   Earlier, riot police chased stone-throwing Palestinian school
girls into a sacred mosque complex in Arab east Jerusalem and fired
tear gas at the demonstrators, witnesses said.
   Police said four demonstrators were arrested.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, merchants shuttered their stores for
a second straight day to mourn the deaths of two residents killed
Saturday by army gunfire.
   In the occupied West Bank, troops raided the village of Salem
near Nablus and ordered residents to paint over pro-PLO slogans.
Villagers stoned soldiers who opened fire, wounding a 22-year-old in
the left leg, said officials at Nablus' Al Ittihad Hospital.
   The protest in Jerusalem erupted on the Temple Mount, which is
sacred to Moslems and Jews. The mount, known in Arabic as Haram
Al-Sharif or Noble Enclosure, houses the Al Aqsa mosque and Dome of
the Rock shrine _ the holiest sites in Islam after Mecca and Medina
in Saudi Arabia.
   Several hundred teen-age girls gathered in front of their
religious high school inside the complex, chanting ``Allahu Akhbar''
(God is great) and throwing stones at police, said police and Arab
merchants in the area.
   Police entered the complex and started firing tear gas, said
Mohammed Jamal, a member of the Supreme Islamic Council which
administers the two mosques.
   ``While I was talking to the girls about what was going on, they
(police) shot four canisters inside the school, and then they shot
more and more,'' Jamal told The Associated Press.
   He said none of the tear gas got into the mosques, which are
about 50 and 100 yards from the school.
   Jerusalem police spokesman Rafi Levy and his assistants could not
be reached for comment despite several calls to their office and
residences.
   Jamal said he asked the students to go home, and most eventually
dispersed. A group of about 50 continued to chant ``Allahu Akbar''
on their way to east Jerusalem's central bus station, where mounted
police charged into the group.
   AP photographer Max Nash said the teen-agers fled into the narrow
corridors of the station, pursued by club-wielding mounted police.
One, about 16, grabbed a policeman's club and tried to pull him off
the horse, Nash said.
   Police hit some teen-agers who responded by throwing rocks and
bottles. Police charged into buses in search of agitators. Three
girls and one boy were detained.
   Gaza shops were closed to mourn the deaths Saturday of a
16-year-old Gaza City youth who hurled a firebomb at soldiers and an
Arab prisoner who attacked a guard with a homemade knife.
   The deaths brought to 322 the number of Palestinians killed in
the year-long revolt against Israeli rule. Eleven Israelis also have
been killed.
</TEXT>
