<2ND_LINE>AM-Sachar-Kihss Award,0170</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Newsday Reporter Gets Kihss Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emily Sachar, city schools reporter for New York
Newsday, is the winner of the 1988 Peter Kihss Award for Outstanding
Reporting on New York City Government and Public Affairs, it was
announced Monday.
   Ms. Sachar will receive a $5,000 grant at a ceremony Tuesday. The
award honors Peter Kihss, a reporter who covered the city for 50
years and retired from The New York Times in 1982. He died two years
later, shortly after receiving the first Kihss award.
   ``Emily Sachar has been a reporter since 1980, and has covered
Newsday's public education beat with distinction since 1986,'' said
Edward Costikyan, chairman of the award selection panel.
   ``She shares with Kihss a mind that is curious, discriminating
and hungry for the little details and statistics that say to the
best reporters: dig here,'' Costikyan said.
   The award is sponsored by the Fund for the City of New York.
</TEXT>
