<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlaskaQuake     12-12 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alaska Quake,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Rumbles Through Southeast Alaska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMER, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake rocked portions of
Southeast Alaska early Monday, rattling windows but causing no
reported damage or injuries, the Alaska Tsunami Warning Center
reported.
   Geophysicist Paul Whitmore said the 9:57 a.m. (AST) temblor
measured 4.7 on the Richter scale. It was centered about 90 miles
northwest of Juneau, or 40 miles west of Haines, he said.
   The quake rattled windows in Juneau and Haines, he said.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus, a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 time
stronger than one of 6.5.
   The 1964 ``Good Friday'' earthquake in Alaska measured 8.5 on the
Richter scale and was centered in Prince William Sound. It generated
large waves that devastated several coastal communities and killed
114 people as far south as Oregon and Hawaii.
</TEXT>
