<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tibet     12-12 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Make Arrests as Tibetans Mourn after Clash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mourning Tibetans made shrines of stones around
pools of dried blood on Monday, a day after a clash with police who
were seen taking residents from their homes, Western travelers said.
   Travelers reached by telephone in Lhasa said they heard
unconfirmed reports of Tibetans throwing stones at police patrols
after dark Sunday and of police firing tear gas.
   China's official media has not reported any arrests, but said one
Tibetan Buddhist monk was killed and 13 people were injured when
police fired warning shots Saturday at 30 Tibetans who marched into
the central square waving their banned nationalist flag.
   An English-speaking tourist who asked not to be identified said
some Tibetans told her their friends and relatives had disappeared
and were believed arrested.
   Robert Dean, 24, of Auckland, New Zealand, said he saw police
drive up to Tibetan homes, talk to residents and lead some away.
``One particular (official) I saw four times at four different
homes, taking four different people away,'' he said.
   Authorities allow few foreign reporters to travel to Tibet and
then only when conditions are calm.
   Police on Monday confiscated the passport of a Dutch woman who
was shot in the arm, and the ticket office for the state airline
said she was not allowed to leave town, a Canadian friend said.
   Ron Schwartz, a professor at the University of Newfoundland in
St. John's, said he tried to buy a ticket to Canton for Christa
Meindersma of Amsterdam, but was refused. Ms. Meindersma was treated
at a Lhasa hospital and released.
   ``We wanted to take her to Hong Kong and put her in a hospital,''
said Schwartz.
   Ms. Meindersma and Schwartz witnessed Saturday's protest, but
both said they had no connections to anti-Chinese Tibetan activists.
   Dutch consular attache Willem de Bruin said in Beijing he would
ask Chinese authorities to allow Ms. Meindersma to leave. ``I hope
this is just a formality,'' he said, adding he was disappointed
authorities had given him little information on her condition.
   Tibetan nationalists, including Buddhist monks and nuns, dispute
China's claim to seven centuries of sovereignty over Tibet. They
want an independent country led by the Dalai Lama, the leader of
Tibetan Buddhism who has been in exile in India since an abortive
anti-Chinese uprising in 1959.
   Tibetans have staged many small protests in the past 14 months,
but Saturday's was the third to turn bloody. At least 38 people were
killed in violent clashes with police Oct. 1 and March 5.
   China has maintained that foreign travelers took part in some
previous protests, but has not made such charges about Saturday's
violence.
   Police searched guest rooms at the Yak backpacker hotel Sunday
and Monday, said Todd Johnson, 24, of Santa Cruz, Calif.
   ``They seem to be looking for particular individuals who they
believe were eyewitnesses,'' he said.
</TEXT>
