<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HijackAttempt     12-12 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack Attempt,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Exile Awaits Extradition After Hijacking Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban exile who tried to hijack a commercial
airliner to Cuba but was tricked into landing on an island south of
the Bahamas was questioned Monday by FBI agents trying to learn his
motive, officials said.
   Felix Sanchez Rodriguez, 26, allegedly used a fake bomb to demand
the TWA flight from San Juan, Puerto Rico, be diverted to Cuba. He
was arrested after the plane landed instead in the Turks and Caicos
Islands, a British colony.
   ``They tricked him good and nobody got hurt _ that's the
important thing,'' said Paul Miller, FBI spokesman in Miami.
   The hijacking attempt, only the second attempt on a domestic U.S.
airliner in more than two years, ended when the Boeing 727 and its
121 passengers flew on to Miami Sunday night.
   ``All we know for sure is that the man wanted to go to Cuba,''
Miller said. ``He apparently wanted to see his mother _ she was
either very sick or dying. Because of the language difference it was
difficult to find out for sure.''
   An FBI agent interviewed Rodriguez at his jail cell on Grand Turk
Island, Miller said, adding that it probably will be several days
before the man is brought to Miami to face federal air-piracy
charges.
   The pilot of Flight 469 was able to get permission to land on
Grand Turk island where police, using a Spanish-speaking person,
were able to convince Rodriguez he was in Havana, Miller said.
   ``He was horrified to realize he had been tricked,'' said
passenger Willie Douglas of Montgomery, Ala.
</TEXT>
