<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Niko'sFarewell     12-12 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Niko's Farewell,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guatemalan Gets New Lease on Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLEN G. BREED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of 10 children who made and sold
pottery to pay for her education in Guatemala, Nicolasa Menchu was
used to beating the odds when she arrived here in 1986 with a
serious spinal curvature that doctors said eventually would have
killed her.
   Almost three years later, she is on her way back to her native
land, not only out of danger, but 2{ inches taller and with a
bachelor's degree in elementary education from the University of
Louisville.
   At a farewell party at the university last Friday, the huge smile
that has become ``Niko's'' trademark among her friends said it all.
   ``I feel excited and at the same time I feel sad,'' said Ms.
Menchu, who recently celebrated her 28th birthday. ``I have so much
to say thank you for to all the people who helped me make my goals.''
   Ms. Menchu's ordeal began last fall when she developed breathing
problems while swimming. She was turned over to Dr. John Johnson,
co-director of the spine clinic at Louisville's Norton Hospital.
   Ms. Menchu underwent a series of four operations, all free, to
correct a 142-degree curvature of her spine that was choking off her
vital organs. Doctors said the operation carried a 60 percent chance
of success and a 20 percent chance that the patient would not
survive.
   While she still experiences some pain in her back when it is
cold, Ms. Menchu doesn't complain. ``I just hold it in,'' she said.
   Her sights are set on becoming a special education teacher in
Guatemala City.
   But she will never forget the American doctor who saved her life.
   ``He offered me his help, and I don't have anything to pay him
with,'' she said. ``I just have to show him some kind of
appreciation. It was not just something simple, it was something for
my life.''
</TEXT>
