<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     12-12 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Likud and Labor Hold New Coalition Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Likud and Labor negotiators met for six hours
Monday about a possible coalition government of the two main
parties, and Labor demanded electoral reforms to curb the power of
religious parties.
   Small religious parties won 18 of the 120 parliament seats in the
Nov. 1 election and hold the balance of power between the
conservative Likud bloc, which got 40 seats, and the center-left
Labor Party with 39.
   They have demanded important Cabinet posts and stricter
government policies on religion as terms for joining a right-wing
coalition with Likud, led by Prime Minster Yitzhak Shamir.
   Negotiators from both major parties reported progress in Monday's
talks and some predicted a coalition deal would be made this week.
   Likud and Labor, whose leader is Foreign Minister Shimon Peres,
have been equal partners in a ``national unity'' coalition since the
indecisive election of July 1984. The leaders traded jobs two years
ago.
   Many issues appeared unresolved after the meeting of the
three-member teams Monday in Jerusalem, but Moshe Katzav, a Likud
Cabinet minister, told army radio as he emerged:
   ``There was progress. There are still a few open questions, but
... we have established intensive discussions and we want to finish
as soon as possible. I hope that we conclude the discussions in a
day or two.''
   Israel radio said the negotiators focused on guidelines for a
joint government and agreed to an evenly divided Inner Cabinet,
which makes the major security and foreign policy decisions.
   A Labor official close to Peres said privately the party demanded
electoral reforms, including direct election of the prime minister
and requiring more votes to qualify for a seat in the Knesset,
Israel's parliament.
   Each party assigns Knesset seats from its own candidate list on
the basis of how many votes it receives.
   Requiring more votes per seat would make it difficult for smaller
parties to get into parliament, thus limiting the power of religious
parties, among others.
   After negotiating with right-wing and religious parties, Shamir
turned back to Labor in an apparent effort to avoid major
concessions on religious and political issues demanded by the small
factions.
   His talks with those parties continue, however, and officials
close to the prime minister said the factions may join whatever
government is formed.
   The Peres aide said Labor opposes Likud's agreement with the
far-right Tehiya and National Religious parties to build 40 new
Jewish settlements in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in the
next four years.
   Six new settlements were authorized in the four years of
Labor-Likud coalition that began in 1984.
   Yossi Ahimeir, an adviser to Shamir, said Likud wants more
emphasis on new settlements but is prepared to ``reconsider'' if
Labor joins the government.
   About 70,000 Jews live in more than 130 settlements in the West
Bank and Gaza, where a rebellion began a year ago among the 1.5
million Palestinian residents.
   According to the Peres aide, Labor will insist on the right to
oppose such religious legislation as the proposed ``Who Is a Jew''
law, which would accept only conversions to Judaism performed by
Orthodox rabbis.
   Jews in the United States, where the Conservative and Reform
movements are strong, oppose the legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
