<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1704EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Sodomy 1stLd-Writethru a0611 12-12 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Sodomy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,410</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS vote in 2nd graf, By an, and eliminates penultimate
graf, Justice William, to reflect that Brennan did take part.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today threw out a Kentucky
man's sodomy conviction because he was barred at his trial from
questioning the alleged victim, a white woman, about her living with
a black man.
   By an 8-1 vote, the justices overturned the conviction and
10-year prison sentence of James Olden. The court expressed
skepticism about the alleged victim's testimony that she did not
consent to have sex with Olden.
   Olden and a friend, Charlie Ray Harris, were indicted on
kidnapping, rape and forcible sodomy charges.
   Both men, who are black, were accused of forcing a young white
woman to have sex with them after they met her at a bar in
Princeton, Ky.
   The woman initally told police she was raped by four men; later
said she was raped by Olden and Harris, and at trial said Olden was
the sole rapist.
   She also testified at trial that Olden threatened her with a
knife, although in earlier statements to police she did not allege
that he was armed.
   Olden and Harris said the woman consented to having sex with them.
   At the trial, the defendants' lawyers sought to introduce
evidence that the woman was living with another man, Bill Russell,
who is black and a half-brother of Olden.
   The defense lawyers said the woman concocted the story of being
raped to prevent Russell from learning the truth that she consented
to sex with the defendants.
   The trial judge refused to let the defense lawyers question the
woman about whether she was living with Russell.
   The judge said allowing evidence of an inter-racial living
arragnment would have created ``extreme prejudice'' against the
woman.
   Harris was acquitted. Olden was acquitted of kidnapping and rape,
but convicted of forcing the woman to commit sodomy.
   But today the Supreme Court said Olden's right to confront his
accuser was violated by excluding the evidence of the alleged
victim's living arrangement.
   In an unsigned opinion, the court said, ``Speculation as to the
effect of jurors' racial biases cannot justify exclusion of
cross-examination with such strong potential to demonstrate the
falsity of (the alleged victim's) testimony.''
   Justice Thurgood Marshall dissented on grounds that the court
should have held formal arguments in the case rather than summarily
reversimg Olden's conviction.
   The case is Olden vs. Kentucky, 88-5223.
</TEXT>
