<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoyPilot     12-12 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boy Pilot,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Drinking Boy Stole Plane, Landed Safely At Busy Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old boy who police say had been
drinking because of family problems took a small plane on a
three-hour flight through some of the nation's busiest airspace
before another pilot talked him down.
   Air traffic controllers and some commercial flights were on alert
Saturday night as the boy, who had only a few hours of flying
instruction, zigged and zagged across major air corridors serving
Newark International, Kennedy International and LaGuardia airports.
   The boy, whose name was withheld because of his age, allegedly
broke into a trailer at Old Bridge Airport in Middlesex County and
took keys to a single-engine Cessna 172, Old Bridge police Sgt.
William Lynch said.
   ``He got the plane off the ground, and I guess nobody noticed
because the airport is closed at night,'' Lynch said. ``It was
pretty good in the dark.''
   The stolen plane went unnoticed until the boy got about 18 miles
away from the Old Bridge airport and began radioing a ``mayday''
distress signal, said Bill Cahill, a spokesman for the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey, which owns and operates the
three major airports.
   The signal was heard all along the mid-Atlantic region's air
traffic facilities, said Kathleen Bergen, a spokeswoman for the
Federal Aviation Administration.
   ``The kid is not a pilot, and he allegedly was intoxicated when
he was flying around,'' she said. ``It's not that busy after
midnight on a Saturday and it's a good thing.''
   The boy told police he was having family problems, Lynch said.
   Raymond Malawich, a corporate charter plane pilot heading for
Teterboro Airport, heard the boy's call for help and went in search
of the other plane.
   ``It took 15 minutes to find him,'' Malawich said. ``He was kind
of scared and disoriented.''
   Malawich radioed the boy and told him to follow his tail lights
to Newark International. At one point, the boy lost sight of the
corporate plane and started following another plane toward Linden
Airport.
   ``I picked him up again and took him from there into Newark,''
Malawich said.
   The boy landed safely at Newark at 12:43 a.m. Sunday, with
Malawich talking him through the landing.
   Port Authority police took him into custody and he he failed a
Breathalyzer test, Cahill said.
   The plane was not damaged, Lynch said. The boy was released in
his parents' custody and his case was turned over to juvenile
authorities, who will decide whether to prosecute him on burglary
and theft charges, Lynch said.
   Ms. Bergen said the FAA could press charges of its own.
</TEXT>
