<HEAD>Union Leader Rejects Guardian Angels' Offer to Set Up Patrols</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rail union leader Monday rejected a plan by the
U.S. Guardian Angels group to set up patrols in London's subway
system after two people were fatally stabbed and a third was wounded.
   ``Private individuals are indisciplined,'' said Neil Milligan,
secretary of the 30,000-member Associated Society of Locomotive
Engineers and Firemen. He said police and rail staff should be
increased.
   The latest victim of violence in the Underground was a
29-year-old man who was stabbed with a knife Sunday night during a
fight at London Bridge station. He later had a kidney removed in an
operation Monday.
   Members of the Guardian Angels, who operate in 70 U.S. cities,
said they planned to visit London to train British groups to begin
patrolling the Underground next year. The government opposes the
plan.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd and Transport Secretary Paul Channon
are to meet this week to discuss increasing violence on British
subways and railroads.
   A Turkish visitor, Hakan Koseoglu, 17, was fatally stabbed Friday
in Holborn station after he resisted two muggers who grabbed a gold
chain from his neck. The two were tackled by two other passengers,
but escaped.
   Six hours later, mechanic John Heron, 35, was stabbed at the
Waterloo station during an argument as he stood in line for
information. The assailant escaped and Heron died Saturday.
   Crime on the London Underground has multiplied by 20 times since
1980. This year, 18,383 criminal incidents were reported, subway
officials said.
