<HEAD>US, England and Canada to Suspend Low-Level Jet Training Over West
Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, Britain and Canada have
agreed to join West Germany in suspending all low-level jet fighter
training over West Germany for the next three weeks, the Pentagon
announced today.
   The suspension follows last week's fiery crash of a U.S. warplane
in the German city of Remscheid, in which five people were killed
and dozens injured.
   ``The suspension will remain in effect until Jan. 2, 1989, at
which point fighter training will resume,'' the Pentagon said in
releasing a joint communique from the four NATO allies.
   The suspension, ``through the holiday season, (was agreed to) out
of respect for the victims and the families of the victims of the
Remscheid accident, and for Capt. Michael Foster, USAF, and his
family,'' the statement added.
   Foster, 34, of Seal Beach, Calif., was the pilot of the A-10
Thunderbolt II attack jet that crashed in Remscheid, destroying two
dozen homes. The accident occurred on Dec. 8 and immediately
generated new demands in West Germany for curbs on NATO flights.
   The agreement to suspend fighter training until after New Year's
was announced shortly after Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci held
a closed-door meeting with his West German counterpart, Defense
Minister Rupert Scholz, at the Pentagon.
   Neither Scholz nor Carlucci was available after the meeting to
discuss the flight suspension. But Pentagon officials who asked not
to be named said the West German government had asked the United
States to stop military aerial training until after the holidays.
   Scholz previously had told reporters that France, Belgium and The
Netherlands had acceeded to his government's request.
</TEXT>
