<HEAD>Green River TV Show Leads To Arrest Of Two In Separate Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENT, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television special on the Green River serial
killings has led to the arrests of two people in the murder of a
woman whose body was found in the river, police said Monday.
   The killing, however, was believed to be unrelated to the Green
River case, Kent police Sgt. Bob Cline said.
   Authorities on Saturday arrested Michael Hill, 27, and a
17-year-old boy, whose name was withheld, in the Oct. 25 killing of
Alice Cecila Worthing, 25. Ms. Worthing's body was found the next
day in the Green River.
   The arrests were made on the basis of a tip phoned in after last
week's nationwide broadcast of ``Manhunt: A Chance to End the
Nightmare,'' which chronicled police efforts to capture the Green
River killer.
   The Green River killer is officially blamed for the deaths of as
many as 48 young women, many of them prostitutes, between the summer
of 1982 and early 1984.
   Forty are known dead and the Green River Task Force blames the
killer for the disappearances of eight women. The case takes its
name from the river south of Seattle where the first five victims
were found in the summer of 1982.
   Although Ms. Worthing's body was recovered from the Green River,
her death is believed to be unrelated to the serial killings.
   Ms. Worthing, who had brushes with police in connection with drug
and prostitution offenses, was last seen walking in the Holly Park
area of Seattle, Cline said. Her body was found by fishermen. She
had been asphyxiated.
   Cline said he did not know what information was called in, and
further details about the arrests were not immediately available.
   The telephone tip leading to the arrests was among more than
50,000 that have flooded investigators since the television show.
   ``They're still coming in as fast as we can take them,'' King
County Police detective Frank Spence said. He said it would be
months before investigators finish checking out the tips.
</TEXT>
