<2ND_LINE>AM-Cocaine Parents,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents Showed Her How To Smoke Cocaine, Daughter Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father charged with furnishing
cocaine to his 17-year-old daughter said he ``wanted her to be
exposed to it at home,'' police said Monday.
   Victor P. Hupman, 36, and his wife, Patricia, 34, were arrested
Friday on four charges of furnishing cocaine to a minor after their
daughter Stephanie, a student at Los Altos High School, told a
school counselor her parents had a drug problem and were openly
using cocaine.
   Stephanie first saw her parents using cocaine in 1986 and asked
several months ago if she could try the drug, according to police.
   ``She made the inquiries. He offered, she accepted,'' Mountain
View police officer Chris Lindholm said. ``They didn't seek her
out.''
   She told authorities that her father showed her how to cook the
powdered drug into potent, rock-like ``crack'' before smoking a
pipeful with her.
   The high school student tried cocaine four times with her
parents, including twice with crack, police said.
   The teen-ager last took cocaine the night her father took so much
he got sick and thought he was suffering a heart attack, police said.
   ``She was frightened by what she saw and thought it was related
to cocaine,'' said Lt. Gary Smith. ``She said she would never try it
again.''
   She was afraid the drug would kill her parents when she told the
school counselor about their drug use, authorities said.
   The couple surrendered after police interviewed the five Hupman
children, ages 6 to 17, Smith said.
   Police said there is no indication that any other children were
exposed to cocaine at the home in Mountain View, 45 miles southeast
of San Francisco. A search of the family's apartment turned up no
drugs or drug-related paraphernalia, Smith said.
   Victor Hupman, a printer at Stanford University, is scheduled to
be arraigned Dec. 20. Patricia Hupman, a patient relations
specialist at the university, is scheduled to be arraigned later.
They were freed on $25,000 bail Saturday.
   If convicted, they face a maximum penalty of seven years in
prison.
   The Hupman's children have been placed temporarily with Patricia
Hupman's parents in San Jose, Smith said.
   Although the teen-ager wanted her parents to get help, she also
feared that reporting their drug use could break up the family,
Lindholm said. State child abuse laws require school officials to
relay reports of drug use to police.
   ``Her (Stephanie's) attitude was what has to be to be done has to
be done,'' said Lindholm. ``As long as the family was going to get
some help, it was OK.''
</TEXT>
