<HEAD>U.S. Mediator Arrives For Signing of Peace Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant U.S. Secretary of State
Chester Crocker arrived Monday to prepare for the signing of a peace
agreement between South Africa, Cuba and Angola.
   The U.S.-mediated accord will be signed Tuesday, according to
government-run Congo radio.
   Crocker has been the chief mediator in the negotiations, whose
goal is the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola and
independence for the South African-ruled territory of South-West
Africa.
   The negotiations broke off Dec. 3 after the surprise departure of
the South African delegation, which said it needed to consult with
its government on proposals for the verification of the Cuban
withdrawal.
   The Cuban and Angolan delegations accused the South Africans of
bad faith and charged Pretoria was not interested in independence
for South-West Africa, also called Namibia.
   Diplomats have said an interim accord would be signed in
Brazzaville, with a formal treaty to be signed in January at the
United Nations in New York.
   The Cuban delegation was headed by Ricardo de Quessada,
vice-minister for external affairs. The South African and Angolan
delegations were expected Tuesday.
