<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     12-12 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firebomb Wounds Six in Israeli Bus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A firebomb was hurled at an Israeli bus Monday
in Arab east Jerusalem and the bus crashed into a wall and a parked
car, injuring six people, including an American woman, police said.
   Israeli soldiers in the occupied Gaza Strip confined 650,000
Palestinians to their homes with an indefinite curfew beginning at 9
p.m.
   Gaza residents said the curfew might be intended to limit
demonstrations during the speech Tuesday to the U.N. General
Assembly in Geneva by Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine
Libration Organization.
   Shopkeepers in the Gaza Strip closed for a second day to mourn
the deaths of two residents killed Saturday by army gunfire
Saturday. At least 322 Palestinians have died in a year of rebellion
against Israeli rule in the occupied territories, and 11 Israelis
have been slain.
   Police fired tear gas on the grounds of Jerusalem's holiest
mosques after chasing Palestinian high school girls who threw
stones, witnesses said. Three teen-age girls and a boy were reported
arrested.
   Jerusalem police searched for the bomb-thrower, believed to be a
Palestinian. They closed Saladin Street, east Jerusalem's main
commercial thoroughfare, where the attack occurred.
   ``The moment the bottle was thrown, the front windshield of the
bus was covered in fire and smoke,'' said Deputy Police Chief Maod
Halevi. ``The driver kept going until he slammed into a wall and a
car nearby.''
   Among the injured was Salwa Kanana, of Wisconsin, who was seen
lying in an ambulance wearing a neck brace. Hospital officials said
five other passengers were slightly injured.
   Masoud Fadida, a Palestinian from Ramallah homeward bound on the
bus, said: ``We thought the bus was going to turn over, then we
managed to crawl out the back door.''
   The stone-throwing in Jerusalem occurred on Temple Mount,
venerated by both Moslems and Jews and known in Arabic as Haram
al-Sharif (Noble Enclosuree). In the complex are the silver-domed Al
Aqsa and gold-topped Dome of the Rock mosques.
   Several hundred teen-age girls gathered in front of their
religious high school on the grounds, chanting ``Allahu Akhbar!''
(``God is great!'') and throwing rocks at police, both officers and
Arab merchants reported.
   Riot police entered the complex and fired tear gas, said Mohammed
Jamal, a member of the Supreme Islamic Council that administers the
two mosques. Haram al-Sharif is the third holiest site of Islam,
after Mecca and Medina in Saudi Arabia.
   ``Police shot four canisters inside the school and then they shot
more and more'' but none of the gas entrered the mosques, Jamal said.
   About 50 girls marched to the central bus station in east
Jerusalem, where they began throwing stones and were charged by
mounted police.
   An Associated Press photographer said girls fled into alleys
around the station, pursued by mounted police swinging clubs, and a
girl of about 16 tried to pull one of the officers off his horse.
   Soldiers shot and wounded a 22-year-old Palestinian during a raid
on Salem village in the West Bank near Nablus, said doctors at Al
Ittihad Hospital in Nablus. Troopers began shooting after they were
stoned by villagers who resisted orders to paint over pro-PLO
slogans.
   The army said it had discovered several Palestinian squads that
belonged to Arafat's Fatah guerrilla faction and were suspected of
attacks on soldiers and Israeli civilians.
   A military spokesman said the squads were responsible for a knife
attack on two young Israelis in a Tel Aviv suburb in September 1987
and for planting three bombs aimed at Israeli patrols in the Gaza's
Deir el-Balah refugee camp.
</TEXT>
