<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     12-12 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ishaq Khan Elected President; Bhutto Wins Confidence Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ghulam Ishaq Khan easily won
his first full five-year term on Monday, and Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto won her first parliamentary vote of confidence.
   Ms. Bhutto told legislators after her People's Party won 148-55
that Pakistan's destiny does not belong to any one party.
   ``It is the destiny of the entire people of Pakistan. Each one of
us has to shoulder the responsibility,'' she said.
   Earlier, right-wing lawmaker Mohammad Zaheer Khan tried to block
the confidence vote by saying the prophet Mohammed taught that a
woman could not rule Moslems.
   A few minutes later, nearly 73 percent of his colleagues approved
Ms. Bhutto's leadership.
   Her party emerged as the largest single party Nov. 16 in the
country's first free elections in more than a decade. But with 105
seats, it fell short of an outright majority in the 237-seat
legislature.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35, since has gained support from several
independents and minor parties, which entitled her to become the
first female prime minister in the Moslem world.
   Under the constitution, the governing party has to pass a vote of
confidence in parliament within 60 days of forming a government.
   Federal Election Commissioner S.A. Nusrat announced on television
that Ishaq Khan, of the Muslim League, swept 78 percent of
presidential votes cast by an electoral college of the Senate,
National Assembly and four provincial assemblies.
   Ms. Bhutto's party and the right-wing opposition alliance, headed
by the Muslim League, both supported Ishaq Khan among the four
presidential candidates, guaranteeing his victory.
   Of 446 valid votes, Ishaq Khan polled 348 compared with 91 to his
nearest rival, veteran politician Nawabzada Nasrullah Khan, Nusrat
said.
   Ishaq Khan, 78, credited with guiding Pakistan back to democracy
after 11 years of autocratic rule, is to take the oath of office
Tuesday.
   For the last eight years, Pakistan was ruled under martial law by
President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, who died in an Aug. 17 plane crash
that investigators said was probably caused by sabotage.
   Because he was Senate chairman, the presidency passed to Ishaq
Khan, who has nearly 40 years of experience in senior administrative
posts, six of them as finance and commerce minister.
   Pakistan's president holds a largely ceremonial post, but the
roles of both president and prime minister are under debate.
   A 1985 constitutional amendment authored by Zia gives the
president broad but vague discretionary powers.
   Ms. Bhutto has called for a repeal of that amendment, which would
restore supreme political powers to the prime minister as they
existed during her father's 1970s government.
   Zia ousted Zulfikar Ali Bhutto in 1977 and had him executed two
years later for allegedly plotting to overthrow a political foe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
