<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MineStrike     12-12 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mine Strike,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mine Workers Set Strike Deadline For Pittston Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Mine Workers President Richard
Trumka said Monday the Pittston Group has until Jan. 31 to reach a
new contract with 2,000 union members in three states, or face a
strike.
   ``We want to go the last step, the last mile, to see if an
agreement can be reached,'' Trumka said at a news conference called
to announce the start of a media campaign to pressure Pittston to
negotiate. ``But this is one union that has never run from a fight,
and we're prepared to fight this one.''
   But Pittston President Gene Matthis, who has said the company
will continue to operate if the union strikes, said Monday he does
not expect talks to resume soon.
   ``We think it would be most unfortunate if the union would carry
through with this,'' Matthis said. ``It would create a lot of
hardship in some of these communities.''
   Pittston miners in West Virginia, Virginia and Kentucky have been
working without a contract for 11 months, since the 1984 national
coal contract expired last Jan. 31. Trumka said there have been no
negotiations since Nov. 9, when Pittston gave the union ``a
take-it-or-leave-it offer.''
   Trumka said the company's offer would weaken safety rights,
eliminate the eight-hour day, increase health care costs and give
the company control of the pension plan.
   Pittston dropped out of the national coal industry bargaining
organization before negotiations began for the 1988 agreement,
saying the company's needs were different than those of the rest of
the industry. The union contends Pittston has demonstrated no
interest in reaching an agreement.
   Matthis said his company's latest offer is better than the
contract the UMW recently signed with A.T. Massey Coal Co., ending a
bitter conflict that began in 1984.
   The campaign announced by the union on Monday will ``increase
pressure against the company on all fronts,'' Trumka said. He said
the UMW is urging other unions and their supporters to withdraw
funds from banks lending money to Pittston.
</TEXT>
