<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChicagoMayoral     12-12 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alderman Ed Burke Drops Out of Mayor's Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Burke, the alderman once considered the
strongest white mayoral candidate, quit the contest Monday and threw
his support behind fellow Democrat Richard M. Daley.
   Daley's entry into the race a week ago doomed Burke's chances,
particularly among white ethnic voters, the source of both men's
strongest support.
   ``I can read the cards as well as anyone else,'' Burke said. ``I
said I would not continue in this race if all indications did not
point to a successful result for me. They do not at this time.''
   Burke made the announcement after recent polls showed Daley, the
Cook County state's attorney and son of legendary Chicago Mayor
Richard J. Daley, leading the field.
   He said he was joining Daley's campaign because ``of the
remaining candidates, he's the one who has the best chance of
winning.''
   Burke, 44, former chairman for the City Council's Finance
Committee, was a leader of council opposition to Mayor Harold
Washington, the city's first black mayor who died in office a year
ago. A special mayoral election will be held April 4. The primary is
scheduled for Feb. 28.
   Burke's withdrawal ``means a clear field for Daley in corraling
the white ethnic vote,'' said Paul Kleppner, director of the Social
Science Research Institute at Northern Illinois University in DeKalb
and a longtime observer of Chicago politics.
   Kleppner predicted a Daley victory unless one of the two leading
black candidates _ Mayor Eugene Sawyer and Alderman Timothy Evans _
decides to drop out.
   If both stay in the race, they likely will split the vote in the
black community and pave the way for a Daley triumph, Kleppner said.
   Burke's announcement came a day after Sawyer said he will seek to
stay in office. Sawyer was elected acting mayor by fellow aldermen
last December, after Washington's death.
   The other announced Democratic candidates are Aldermen Timothy
Evans, Lawrence Bloom and Danny Davis, and former state Sen. James
Taylor.
   Former Chicago Parks Superintendent Edmund Kelly withdrew from
the Democratic field Dec. 6, the day after Daley announced his
candidacy.
   Edward Howlett, son of a former Democratic secretary of state, is
the only announced GOP candidate.
</TEXT>
