<DOCNO> AP881212-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1924EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavingsBonds     12-12 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savings Bonds,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales of Savings Bonds Continue Upswing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S. Savings Bonds increased for the
second consecutive month in November, rising 7.1 percent to $587
million, the highest level in five months, the government said
Monday.
   The Treasury Department said sales rose $39 million from October
and were up $44 million, or 8.1 percent, from November 1987. It was
the highest total since June, when $615 million in bonds were sold.
   Jerrold B. Speers, executive director of the U.S. Savings Bonds
Division, attributed the increase to a normal seasonal pickup in
purchases for Christmas gifts and to a rise in the market-based rate
on the bonds.
   Effective Nov. 1 through next April 30, bonds held five years or
longer will earn at an annual rate of 7.35 percent for the six
months, up from 6.9 percent the previous six months.
   As of Nov. 30, the total value of savings bonds held by Americans
was $108.9 billion, up 8.9 percent from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
