<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Israel,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Orders Two Quake Relief Planes to Regroup at Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Israeli air force planes with supplies for
Armenia's earthquake victims turned around and flew back home Monday
because an Israeli already at their destination told them they were
not needed, officials said.
   The civil defense commander, Maj. Gen. Aharon Vardi, radioed the
pilots to return a few hours after takeoff so they could reorganize
for a relief mission elsewhere in the area devastated by Wednesday's
earthquake, Israeli officials said.
   Vardi came to Armenia on an earlier Israeli relief flight. A
military spokesman said on condition of anonymity that Vardi decided
the planes ``could not be used effectively at the scene'' because
their medical assistance was not needed in Leninaken, one of the
hardest-hit cities in the southern Soviet republic.
   The planes were carrying relief supplies, medical teams and a
field hospital.
   The military spokesman stressed that the Israeli official, not
the Soviet government, made the decision to order the U.S.-made
Hercules airplanes back to Israel.
   He said the aircraft were waiting at Ben Gurion International
Airport in Tel Aviv for orders to return to the Soviet Union. Israel
was waiting for further instructions from Soviet authorities before
sending the planes back, he said.
   When the planes took off Monday, Moscow's top diplomat in Tel
Aviv said the assistance would bring the Israeli and Soviet peoples
closer.
   ``We are greatly moved by this,'' said Georgy Martirosov, head of
the Soviet consular delegation in Tel Aviv, on Israel army radio.
``This help by the Israeli people will bring us closer emotionally.''
   The Soviet Union broke diplomatic ties with Israel during the
1967 Middle East War. But relations have warmed gradually in the
last two years with agreements to exchange low-level diplomats.
</TEXT>
