<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FrigidFlorida     12-12 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Frigid Florida,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mountainside Town Doesn't Live Up To Its Balmy Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Storms-Cold Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLORIDA, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though the town's name evokes images of
palm trees and sunny beaches, the 650 residents of Florida shivered
in air that hit 18 degrees below zero Monday, the coldest
temperature in Massachusetts.
   But townspeople say subzero temperatures are common in the
mountainside community that sits 2,800 feet above sea level, just
500 feet below the state's highest peak, Mount Greylock.
   ``We're just used to coping with stuff like that,'' said Wayne
Boyce, a member of the Board of Selectmen. ``It's not unusual for us
to have snow banks taller than cars.
   ``When Boston gets three or four inches of snow, everybody
panics, nobody can move. We get a couple of inches daily,'' Boyce
boasted. ``That's nothing for us.''
   He said the town in Massachusetts' northwest corner probably was
named after the southern state because Florida ``had a magical sound
to it.''
   ``Probably because of Ponce de Leon and the fountain of youth,''
he said, adding there also are Floridas in neighboring New York and
Vermont.
   Einar Oleson, a former town clerk and member of the local
historical society, also believes the town was been named in honor
of the state, which the nation was considering buying from Spain at
the time of the town's incorporation in 1805.
   Another theory has it that the town was named for the wild
azaleas, called floribunda, that once covered the mountain on which
the community sits, she said.
   Boyce said he rarely hears jokes about the town's moniker, but a
photograph several years ago of a resident holding a snow shovel and
standing next to the frozen highway sign bearing the town's name was
published in several newspapers in the southern state.
</TEXT>
