<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Plane,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim They Downed Afghan Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-backed Moslem rebels on Monday
claimed they shot down an Afghan military aircraft, but
Afghanistan's official radio gave a different account and said a
passenger plane was shot down with all 25 people aboard killed.
   Official Radio Kabul charged that a Pakistan air force plane on
Saturday shot down a Soviet-made Antonov-26 airliner as it was
heading toward Kabul, the capital, from the eastern city of Khost,
18 miles from the Pakistan border.
   Pakistani officials denied the allegation.
   Abdul Kabir, a spokesman for the Hezb-e-Islami rebel group, said
guerrillas brought down a military transport plane on Saturday with
a sophisticated, U.S.-supplied anti-aircraft missile.
   Radio Kabul and the rebels, known as mujahedeen, or holy
warriors, presumably were referring to the same incident.
   ``We only know that some government officials and other military
officers were on the plane,'' Kabir said, dismissing Radio Kabul
claims.``Khost is under siege by mujahedeen and only military planes
go there.''
   He said his guerrilla organization probably was the one involved
because it is the strongest in the area and has most of the Stinger
missiles.
   Afghanistan and Pakistan, which signed a U.N.-brokered accord in
April providing for the withdrawal of more than 100,000 Soviet
troops from Afghanistan, often accuse each other of air and missile
attacks.
   Afghan guerrillas based in Pakistan have been fighting Kabul's
communist government for 10 years.
   On Nov. 21, Radio Kabul accused Pakistan of shooting down a
commercial plane that strayed into Pakistani airspace, killing all
27 people aboard.
   Pakistan acknowledged the incident, but identified the plane as a
military transport.
   Pakistan's air force has standing orders to shoot down intruding
Afghan military planes.
   Also on Monday, Radio Kabul said authorities responded to Turkish
appeals and freed two Turks jailed for entering Afghanistan
illegally with rebels.
   It said Turgut Osul and Ottoman Dimirial were released on Sunday.
   Osul was arrested four years ago and sentenced to 16 years.
Dimirial was arrested this year and sentenced to 20 years, the radio
said.
