<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmCrops     12-12 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Crops,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cotton Crop Expected To Hit Seven-Year High This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 cotton crop is expected to be at a
seven-year high of 15.2 million bales, up 3 percent from last year's
harvest and 2 percent more than forecast a month ago, the
Agriculture Department said Monday.
   In a new estimate based on field conditions as of Dec. 1, the
department's Agricultural Statistics Board said this year's cotton
production would be the largest since 15.6 million bales were
harvested in 1981.
   The report also indicated dry edible bean production this year at
19.1 million hundredweight, down 26 percent from last year, and
burley tobacco production at 459 million pounds, up 9 percent from
the 1987 harvest.
   Orange production, at 215 million boxes, is up 9 percent from
last season but about 1 percent shy of 1987-88 production.
   The report did not include new 1988 production figures for other
major crops such as wheat, corn and soybeans. An annual report on
this year's producton of those commodities will be issued Jan. 13.
   Planting of winter wheat for the 1989 harvest was 95 percent
completed by Nov. 1, about 5 percentage points ahead of average, the
report said. But lack of moisture hampered development in much of
the major growing areas.
   ``Near the end of the month, rain and snow provided needed
moisture in portions of the plains and Pacific Northwest,'' the
report said. ``Greenbugs continued to be a problem in Kansas and
Texas. In Texas, central and southern areas remained dry and showed
little or no growth.''
</TEXT>
