since August, when authorities launched a crackdown after 92
elephants were slaughtered in four months, the Kenya Times said.
   The Nairobi-based U.N. Environmental Program said Kenya's
elephant population has fallen by 85 percent in the past 15 years,
and less than 5,500 elephants remain in the Tsavo area.
   Experts blame the slaughter on an all-time high in ivory prices,
which average $82 a pound.
