<DOCNO> AP881212-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1930EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Amnesty     12-12 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More than Half UN Countries Have `Prisoners of Conscience'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half the countries in the United
Nations still hold ``prisoners of conscience'' 40 years after the
U.N. declaration of human rights, Amnesty International charged on
Monday.
   The United Nations now has 159 member states.
   ``Torture done with methods that equal anything the Nazis devised
is practiced systemically in more than one-third of the world's
nations,'' Deputy Director Curt Goering of Amnesty International
said.
   Goering, an American born in Kansas, said ``It is all systems of
government that are at fault. Dictatorships as well as democracies,
countries with military rule as well as civilian rule, countries
with free elections and countries with no elections.''
   He spoke to the Washington chapter of the United Nations
Association at a meeting to mark the 40th anniversary of the U.N.
Declaration of Human Rights on Dec. 10, 1948. Goering said the past
week had seen the discovery of graves of political prisoners in Iran
and, in Paraguay, dozens of people were arrested demonstrating for
human rights.
   ``Today in countries from South Africa to Vietnam, from Uganda to
Israel, thousands upon thousands of political prisoners languish,
uncharged and untried, in filthy and overcrowded prison cells, in
mountains and in deserts, beaten, humiliated and isolated,'' he said.
   He cited three specific cases:
   _Ali Ardalan, arrested in Iran in May for asking an end to the
war with Iraq, held incommunicado, whereabouts unknown. There has
been a cease-fire in the war since August.
   _Vazif Meylanov, 49 years old, arrested Jan. 25, 1980 and
imprisoned in the Soviet Union for demonstrating against the
internal exile of Andrei Sakharov. Sakharov was freed and recently
visited the United States.
   _Ma'ruf Abdullah Fatah, 27, arrested in Iraq on suspicion of
organizing a banned political party. Goering said Fatah tortured by
having his head enveloped in a hood filled with flying ants and went
insane.
   Goering denied that Amnesty, an international private
organization, has any ideological interest, saying it had been
called communist by the government of Guatemala and accused by the
communist government of Afghanistan of being in league with the
Voice of America.
   ``We frankly don't care whether the government is torturing
someone in the name of the revolution, or in the name of fighting
the revolution, or in the name of restoring order so that democracy
might flourish,'' he said.
   ``All we care about is that the torture stop.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
