<HEAD>First Vietnam-Era Medal of Honor Winner To Retire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army Col. Roger H.C. Donlon, the first
serviceman to win a Medal of Honor for valor during the Vietnam War,
will retire later this week after 32 years of military service, the
Pentagon announced Monday.
   Donlon was awarded the Medal of Honor by President Johnson during
a White House ceremony on Dec. 5, 1964, in recognition of his
bravery in repulsing a Viet Cong attack at Nam Dong on July 6, 1964.
   Donlon, who is the alternate-president of the Army's Physical
Evaluation Board at the Presidio of San Francisco, will retire
during ceremonies scheduled Wednesday morning at Fort Leavenworth,
Kan., the Pentagon said.
   ``He and his wife, Norma, will reside in Leavenworth,'' the
Pentagon added.
   Besides the Medal of Honor, Donlon also has won the Bronze Star,
the Meritorious Service Medal with two Oak Leaf Clusters, the Joint
Service Commendation Medal and a Purple Heart.
