<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CerealContents     12-12 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cereal Contents,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kellogg Takes Tropical Oil Out of Cracklin' Oat Bran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kellogg Co. said Monday it has stopped
using tropical oil in its Cracklin' Oat Bran cereal, eliminating an
unwanted dose of saturated fat for consumers who buy the cereal for
cholesterol-lowering bran.
   ``I'm elated,'' said Phil Sokolof, founder of National Heart
Savers, a Nebraska organization that has campaigned against products
which use tropical oils, such as palm and coconut.
   ``Thousands of ounces of coconut oil will no longer be clogging
the arteries of America'' as a result of Kellogg's action, he said.
   Oat bran helps keep down cholesterol, while saturated fat can
boost it. People who have high levels of cholesterol run a higher
risk of a clogging of the arteries that can lead to heart attacks.
   Joseph Stewart, senior vice president for Kellogg's corporate
affairs, told Sokolof in a letter that the company was taking
coconut oil out of the cereal. He said the new product will be on
grocery shelves within three months.
   Stewart said Monday that Kellogg had been working on a new
formula for Cracklin' Oat Bran because the cereal maker sensed
growing public sentiment against use of tropical oils.
   ``We don't want to lose it (consumer confidence) over confusion
about one product out of 40,'' he said, adding other Kellogg
products don't contain the tropical oils.
   Kellogg replaced the coconut oil in Cracklin' Oat Bran with a
combination of cottonseed and soybean oils that eliminates the
saturated fat content.
   In addition to Kellogg, Pepperidge Farm earlier said it was
taking tropical oil out of its breads with plans for removing it
from cookies, and Sunshine Biscuits Inc. said it was taking tropical
oils out of its cookie products, Sokolof said.
   Sokolof said coconut oil contains 100 percent more saturated fat
than lard.
   Coconut and palm oil are popular because they contribute to the
shelf life of food products, Sokolof said. Many products advertised
as being free of cholesterol contain tropical oils that can help
cholesterol form after consumption, he said.
   ``When they say `No cholesterol' on a product ... it may be fine,
but it may contain highly saturated palm and coconut oils,'' Sokolof
said.
   National Heart Savers plans $140,000 worth of ads Tuesday in the
Wall Street Journal and USA Today, citing other products it says are
high in palm and coconut oils.
   The products to be cited Tuesday are Nabisco Triscuit crackers
and striped Chips Ahoy cookies; Post Fruit & Fibre cereal;
Pepperidge Farm Goldfish crackers; Keebler Club crackers; Quaker
Chewy Granola Bars; Borden Cremora creamer; Carnation Coffeemate;
Birdseye Cool Whip topping; and Procter & Gamble Crisco. All but the
granola bars and Chips Ahoy cookies were cited previously, Sokolof
said.
   ``These are the ones that people eat and don't realize what
they're consuming,'' Sokolof said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0162 </DOCNO>
