<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1656EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Quake-Construction     12-12 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Construction,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pravda Recommends Criminal Charges Against Builders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges should be filed against the
``scrap-builders'' of shoddily constructed buildings deatroyed by
the earthquake that killed more than 50,000 people in Soviet
Armenia, Pravda said Monday.
   The Communist Party newspaper recommended the action in a
scathing artlcle about apartment buildings in the devastated region
that crumbled into ``concrete and metal graves over victims who were
buried alive.''
   ``In fragments of concrete panels, it is impossible to know
whether there is more sand or more cement,'' it said of the wreckage
in Leninakan, a city of 250,000 where more than three-quarters of
the buildings fell.
   ``It is time to answer the question, how many criminal cases were
filed against the scrap-builders and what was the outcome?'' Pravda
asked. ``Who closed their eyes to the warnings of the seismologists,
here and in other regions?''
   All construction in the Soviet Union is handled by government
agencies.
   American earthquake experts have said a quake of the same
strength would have killed only 1,000 people in heavily populated
Southern California because of the difference in building techniques.
   Concrete-slab apartment buildings were hastily built throughout
the Soviet Union in the past 20 years to ease a chronic housing
shortage.
   The Kremlin has sent a commission to Leninakan to determine why
so many buildings disintegrated in an area where where builders
supposedly used construction techniques designed to survive quakes.
Authorities have said the temblor last Wednesday was stronger than
expected in northwestern Armenia.
   Photos of the ruins show entire sections of high-rise residential
buildings sheared off, with no evidence of steel reinforcing bars at
stress points as required in Western countries.
   ``If the construction of the buildings was better, maybe less
would have been destroyed,'' Leonid Bibin, deputy chief of Soviet
construction, told a news briefing Monday.
   A broken slab on which was writtren ``This piece of concrete is
not to be used,'' lay in the rubble Monday in Leninakan. Short
supply is common in Soviet industry and workers often use the
defective or makeshift to finish projects.
   Bibin said the earth shook vertically during the quake, causing
buildings constructed of concrete slabs to collapse. He also said
the earth was soft in some areas.
   ``Why did buildings from three years ago collapse while those of
three or five stories built under (former leader Nikita) Khrushchev
are still standing?'' President Mikhail S. Gorbachev demanded on
television Sunday night.
   In Leninakan, older low-rise apartment blocks stood unscathed
while ``everything built in the years of stagnation collapsed,''
Pravda said, using the Soviet term for the regime of the late Leonid
I. Brezhnev.
   ``Geophysicists more than once warned builders of the high
seismic activity in northwest Armenia, but stubbornly they continued
to raise five- to nine-story buildings,'' the paper said.
   Acccording to Bibin, every building more than five stories high
collapsed.
   Kagik Avakyan, a resident of Leninakan, told The Associated Press
the city had no buildings taller than two stories until 20 years ago
because of the threat of earthquakes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
