<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-PLO     12-12 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-PLO,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Accuses Arafat of 10 Terror Acts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arafat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's highest ranking counterterrorism
official alleged on Monday that PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat had
direct involvement in 10 terror attacks in Israel and abroad.
   Yigal Carmon, special adviser on terrorism to Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir, told a news conference Arafat was involved through
``approval of plans, issuing orders and allocating the funds
necessary for the special operations.''
   ``There are other types of involvement, but I cannot specify,''
he added.
   The 10 acts Carmon listed ranged from the July 1987 assassination
in London of Palestinian cartoonist Naji al-Ali, known for his
anti-Arafat drawings, to the April 1986 bombing of a TWA jetliner
over Greece which killed four people.
   Carmon gave no specifics and would not say how Israeli officials
concluded Arafat was personally linked to the incidents.
   His remarks came at a government-sponsored briefing held to
counter claims by Arafat that the Palestine Liberation Organization
has accepted Israel and renounced the use of terrorism.
   A group of nine dovish Labor Party legislators published a
statement Monday saying they would endorse peace talks with the PLO
if the PLO followed up its acceptance of Israel with a renunciation
of terrorism.
   The statement appeared in leading newspapers and was seen as a
significant shift in the thinking of mainstream politicians.
Supporters included Yossi Beilin, a former senior aide to Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres.
   It said that ``prospects of opening negotiations with this
Palestinian leadership'' have been brought closer, but that
``without an unequivocal decision to renounce terror and stopping
it, there will be no negotiations.''
   The PLO condemned terror but said the organization will continue
armed operations in Israeli-held territory.
</TEXT>
