<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Shuttle-SanAntonio     12-12 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-San Antonio,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Atlantis Stops For Night In San Antonio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space shuttle Atlantis arrived here Monday
atop a modified jumbo jet for an overnight stay on its hopscotch
journey back to its Florida launch site.
   The shuttle, which arrived at Kelly Air Force Base at 2:30 p.m.
CST from Davis-Monthan Air Force Base near Tucson, Ariz., was to
continue its journey to the Kennedy Space Center at Cape Canaveral,
Fla., between 8 a.m. and 10 a.m. Tuesday, said Kelly spokeswoman
Phebe Brown.
   Atlantis, which returned last week from a classified military
mission, left Edwards Air Force Base in California at 3:27 p.m.
Sunday, carried piggypack atop a Boeing 747 and stopped for the
night at the Arizona base.
   Weather along much of Atlantis' route back to Florida has been
stormy, and National Aeronautics and Space Administration officials
are concerned that flying through rain could damage the thousands of
ceramic tiles on the shuttle's belly. The tiles ward off the extreme
heat of re-entry into the Earth's atmosphere.
   Ms. Brown said an air-conditioning, heating and filtering unit
was flown from Davis-Monthan and would be hooked to the shuttle for
its overnight stay in Texas. The unit maintains the temperature and
filters the air inside the orbiter, she said.
   Atlantis landed at Edwards after a four-day secret mission that
reportedly included deployment of a military spy satellite. It was
the second shuttle flight since missions resumed following the 1986
Challenger disaster, which claimed the lives of seven astronauts.
</TEXT>
