<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drugs-Quake     12-12 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Quake,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Drug Companies Mobilize To Send Supplies To Earthquake Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. drug companies, tutored by recent
disasters in the Caribbean, Mexico and Bangladesh, prepared Monday
to send antibiotics, bandages and other medical supplies to tens of
thousands of earthquake victims in Soviet Armenia.
   The manufacturers were working through a network of donor
churches, a Connecticut relief agency and their own foreign offices,
company officials said.
   The earthquake last week killed up to 60,000 people, leaving half
a million homeless and the threat of infection and disease.
   At Hoffmann-La Roche, where two regional sales managers are of
Armenian descent, the effort has taken on special meaning.
   ``It really brings it down to a personal level, knowing these
people have relatives there,'' said Kassy McGourty, a spokeswoman
for the Nutley-based pharmaceutical company.
   She said workers were preparing a tractor-trailer load of
antibiotics, enough to treat 2,000 to 3,000 people _ the company's
largest shipment ever.
   The drugs were to be routed by Interchurch Medical Assistance
Inc., a New Windsor, Md.-based umbrella group for church missions
and denominational relief agencies.
   ``We've had all these emergency shipments to the point where
we're down to the bottom of the barrel of supplies,'' said the
organization's associate director, Paul Maxey.
   IMA issued an urgent appeal to drug companies for Armenia after
this year's earthquake in Mexico City, floods in Bangladesh and a
hurricane in Jamaica, Maxey said.
   He said 107,000 pounds of medical supplies are ready to be
shipped.
   Johnson & Johnson sent $500,000 worth of sutures, disinfectants,
dressings, bandages and other products in a shipment Saturday sent
by AmeriCares Foundation Inc., a New Canaan, Conn.-based relief
agency, said Johnson & Johnson spokesman Ed Watson.
   Another load was due to leave Tuesday from Seattle with the
Seattle-King County Disaster Team. The shipment was enough to supply
four field hospitals for several days, Watson said.
   Lederle Laboratories, a division of American Cyanamid, is waiting
to hear from AmeriCares about when to forward antibiotics, said
spokesman Robert Schwadron in Wayne.
   ``We respond when these disasters take place,'' he said. ``You
have to. You have to be compassionate.''
   Spokeswoman Peggy Ballman at Princeton-based Squibb Corp. said
the company had decided to send supplies directly through its London
office. A meeting with Soviet health officials and the operations
director for Eastern Europe is scheduled for Wednesday, she said.
   On Sunday night, Merck & Co. Inc. of Rahway sent 1 million
penicillin tablets from its division in Montreal, said spokeswoman
Cindy Zarski. Merck planned to send 4,900 vials of surgical
antibiotics Tuesday evening, she said, and was prepared to send
1,000 vials of hepatitis antibodies if needed.
   Ron Asinari, a spokesman for Schering-Plough Corp. of Madison,
said the company was still developing plans for assistance.
</TEXT>
