<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NavyContract     12-12 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Contract,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florio Asks Probe of Navy Computer Contracting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key congressman said Monday he wants an
investigation into Navy computer contracts in the wake of a ruling
by a federal appeals board that specifications for a series of
contracts had favored International Business Machines Corp.
   ``In the next two years, Congress will play an important role in
the defense procurement question and with shrinking budgets, it is
important that we get the most for our defense dollars,'' said Rep.
James Florio, D-N.J.
   Florio is chairman of the Energy and Commerce consumer protection
subcommittee.
   Speaking by telephone from his New Jersey office, Florio said he
has asked the General Accounting Office to investigate in the wake
of last week's decision by the General Services Administration's
board of contract appeals.
   The board ruled in a case involving a $150 million computer
contract. IBM competitors had complained, charging that the Navy's
specifications for the contract unfairly favored the giant company.
   In the ruling, Judge Robert W. Parker concluded that the Navy
contract ``solicitation provides for less than full and open
competition and that the Navy has not properly justified such a
restriction on competition.''
   Telephone calls seeking comment were not returned Monday by Navy
officials.
   The case involves a Navy contract to purchase about 20 computer
systems for 14 different data centers and facilities. The 10-year
contract also includes training and technical support. The
specifications were issued more than a year ago.
   The Navy argued that using a single contractor would have
technical and administrative advantages and suggested that using
more than one source would mean non-compatible computers.
   The protest to the GSA board was filed by PacifiCorp. Inc. of
McLean, Va., one of the companies seeking to bid.
   Florio said he wanted the GAO, the congressional watchdog agency,
``to investigate the process under which the Navy has apparently
violated federal procurement rules.''
</TEXT>
