<1ST_LINE>u p AM-IndianaSenator 1stLd-Writethru a0700 12-12 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indiana Senator, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0700,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rep. Dan Coats, a Former Aide, Gets Quayle's Senate Seat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates thruout with Coats, Quayle, Lugar news conference</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Coats, who got his start in politics
as an aide to Dan Quayle, was named Monday to take the vice
president-elect's seat in the Senate.
   ``I believe in providence,'' said Coats, the Indiana Republican
who had succeeded his boss in the House eight years earlier when
Quayle moved up to the Senate.
   Coats, 45, had won re-election to a fifth House term on Nov. 8,
the same day Quayle won the vice presidency as George Bush's running
mate.
   Indiana Gov. Robert Orr announced Coats' name at a news
conference in Indianapolis, saying he ``represents values near and
dear to the people of Indiana.''
   Quayle, appearing with Coats on Capitol Hill, praised the
Republican congressman as a dedicated family man and trusted friend.
But he turned aside suggestions that Coats was his hand-picked
successor.
   ``This was a one-man vote. The governor made the decision. ... I
did not make any specific recommendation,'' Quayle said.
   Coats thanked Quayle, Orr, and Indiana's senior senator,
Republican Richard Lugar, for their support and promised great
efforts on behalf of his Indiana constituents.
   ``I realize I'm not their elected senator. I'm their appointed
senator. I hope over the next two years to work my very hardest to
earn their respect and support,'' he said.
   He will serve until a special election in 1990, when voters will
decide whether he or someone else should fill the last two years of
Quayle's term. An election for a full six-year Senate term will be
in 1992.
   In response to a reporter's question about the coincidence of
twice following Quayle into elected posts, Coats replied, ``I
believe in providence, rather than fate. However that House seat was
a hotly contested seat in 1980 ... I hope that I earned that seat in
1980 and in the subsequent eight years demonstrated my ability to do
the job.''
   He had worked in Quayle's congressional office in Fort Wayne,
Ind., from 1976 to 1980.
   Orr said Coats had ``the ability, the intellect, the character
and the temperament to be an outstanding United States senator,'' a
thought echoed by Lugar.
   ``He is a remarkable legislator, a remarkable campaigner, but
even more importantly, a decent human being,'' Lugar said.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole issued a statement welcoming
Coats to the Senate and saying he was confident Coats would
``continue to represent the people of Indiana with vigor and
commmitment to their heartland values.''
   In the House, the low-key Coats has compiled a conservative
record that drew an 82 percent approval rating in 1986 from the
American Conservative Union.
   He is a supporter of aid to the Nicaraguan Contras and to the
Angolan rebels. In 1984, he attempted to attach to an education bill
an amendment to cut off federal aid to schools and states banning
voluntary school prayer. The amendment was defeated.
   In selecting Coats, Orr cited his ``very fine electoral record''
in five House elections and an ability to build a strong base to
withstand a Democratic challenge. Coats has never received less than
61 percent of the vote in his northeastern Indiana district. Last
month he won re-election with 62 percent.
   His selection makes no change in the Democratic-Republican split
in the Senate, where Democrats hold a 55-45 majority in the new
Congress.
   Quayle has announced he will resign, probably effective Jan. 2,
to allow his successor to gain seniority by being sworn in before
the rest of the Senate on Jan. 3. However, Coats said he expected to
be sworn in with the rest of the Senate.
   Several other names had been mentioned as potential candidates
for Quayle's seat, including former White House political director
Mitchell Daniels and Quayle's wife, Marilyn. Both took themselves
out of contention several weeks ago.
   Quayle said his wife was ``very gratified'' with Orr's decision.
   Coats was born in Jackson, Mich., graduated from Wheaton College
and then served in the Army. Like Quayle, he got his law degree at
Indiana University in Indianapolis.
   He worked as assistant vice president and legal counsel for
Mutual Security Life Insurance Co. before going to work for
then-Rep. Quayle.
 
</TEXT>
