<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MexicanAmbassador     12-12 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexican Ambassador,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Names Top Economist As Ambassador To Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari chose his
predecessor's treasury secretary as ambassador to Washington on
Monday, another sign of his desire to alter the terms of Mexico's
huge foreign debt.
   An announcement from the Foreign Ministry said Gustavo
Petriccioli, who has a master's degree in economics from Yale, will
replace Jorge Espinosa de los Reyes.
   Salinas, who began his six-year term Dec. 1, has said
renegotiating terms of the $102 billion foreign debt leads his
priority list, and he discussed it with President-elect George Bush
at their meeting in Houston last month.
   As Treasury Secretary for the last two years of de la Madrid's
term, Petriccioli sought a postponement of debt payments because of
the financial squeeze caused by the collapse of world oil prices in
the early 1980s.
   He negotiated an an agreement with creditor banks signed March
21, 1987, that included $7.7 billion in new loans, restructured
$43.7 billion of the debt and decreased interest rates on $8.6
billion loaned in 1983-84.
   Petriccioli, 60, also worked out Mexico's purchase of several
billion dollars worth of its foreign debt certificates at discount
rates this year and helped enforce a ``solidarity pact'' of
government, business and labor that helped lower annual inflation
from 150.9 percent in 1987 to about 48 percent in 1988.
   By keeping interest rates high and the peso's value virtually
steady against the dollar, Petriccioli also managed to accumulate an
all-time record of $16 billion in foreign currency reserves last
year.
   Salinas has promised to lighten the burden of austerity economics
on average Mexicans, whose real wages have been cut in half during
the past six years.
   Salinas has noted Mexico's economic growth remained near zero
during that period and said renegotiating debt payments is vital to
provide money for industrial development.
   Foreign creditors have balked at Mexico's proposals to reduce the
$13 billion it is paying in debt service this year. Debt service
payments for next year are estimated at $16 billion.
</TEXT>
