<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Chairman,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wiener Gets Western Backing for DNC Chairmanship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan Democratic chairman Richard Wiener
picked up endorsements from 13 party leaders from Western states on
Monday in his bid to win election as Democratic national chairman.
   Wiener was backed by state chairmen from California, Oregon,
Arizona, Utah, Wyoming, Montana, Idaho and Nevada, as well as
several vice chairmen.
   ``We believe that our next national chair must be a proven party
builder and mount broad support throughout the Western part of the
United States _ a region where we have great potential to expand our
Democratic base over the next four years,'' the officials said in a
statement.
   The endorsements reflect a natural base for Wiener, outgoing
chairman of the Association of Democratic State Chairs.
   Wiener announced his support as former Oklahoma Rep. Jim Jones
spread the word he would make an announcement Wednesday about the
race to succeed outgoing party chairman Paul Kirk. Jones, a
Washington lawyer, said last week he was considering running.
   Other contenders include Ronald H. Brown, who claims the support
of roughly 60 percent of the votes needed to win election at the
Democratic National Committee meeting Feb. 9 and 10. Brown, a
longtime party activist who was convention manager for Democratic
presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson last summer, was endorsed last
week by Massachusetts Sen. Edward M. Kennedy.
   Former Reps. Michael Barnes of Maryland and James Stanton of Ohio
are other contenders.
