<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Wainwright     12-12 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Wainwright,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Loudon Wainwright, Life Magazine Columnist, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalist Loudon Snowden Wainwright, who wrote
Life magazine's ``The View From Here'' column and chronicled the
magazine's history in a 1986 book, died Monday of cancer at age 63.
   After serving in the Marines and graduating from college,
Wainwright joined Life in 1949 as an office boy. In the 1950s he
distinguished himself as a reporter, correspondent, bureau chief and
staff writer.
   He was later known for his close relationship with the Mercury
astronauts and wrote their personal accounts of their missions for
Life.
   Wainwright started ``The View From Here,'' the magazine's first
personal column, in 1964 and, despite interruptions, was writing it
up until his death.
   In 1969, Wainwright was named Life's assistant managing editor
and held that position until the weekly ceased publication at the
end of 1972. He rejoined the writing staff for Life's revival as a
monthly in 1978.
   In 1986, Knopf published Wainwright's ``The Great American
Magazine,'' which tells the history of Life from an insider's
viewpoint.
   A memorial will be held in January.
   Wainwright is survived by his wife Martha, from whom he has been
separated for more than a decade, and their four children. A son,
Loudon Wainwright III of New York City, is a well-known folk-rock
singer and songwriter.
   He is also survived by his longtime companion, Martha Fay, and
their 6-year-old daughter.
</TEXT>
