<DOCNO> AP881212-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1735EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Arafat     12-12 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Arafat,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Renews Appeal To Arafat To Renounce Terrorism, Accept Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration renewed its offer
Monday of a ``substantive dialogue'' if Yasser Arafat, the chairman
of the Palestine Liberation Organization, explictly recognized
Israel and renounced terrorism.
   The offer was made by the State Department on the eve of Arafat's
arrival in Geneva for a U.N. General Assembly debate on the conflict
between Israel and Palestinian Arabs. The session was shifted to the
Swiss city after Secretary of State George P. Shultz blocked a visa
for Arafat to speak in New York.
   Shultz cited the PLO's terrorism record and called Arafat an
``accessory.'' He invoked a U.S. law denying entry to terrorists as
superseding a U.S. agreement with the United Nations to facilitate
travel for foreigners to attend U.N. sessions.
   At the same time, though, Shultz called Palestinian participation
in any Mideast peace talks essential. He also invited Arafat to
agree to three U.S. requirements that must be met before the
administration will hold diplomatic talks.
   These are: acceptance of U.N. resolutions 242 and 338, adopted by
the Security Council in 1967 and 1973; recognition of Israel's right
to exist; and renunciation of terrorism.
   The two resolutions implicitly recognized Israel's right to exist
within secure boundaries. The Palestine National Council, the
legislative arm of the PLO, last month approved holding Mideast
negotiations within the framework of the resolutions but did not
accept the resolutions directly.
   In another move, the council edged away from advocating
terrorism, but L. Paul Bremer, who directs the State Department's
office of counterterrorism, said it did not amount to renouncing
terrorism. Bremer referred to a reaffirmation of Palestinians' right
``to resist the Israeli occupation of their land in any way
possible.''
   And the PLO group did not directly recognize Israel.
   ``We've put forward some very clear-cut requirements, which are
necessary to satisfy to enter into a substantive dialogue with the
PLO,'' Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said. ``We
look forward to the day when they'll do that, step up to bat.''
   The U.S. official called the three requirements ``a set of
criteria'' and said ``when those criteria are satisfied ... when
those conditions are met, we are prepared to engage in a substantive
dialogue.''
   Still, Redman left unclear whether the United States would
immediately deal with the PLO if Arafat met the three U.S.
conditions in Geneva.
   ``I don't want to predict what will happen,'' he said. ``We have
to make a judgment when and if those three things are addressed.
That judgment I can't make in the abstract.''
   U.S. policy on the Mideast has not changed, Redman said.
   The main aim is direct negotiations between Israel and the Arabs,
including Palestinians, on an overall peace settlement. Holding an
international peace conference as a backdrop for such talks would be
considered, the U.S. official said.
   Redman said Vernon A. Walters, the U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, would represent the United States in the Geneva debate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
