<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 2045EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FamilyKilling     12-12 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Family Killing,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Now Says He Lied About Child-Poisoning Confession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARCADIA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last surviving witness to the alleged
jailhouse confession of a farmworker in the poisoning of his seven
children more than 20 years ago has recanted his testimony, a
newspaper reported Monday.
   James Richardson was convicted for one of the 1967 killings and
sentenced to life, accused of putting the deadly insecticide
parathion in a lunch a baby sitter served his children, age 2 to 8.
   Now, a cellmate who testified to a jailhouse confession says it
never happened, The Miami Herald reported Monday.
   ``I didn't hear Richardson say anything while I was in there,''
James Weaver, 67, told the Florida Department of Law Enforcement, a
statement he later repeated to The Herald, the newspaper said.
   ``I ain't never heard the boy say anything about it. I hope
Richardson will get out. I want him to get out.''
   Weaver did not explain to state investigators or the newspaper
why he may have lied at the trial, saying he could not recall the
details of his testimony.
   The admission may lend additional impetus to a movement to spring
Richardson from prison.
   The department of law enforcement, already investigating the case
at the request of Gov. Bob Martinez, is expected to submit its final
report to the governor this week.
   ``We are examining it now, and have been for the past number of
weeks and the governor is actively considering reviewing it on a
more formal basis,'' Brian Ballard, Martinez's director of
operations, said Monday.
   He noted that the governor can call for a clemency hearing. ``He
hasn't made that decision yet. He will be briefed on it probably
this week.''
   Richardson's lawyers had said earlier they plan to file a
petition for a new trial Thursday.
   ``I think this Weaver thing is going to put the icing on the
cake,'' John Spencer Robinson of Arcadia, who defended Richardson at
trial and initially appealed the case, said Monday.
   Some of the most damaging testimony against Richardson at his
1968 trial came from Weaver and another felon, James Dean Cuningham,
both of whom alleged that the 32-year-old fruit picker had
remorsefully and repeatedly confessed in his cell while awaiting
trial.
   A third convict died before trial, but his similar account was
read into the record. Cunningham was shot to death in 1979. No one
has been arrested in that case.
   Weaver's recantation is the latest in a series of developments to
cast doubt on Richardson's conviction, his lawyers say.
   The first came earlier this year when it was reported that the
former baby sitter, Betsy Reese, now 67, told nurses in a nursing
home in 1985 that she had poisoned the children.
   And last week, Arcadia's former chief of police, Richard Barnard,
swore he believes Richardson was ``framed'' by then-DeSoto County
Sheriff Frank Cline.
   Barnard said that Weaver and Cunningham were ``handpicked''
informants testifying in return for lenient sentences.
   They ``would have done or said anything that Frank Cline asked
them to do, including making false statements under oath.''
   Cline denied Barnard's allegation. And prosecutors say the baby
sitter, who is immobile and has lapsed into utter silence, became
confused over the years because she had innocently served a poisoned
meal.
   Richardson's new attorneys, Ellis Rubin of Miami and Mark Lane of
Washington, said they will file an appeal to the state Supreme Court
and to the trial court, charging that the state knowingly used
perjured testimony.
   ``I want a jury to hear that he was framed, and to bring out the
perjury on the record,'' Rubin told The Herald.
   Richardson, now 52, is at the Tomoka Correctional Institution in
Daytona Beach, where he will be eligible for parole in 1993.
</TEXT>
