<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HolocaustEducation     12-12 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holocaust Education,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Ask Cavazos to Free Money for Course</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of congressmen asked Education
Secretary Lauro Cavazos on Monday to approve $70,000 to disseminate
a Holocaust education program for which the Reagan administration
previously blocked funding.
   The letter, written by Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., and signed by 65
colleagues, said the course, ``Facing Ourselves and History,'' has
been taught by 1,000 teachers, has rated at or near the top of its
application category and received strong recommendations for
approval from Education Department staff aides.
   Despite these factors, the letter said, money for the program was
denied in 1986, 1987 and 1988, at least partially on the basis of
biased peer reviews. One concluded that ``the Nazi point of view,
however unpopular, is still a point of view and is not presented,
nor is that of the Ku Klux Klan.''
   The official who denied the funding, Shirley Curry, was removed
from her job two days before Weiss' Government Operations
subcommittee on human resources held a hearing on the matter in
October.
   The bipartisan group of House members said all evidence indicates
``Facing History'' is an excellent program and should be distributed
to all schools that want to use it. They asked Cavazos to review the
department's past actions and use his discretionary authority to
release money for it.

</TEXT>
