<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Emperor     12-12 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emperor,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito's Condition Unstable, Bleeding Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors reported Emperor Hirohito's condition was
unstable Monday as he continued to bleed internally and his blood
pressure fluctuated, palace officials said.
   The 87-year-old monarch received a transfusion of nearly a pint,
which helped raise his systolic blood pressure to 104, up from 71 in
the morning, Imperial Household Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda said.
The average reading is about 120.
   ``His condition cannot be described as stable,''Maeda quoted
doctors as saying.
   Hirohito, who has been bedridden since he started to bleed from
his intestine Sept. 19, lost considerable amounts of blood last
week. Doctors have said an intestinal blockage has forced some of
the blood into the abdomen.
   A palace official said on condition of anonymity that doctors
were draining the blood from Hirohito's abdomen ``because there is
the fear that his breathing could be affected by the (buildup of
blood).''
   ``The functioning of each internal organ has more or less
declined in the wake of the bleeding'' last week, Maeda told
reporters.
   The emperor slept most of the day Monday, but he at times has
shown signs of consciousness, Maeda said. Media reports said
Hirohito was in a semi-coma.
   ``His overall condition is gradually weakening, but there has
been no sudden change,'' said the palace official.
   The emperor has no political power but serves as a symbol of the
unity of Japan.
</TEXT>
