<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-US-Jews     12-12 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-US-Jews,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Switch, U.S. Turning Away Many Soviet Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is denying refugee status to large
numbers of Soviet Jews at the main American processing point for
Soviet emigres, Jewish officials say.
   The Rome center has refused 201 refugees in the past three
months, said Ernest Berger, European director for the Hebrew
Immigrant Aid Society.
   U.S. immigration officials blame a sharp jump in the number of
Soviet Jews permitted to leave their country _ more than the Soviet
refugee slots set by the United States.
   Their rejections have stunned Soviet Jews who are being
temporarily housed in the seaside town of Ladispoli near Rome.
   ``It's awful. We are all in shock,'' said Eugene Shpaeyr, 31, a
biologist who came from Riga this fall with his wife and two
children.
   The overwhelming number of Soviet Jews still are granted U.S.
refugee status, U.S. and Jewish officials say. And those rejected
may appeal or apply for public interest parole. The latter program
differs from the refugee program in that emigrants must pay their
own transport to the United States, cannot claim welfare and must be
sponsored by a relative or friend.
   Most Soviet Jews do not want the parole, since it does not allow
them to become U.S. citizens or permanent residents, said Berger.
   The Jews also can move to Israel, he said in a telephone
interview from Geneva.
   A spokesman for the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
in Washington said Soviet Jews used to get refugee status almost
automatically.
   ``Now there are more people than funded positions,'' he said on
condition of anonymity. ``You're going to take those who ... present
the best cases of persecution. You're going to take those in a more
precarious position.''
   Serge Liberman, 29, an engineer from Leningrad who came to Italy
in September with his mother, argues Jews still are attacked.
   ``We were afraid for our lives,'' he said.
   Like most rejected Jews, Liberman is appealing his case.
   ``It seems strange for all the refuseniks,'' he said. ``We don't
understand what is the difference between us and those who got
refugee status. All of us suffered persecution because we were
Jews.''
   Berger also said the rejections seemed arbitrary.
   ``That's possible,'' the immigration spokesman said. ``But
previously we were not faced with having more applicants than slots
available.''
   Berger said the number of Soviet emigrants arriving in Rome grew
from 2,700 in November to 1,500 in the first two weeks of December
alone.
   The United States has agreed to accept 24,500 refugees from
Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union in fiscal 1989, which began on
Oct. 1.
   Although the number is higher than last year's 18,000 slots, it
apparently will not meet demand. The 3,000 slots designated for
Soviet refugees in the first quarter of the year were filled by Oct.
31, the immigration spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
