<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Higgins     12-12 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Higgins,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Calls Hostage Judgment `Grotesque'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday denounced the
kidnappers of U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins for a
``grotesque'' assertion that he had been tried and sentenced to
death.
   Spokeswoman Nancy Beck also dismissed their accusation that
Higgins had spied for Israel as ``nonsense.'' She said the
kidnappers would be held ``fully responsible'' for the American
officer's safety and welfare.
   The pro-Iranian group holding Higgins said in a statement in
Beirut that he would be executed. ``The spy has been turned over to
those responsible for executing this just and revolutionary
verdict,'' said the statement delivered to the Beirut newspaper
An-Nahar.
   A photocopy of a photograph purporting to show Higgins in a dark
sweater was pasted to the bottom of the 15-line statement. Captors
of foreigners in Lebanon usually provide a photograph to
authenticate their statements.
   Higgins, 43, of Danville, Ky., was head of a 76-man observer
group attached to the U.N. peacekeeping force in south Lebanon when
he was kidnapped near the southern port city of Tyre on Feb. 17.
   Spokeswoman Beck, in behalf of the State Department, called upon
the hostage-takers ``and those with influence over them to release
immediately and unconditionally Col. Higgins and all other hostages
in accordance with universal humanitarian obligations.''
   According to State Department records, nine Americans, three
Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and a Belgian are held hostage in
Lebanon.
   Ms. Beck said ``the notion that kidnappers have the right to try
their victims is grotesque. The rendering a judgment of those who
have committed a criminal act is a perversion of civilized concepts
of justice. The so-called trial and outcome represent a cyncial
attempt to exploit toe holding of hostages, particularly during the
Christmas seasnon.''
   The U.S. statement added: ``The charge that Col. Higgins is a spy
is nonsense.''
   It also noted that Higgins was in Lebanon as a member of the
United Nations Treaty Supervision Organization, which had just won
the Nobel Peace Prize when he was abducted.
</TEXT>
