<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Quake-WorldAid     12-12 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-World Aid,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Sends Everything From Trained Dogs to Tea for Quake Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF DONN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   To succor the wretched of Armenia's earthquake, each did what he
could Monday: Alaska sent dogs to sniff out the trapped, Kenya sent
tea to warm the chilled, and a U.S. millionaire personally delivered
a $1 million check.
   Sometimes, their efforts went heartbreakingly awry.
   Before dawn Monday, a Yugoslav military plane crashed while
trying to land at Yerevan airport with medical supplies. All seven
crewmembers aboard were killed, officials said.
   It was the second crash of a relief aircraft in two days. On
Sunday, a Soviet military transport plane went down near Leninaken's
airport, killing 78 people.
   Despite Monday's new disaster, Yugoslavia was preparing to send
another plane soon to help the victims of Wednesday's quake, the
official Soviet news agency Tass said.
   In Juneau, Ala., two dogs, their handlers and an official from
Southeast Alaska Dogs Organized for Ground Search planned to take a
flight Monday to Seattle, Wash., pick up doctors and medical
supplies there, and fly on to Armenia.
   ``The dogs that are over there are wearing out and they need
fresh dogs,'' said Gov. Steve Cowper's press secretary, David
Ramseur.
   In Washington, officials said U.S. private and public donations
to Soviet earthquake relief efforts reached $3.2 million Monday.
First Lady Nancy Reagan said she and President Reagan planned on
making their own contribution.
   The State Department said the total international relief effort
as of Monday was $26.1 million.
   Officials said Armand Hammer, chief of Occidental Petroleum and a
frequent visitor to the Soviet Union, hand-delivered a $1 million
check to Moscow.
   The international drive has mobilized an estimated 40 countries,
which have contributed help in the form of doctors, medicine, food,
blankets, tents, and heavy equipment to move debris.
   In Moscow, Council of Ministers spokesman Lev Voznesensky said 38
relief planes have arrived from abroad. He and other officials said
923 specialists from abroad with 216 search dogs were working in the
disaster area.
   In Nairobi, President Daniel arap Moi of Kenya said Monday that
his country will donate tea leaves for the victims. He did not say
how much.
   ``We in Kenya can't do much to help the victims of the
earthquake,'' he said. ``But we will send them some tea to drink. It
is very cold there.''
   Sometimes, the international efforts lacked coordination.
   Two Israeli air force planes with supplies for Armenia's victims
turned around and flew back home Monday because an Israeli already
at their destination told them they were not needed there, officials
said. They were in Tel Aviv awaiting a new relief assignment
elsewhere in the region.
   The reports of the devastation continued to touch people's heart
around the world, especially those of ethnic Armenians.
   The Armenian community on the Mediterranean island of Cyprus
donated money, food and clothing Monday. Officials said about
$50,000 had been collected.
   An Armenian priest tearfully embraced an 8-year-old boy as he
dropped the equivalent of $20 from his piggy bank on the priest's
desk.
   China's Red Cross relief organization said it planned to send
relief supplies, according to the Xinhua News Agency.
   It was believed to be the first time China has offered emergency
help to the Soviet Union, a former ally with whom political
relations have been strained for nearly three decades.
   Other communist and socialist nations, including Cuba and
Nicaragua, rushed to send help, reports said.
   Turkey will send 20 helicopters to help with relief efforts, a
foreign ministry official in Ankara said Monday.
   The quake also shook Turkey's eastern province of Kars on the
Soviet border, killing four and leveling 200 homes.
   Turkey's efforts to help Armenians also come against a backdrop
of longstanding hatred between the two peoples. Many Armenians still
blame Turkey for a genocide in 1915 that is said to have killed 1.5
million Armenians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
