<2ND_LINE>AM-Walesa, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0698,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Says Solidarity Ready for Talks with Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE Walesa back in Warsaw. Pick up
6th pvs, `There is...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa said Monday his outlawed union
Solidarity is ready to compromise for talks with Polish authorities
and will strike only as a last resort.
   ``We are ready for agreement and compromise ... but we should be
considered as free and independent,'' he told a news conference
before ending a four-day visit to France. ``We are even ready to
talk to the devil and consider that hell exists on condition that he
recognize there is a heaven.''
   About 200 cheering supporters at the Warsaw airport chanted
``Bravo, Lech!'' to welcome the founder of Solidarity back from the
first trip abroad Polish authorities have let him take since 1981.
   An impromptu reception committee made up of prominent Solidarity
activists, fellow passengers and Solidarity members sang ``Sto Lat''
for Walesa as he emerged from customs. The song is Poland's
equivalent of ``For He's a Jolly Good Fellow,'' and says, ``May he
live one hundred years.''
   Supporters thrust flowers into Walesa's hands and police cleared
a path through the crowd of photographers.
   Walesa said in Paris that permission to make the trip indicated a
changing government attitude toward reform.
   ``There is a process that we want to speed up and the fact that
we are here is evidence of a quickening,'' he said.
   After two waves of strikes earlier this year, the Polish
government offered negotiations to include the government, church
and opposition.
   The talks reached an impasse after the government refused to
legalize Solidarity, which was founded in 1980, crushed during
martial law in 1981 and outlawed in 1982. Solidarity is demanding
the government at least signal it will consider legalization before
the union will join talks.
   The talks were necessary, ``but on the condition we are
considered free and independent,'' said Walesa, who won the 1983
Nobel Peace Prize for creating the first independent trade
federation in a communist state.
   He said the union should continue struggling to improve the lives
of its members, but must do so without destroying the country.
   ``Poland doesn't need any more strikes right now. Strikes are a
last resort, an ultimate weapon which can ricochet and hurt
society,'' Walesa said.
   He said he had high hopes for Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's attempts to reform the Soviet system.
   The change in Soviet society ``is a process that does not bring
immediate results. It takes time to change the way people think,''
Walesa said, adding he did not wish to jeopardize Gorbachev's
reforms.
   Surrounded by representatives from most of France's trade unions
and Polish emigres sporting Solidarity pins, the Polish trade
unionist was ebullient, thanking President Francois Mitterrand for
inviting him to attend ceremonies Saturday marking the 40th
anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
   On Nov. 30, Walesa debated the chief of Poland's communist-backed
official union in a live TV broadcast that was the first time since
1983 that he has appeared on Polish television.
   ``Poland needs peace and pluralism. There is a place for both
(Prime Minister Mieczyslaw) Rakowski and Solidarity,'' he said
Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0187 </DOCNO>
