<2ND_LINE>AM-SKorea-Politics,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Presses For Arrest Of Chun, Protests Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders insisted Monday that
President Roh Tae-woo Roh take firm action against his predecessor,
Chun Doo-hwan, and ignored government attempts to calm public anger
over Chun's repressive rule. Radical students and dissidents
protested in Seoul and other cities against Chun, who last month
made a televised apology for misdeeds during eight years of military
rule that ended last February.
   ``Arrest Chun Doo-hwan, Down with Roh Tae-woo!'' about 40
protesters shouted when police blocked their march near a Buddhist
temple in which Chun lives.
   Monday marked the anniversary of Chun's seizure of power Dec. 12,
1979. Roh, then a general, sent troops into Seoul to support Chun.
   In Seoul on Monday, hundreds of radical students armed with
firebombs battled riot police at two universities, the news agency
Yonhap said. It reported peaceful street protests in Taegu, Kwangju
and Kongju.
   Police arrested 20 protesters in the central city of Taejon,
where scores of dissidents shattered windows at the prosecutor's
office.
   Roh, who won the presidential election a year ago, has opposed
punishing Chun. The president asked the nation to forgive his
predecessor but the opposition demanded Chun be forced to testify
before National Assembly committees investigating the actions of his
government.
   Chun has denied personal wrongdoing but some associates and
relatives have been convicted of corruption.
   Opposition parties led by Kim Young-sam and Kim Dae-jung have
urged Roh to arrest aides to Chun who are linked to alleged human
rights abuses.
   Kim Young-sam said the government's lukewarm attitude toward
removing legacies of the Chun era was forcing him to make a decision
on ``the fate of the Roh regime'' and its commitment to democracy.
   Roh has promised to end ties with the old government as part of
promised reforms.
</TEXT>
