<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     12-12 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militansts Order Newspapers Not To Report Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government militants Monday
ordered newspapers not to print anything about next week's
presidential election, said a spokesman for the four major
publishing companies.
   Leaflets written in Sinhalese were delivered the People's
Liberation Front, an extremist Sinhalese group that urged a boycott
of the Dec. 19 balloting, said the spokesman, who insisted on
anonymity. The front opposes peace overtures to minority Tamils and
demands the resignation of President Junius R. Jayewardene.
   The state-owned Lake House Group and the three independent
companies _ the Independent Newspapers, the Upali Group and Express
Newspapers _ will defy the orders, the spokesman said. They publish
12 dailies in English, Sinhalese and Tamil, and 11 weekend
newspapers, with a total circulation of 275,000.
   Anyone who violates the orders will be treated as a and ``dealt
with appropriately,'' the leaflets said.
   They were signed by by Kirthibahu Wijesinghe, widely believed to
be the commander of the Patriotic People's Movement, the military
arm of the Marxist front. The group has vowed to kill anyone who
supports the government's peace efforts.
   On Sunday night, assailants suspected of being Sinhalese
militants fatally shot or stabbed eight Sinhalese to death in
Thaniyana village, about 60 miles south of Colombo, said military
officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   Victims included the two teen-age daughters of former village
leader Maliyawadu Somatunga, a member of the governing United
National Party, officials said. His wife was critically injured,
they said.
   Officials said 18 other Sinhalese were killed since Sunday in
separate incidents in the south, the Sinhalese heartland.
   The front opposes government efforts to end the 5-year-old
insurgency by Tamil rebels who demanding a separate homeland in the
northern and eastern provinces. Nearly 10,000 people have been
killewd since fighting began in 1983.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of the island's 16 million people and
Sinhalese are 75 percen, with control of the government and military.
</TEXT>
