<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     12-12 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity, Government Speak Out on Eve of Crackdown Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity condemned anti-government
violence and the government defended the past use of martial law
Monday, the eve of the seventh anniversary of a crackdown on the
independent labor movement.
   Also Monday, about 200 steel workers at the Nowa Huta steel mill
near Krakow went on strike, said Solidarity activist Stanislaw
Handzlik.
   He said by telephone from the area that the workers are demanding
a 50 percent pay increase. The plant has been a center of strikes
directed by the banned Solidarity movement.
   Solidarity, which the government repressed when it imposed
martial law seven years ago and banned in 1982, denounced the
stoning of a Gdansk police station by about 300 young people.
   ``In connection with this incident, we want to recall the
fundamental principle of Solidarity, which is struggle without
violence,'' union spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said in a statement
from Warsaw.
   A group of people, mostly teen-agers, marched to a police station
Sunday threw stones at it, breaking most of its windows. Riot police
chased away the attackers without reported arrests.
   The Solidarity statement did not say how closely the marchers
were connected with the group. But a Solidarity spokeswoman in
Gdansk, Joanna Wojciechowicz, said older activists had tried to
dissuade the younger marchers without success.
   The Solidarity official in Warsaw said riot police often use
``shockingly brutal means'' against demonstrators and that many
young people have grown up in the violate climate.
   But he added: ``Polish society as a whole does not give in to
such a climate, and that is what determines our strength. Solidarity
cannot answer violence with violence.''
   Solidarity's leader, Lech Walesa, won the Nobel Peace Prize in
1983. He returned to Warsaw on Monday after a visit to France, his
first trip outside the country since 1981.
   A government communique defended Polish leader Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski's decision to impose martial law seven years ago, saying
it ``helped to prevent national catastrophe.''
   The statement was carried Monday by the official PAP news agency.
   On Dec. 13, 1981, suppressed Solidarity and detained thousands of
its faithful, including Walesa. Nine coal miners were killed by
security forces during the crackdown, called the ``state of war'' in
Polish.
   ``Dictated by a supreme necessity, the events ... did not stop
the process of democratization and broad reforms,'' the statement
said.
   ``Under conditions of order, not anarchy, businesslike
discussion, not sterile disputes, the sense of socialist renewal was
restored.''
   Government officials have argued that Solidarity in the early 80s
spearheaded activities that threatened the authority of the
Communist Party and might have prompted a Soviet invasion.
</TEXT>
