<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChicagoSchools     12-12 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Schools,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor OKs Plan for Overhaul of Chicago Public Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. James R. Thompson signed into law Monday a
bill calling for a sweeping overhaul of Chicago's school system,
which former federal Education Secretary William Bennett once
labeled the ``worst in the nation.''
   Thompson signed the bill after a symbolic walk from a
105-year-old school that is closing to the gymnasium of a new $4.6
million school on Chicago's West Side. The legislation, he said, was
``an important first step.''
   ``Parents and other community members have been given
unprecedented opportunities with this bill to control their local
school systems,'' the governor said in a statement.
   The much-debated measure, which takes effect in July, calls for a
shift of authority from the school system's central bureaucracy to
parents and principals in each of its 592 schools.
   It removes incumbent members of the Chicago Board of Education
and calls for the mayor to appoint a new board whose nominees are
suggested by a grass-roots screening committee.
   The legislation also establishes local councils made up of
parents, teachers and community residents. The councils _ one for
each school _ will have power to hire and fire principals, draft
plans for improvements and exercise some control over spending.
   School principals will lose tenure and work under four-year
contracts to be renewed on the basis of performance. They also will
have increased authority to fill teaching vacancies.
   ``While no law can ensure that our students will do better in the
classroom, this legislation will provide a more direct and
meaningful system that will be accountable for the education of our
children,'' Thompson said.
   The old school where the march to the signing ceremoney began
Monday was built in 1883. It is to be razed to make more room for a
high-tech research development.
   Thompson and Chicago Mayor Eugene Sawyer led a procession of
students carrying blue and gold balloons from the old school to the
new. They joined school board officials in cutting a ribbon at the
new school. Before the students entered the building, they let their
balloons float skyward.
   The reform movement that provided impetus to pass the bill grew
in part out of a bitter teacher strike in the fall of 1987 _ the
year then-Secretary Bennett called Chicago schools ``the worst in
the nation.''
   His comments helped fan a heated citywide discussion of schools
and spur legislators to action.
   A bill similar to the one signed into law Monday was passed by
the General Assembly last summer, but that measure was caught in
political bickering between Thompson and Democratic lawmakers from
Chicago over control of an oversight board.
   The dispute was settled with passage of a new bill that gives
oversight powers to the existing Chicago School Finance Authority,
created nearly a decade ago after an earlier financial crisis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
