<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Explosion 1stLd-Writethru a0708 12-12 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Explosion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crowd Demands Punishment After Illegal Fireworks Cause Disaster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with angry crowd pursuing mayor,
details and quotes. No pickup</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   By ANITA SNOW=
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infuriated crowd, shoving and jostling and
demanding justice, followed Mexico City's mayor on his inspection on
Monday of a charred marketplace where 62 people died in an inferno
caused by illegal fireworks.
   From a balcony, residents flung soggy pieces of burnt paper and
wood at Mayor Manuel Camacho Solis, who took office Dec. 1. One
person waved a sign that asked, ``To whom do we owe this tragedy?''
   Hundreds of people milled around Camacho Solis as he and his
aides tramped over muddy ashes and past burned candy stores, melted
rolls of plastic, soaked cigarette packages, mounds of scorched
peanuts and twisted steel beams.
   ``We share the pain of the families who lost relatives in this
tragedy,'' the mayor said during his visit to Merced market in the
heart of Mexico City.
   The shouting crowd led him to untended stalls where crates of
unexploded fireworks were still stored after Sunday's disaster.
Camacho Solis promised to have them removed.
   ``You have to give us justice. Six-year (presidential) terms come
and go but nothing changes. We don't want you to forget us,'' vendor
Liborio Garcia Chocihua said. Camacho Solis and his aides are
presidential appointees.
   Local district attorney Alfonso Nieto on Monday set the toll at
62 dead and 83 injured. None of those hurt were reported in serious
condition.
   The cause of the accident is under investigation, but officials
and residents blame illegal fireworks. Fireworks traditionally are
used from Dec. 12, the Day of the Virgin of Guadalupe, until New
Year's Day.
   Camacho Solis announced a ban on the sale and use of fireworks in
the Valley of Mexico _ something that is already forbidden without
special permit. His aides said none of the vendors in the market
appeared to have permits.
   Francisco Tirado and other vendors said illegal fireworks caused
lesser explosions and fires in the past, but the government did
nothing to prevent their sale.
   ``Usually there are only a few injured, or one or two killed,''
Tirado said.
   Thousands of Merced marketplace vendors work out of stalls on the
street, selling everything from radios to fruit _ and, in December,
fireworks.
   The market was clogged with shoppers when the blasts started.
Explosions ripped through stalls. Screaming people fled the scene.
Dozens died in nearby buildings, trapped when the buildings caught
fire.
   ``In a matter of seconds everything was gone,'' said candy seller
Fernando Cruz.
   Bulldozers ground through yard-deep muck on Monday, clearing away
the wreckage. Nieto said firefighters carted away tons of
unexploded, unsold fireworks during the night.
   A child's pail lay on its side, near a pair of women's shoes
abandoned in the panic. One vendor's table was topped by a pyramid
of blackened, melted fruit. Strands of festive red and silver
Christmas bunting still draped remains of another stall.
   Thousands of pilgrims gathered Monday at the shrine of the Virgin
of Guadalupe in northern Mexico City. Juan Ortega Durante cried as
he crawled into the basilica carrying a picture of the Virgin, then
fainted when he got inside. Family members said his nephew died in
the inferno.
   Municipal leader Everado Gamiz Fernandez said 14 tons of
fireworks were seized in his district last year, where there are
about 2,000 vendors. But he noted, ``There aren't enough resources
to inspect and watch here every day and night.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
