<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Lefebvre     12-12 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Lefebvre,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Meets with Former Supporters of Rebel Bishop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II gave his blessing Monday to
a group of traditionalist priests and seminarians who broke with
rebel Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre to remain loyal to the papacy,
Vatican officials said.
   The pope greeted the 40 members of the Fraternity of St. Peter,
offering his blessing to each one and posing for photographs with
them, said the officials, who asked not to be identified.
   The group was accompanied by Cardinal Augustin Mayer, who heads a
Vatican commission that seeks to convince Lefebvre's followers to
stay with the mainstream Roman Catholic Church.
   Lefebvre, a Frenchman, heads an ultra-traditionalist movement
that rejects many of the modernizing reforms of the Second Vatican
Council (1962-65).
   He was excommunicated after he consecrated four bishops without
papal approval in Switzerland in June, causing the first schism in
the church in more than a century. The Vatican has warned Lefebvre's
followers that they also face excommunication if they adhere to the
schism.
   But the pope has promised to meet their traditionalist needs,
including wider use of the 16th century Latin Mass, if they remain
loyal to Rome.
</TEXT>
