<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PTLAuction 2ndLd-Writethru a0758 12-12 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL Auction, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0758,0807</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bidders Make Offers For PTL; High Bid Just $36.25 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to add that bidders wouldn't explain low
level of offers; judge wouldn't comment. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
``This is ...' SUBS grafs 12-15, `Heritage Ministries ...', with 5
grafs to add further comment on bidding, delete redundant first
reference to Sam Johnson. Picks 16th graf, `Johnson's group ...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian businessman offered $36.25
million Monday for the PTL television ministry, but a bankruptcy
official said the bid probably will be rejected by a judge.
   PTL's court-appointed trustee, M.C. ``Red'' Benton, said ``I
would have to conclude'' that U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds
would not approve the offer when it is reported to him at a hearing
Tuesday in Columbia.
   Benton predicted Reynolds would order the ministry's assets
liquidated. But he said it's possible the judge would open bidding
again at Tuesday's hearing. Reynolds has declined to comment on the
proceedings.
   The judge had wanted the bidding to start at $50 million. Benton
and the bidders declined to say why the bids were far short, and far
below offers made earlier. But the prospective buyers said more bids
were expected Tuesday.
   ``This is more or less a card game where each side is testing the
other side, and I think they (the bidders) are looking forward to
meeting in court with a proposal all of their own,'' Benton said.
   Reynolds has said if no appropriate bid was made, he would order
a liquidation of the ministry. If a bidder meets his guidelines
during the auction run by Benton, the judge said he planned to
approve a sale Tuesday.
   The ministry filed for bankruptcy reorganization in June 1987,
three months after founder Jim Bakker left amid revelations of
luxurious living and hush money paid to Jessica Hahn, a church
secretary with whom Bakker had a sexual liaison.
   Monday's high bid was put in by Stephen Mernick, a Toronto
real-estate developer and orthodox Jew. The opening bid was $20
million by Cy Bahakel, a former North Carolina state senator who now
owns 15 television stations.
   The offers were far below the appraised value of PTL's assets _
between $92 million and $110 million, and half of that offered in
the initial auction in November.
   The auction, which was closed to the public, began about 2 p.m.
and ended about 3:45 p.m.
   The four apparent contenders for the assets _ Mernick, Bahakel,
Heritage Ministries president Sam Johnson and a new bidder, Michael
Karas, president of First Canadian Development Co. of Toronto _ all
said they may bid Tuesday.
   Heritage Ministries did not bid Monday. Karas said he dropped out
of the bidding shortly after it began because he said it was obvious
none of them was going to meet the terms set down by Reynolds, which
included starting bids at $50 million.
   Johnson said he held off bidding because he was unwilling to meet
a condition of the sale that called for the down payment to be
forfeited if the would-be buyer is unable to secure financing.
   Mernick had said he intended to offer less than $70 million for
the 2,200 acres of property, which includes a 500-room hotel, a
water park, a television studio and a 2,000-seat church.
   A month ago, Mernick said he would pay $115 million, $50 million
of it cash. But Reynolds rejected the bid, saying there were
inadequate assurances that Mernick would pay the remaining $65
million.
   Asked Monday why he bid only $36.25 million, he said, ``That's
the bid I made.''
   Johnson's group held a telethon on PTL's TV show last weekend to
try to bring contributions up to $5 million for a deposit on the
property.
   Johnson said the last of the money was raised shortly before noon
on Monday.
   ``This $5 million represents a statement on the part of the body
of Christ that cannot be ignored,'' he said on Monday's television
show.
   The only appraisal so far of PTL's property is based on its value
as an active ministry. That appraisal, conducted for Benton by
Arthur Little & Co. of Atlanta, says that with a ``charismatic
leader,'' the property would be worth $110 million.
   Under a ``stabilized ministry,'' with no well-known figure to
solicit donations, the estimate dropped to $92 million.
   The appraisal estimated that, sold piecemeal, PTL would bring
from $76 million to $85 million.
   Some say the lack of interest in the property puts those figures
in serious doubt, and that the scandals involving Bakker make the
PTL property even harder to sell. Bakker and his top PTL deputy,
Richard Dortch, were indicted last week on fraud charges.
</TEXT>
