<1ST_LINE>r w AM-McDade-Ethics     12-12 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McDade-Ethics,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Common Cause Wants Ethics Probe Of Rep. McDade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Common Cause, the citizens' lobby group, asked
the House ethics committee Monday to investigate whether Rep. Joseph
McDade, R-Pa., accepted gifts in violation of House rules.
   In his written request to the panel, Common Cause President Fred
Wertheimer did not accuse McDade of breaking the law or violating
ethics standards. But he said ``serious questions'' raised about the
Scranton lawmaker's activities warranted an inquiry.
   Wertheimer said his letter stemmed from a recent Wall Street
Journal report that the FBI was probing whether McDade illegally
accepted more than $45,000 in campaign gifts and speaking fees from
officials associated with United Chem-Con Corp., a Pennsylvania firm
that McDade was helping.
   Timothy Tomastik, McDade's press secretary, said the pending
investigation prevents the congressman from answering any of the
allegations yet. Nor did McDade have any comment on Common Cause's
letter, Tomastik said.
   House members must identify gifts of $250 or more, and are asked
``to avoid situations in which even an inference might be drawn
suggesting improper action.''
</TEXT>
