<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 2135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FirstFreeze 1stLd-Writethru a0712 12-12 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-First Freeze, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0712,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Onset Of Winter Highlights Plight Of The Homeless</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4-5th grafs, bgng `Throughout the...', with 4 grafs to
add detail on how many people seek beds in lottery, UPDATE with
electricity use setting record. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Elsewhere,
life...'. SUBS last graf to CORRECT spelling of Ullmann sted Ullman.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kingston House is holding lotteries these days
for beds, trying to be fair as it goes about meeting long lines at
the shelter each day. Even in New England, there's just no getting
used to the kinds of demands that record cold can put on people.
   The first blast of the 1988-89 winter season Monday brought a
record low for the date of 2 degrees, with most of the impact seen
at shelters.
   At the Kingston House, seven homeless people were in line as the
doors to the shelter opened at 6:30 a.m. Phil Gonzalez, in charge of
admitting people to the shelter, said a lottery has been held before
noon in recent days for the beds. Those who lose out are referred to
other shelters or offered a blanket and the floor.
   He said that typically, about 60 people take part in the lottery
seeking one of the 40 beds at the shelter available for transients.
The other 20 beds at the shelter are used by residents who stay for
months while they take part in a rehabilitation program.
   Throughout the city Sunday night, about 75 people were
transported to shelters, and more were expected as the cold weather
continues, Mayor Raymond L. Flynn said.
   Electricity demand set a wintertime record in the region Monday
and came close to surpassing the all-time record, a spokesman said.
   ``I don't have a final number set for today yet, but we can
definitely say we surpassed the previous winter record of 19,277
megawatts,'' said Bill Sheperdson of the New England Power Pool.
Monday's average peak load was between 19,400 and 19,500 megawatts,
he said. The system record of 19,500 megawatts was set during a heat
wave in August.
   Elsewhere, life went on, albeit at a slower pace.
   Hardy fishermen at the Boston Fish Pier told of chipping ice off
the bows with wooden mallets to keep trawlers from getting nose
heavy.
   ``No grog. A lot of coffee,'' said Paul Hughes, 38, a mate aboard
the Olympia, an 86-foot fishing trawler that had just returned from
a week at sea.
   ``As long as you're moving, it isn't bad,'' said Hughes, wearing
four layers of long-sleeved shirts and a cap with ear flaps. ``The
bad part is if we do damage. Then you've got to stop and mend it up.
That's bare-handed. That's nasty.''
   Ray Southmayd, of the United Services of America window washing
service, said workers use a special non-freeze solution in bitter
weather.
   ``I'm sure (any window washer) is miserable, but it's all in the
line of work,'' Southmayd said.
   Gerry Cudyer, who runs the city's 24-hour hotline for citizen
complaints, said her office received about 100 calls since the
temperature took a dive Sunday. Most were about a lack of heat from
tenants whose landlords seemed unprepared for the cold, she said.
   ``In winter it's inevitable. But when it was 50 degrees last
week, they let the oil run out,'' she said. ``They were caught by
the dramatic swing in temperature from 50 to 0 in a matter of days.''
   The homeless problem in Boston gets special attention from a city
commission and a mayor who heads a national conference on the issue.
   At a city-sponsored summit Monday on the homeless, which was
designed to begin building a groundswell of support for more federal
participation in providing affordable housing, speakers said efforts
must focus on moving beyond temporary shelter to permanent housing.
   Flynn said the federal commitment to providing housing dropped
off sharply during the Reagan administration. The mayor also touted
Boston's pledge to provide a warm bed and hot meal for anyone on the
streets.
   Results of a street-by-street count of the homeless have not been
tallied yet, but Flynn said preliminary figures indicate it will top
the 3,300 recorded in February. The number of city shelter beds has
increased from 972 in 1983 to 2,754 this year.
   Shelter officials say they see more children than before. At the
Salvation Army, a special party was planned Tuesday for 350 children
with actress Liv Ullmann and a live performance of the
``Nutcracker'' ballet.
</TEXT>
