<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-12 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Winds, Bitter Cold In East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Arctic air that flowed across Canada and into the north-central
and northeast United States caused record-low temperatures Monday,
but Billings, Mont., had a record high.
   Hugh Crowther, a meteorologist at the National Weather Service's
Severe Storms Center in Kansas City, Mo., said about 25 cities
reported record low temperatures.
   Among them were Albany, N.Y., where thermometers dipped to 12
below zero; Allentown, Pa., 2 degrees; Asheville, N.C., 16 degrees;
Baltimore, 12 degrees; Boston, 2 degrees; Detroit, 2 below zero;
Elkins, W.Va., 10 below; Hartford, Conn., 3 below; Houghton Lake,
Mich., 12 below; Newark, N.J., 6 degrees; Philadelphia, 8 degrees;
and Wilmington, Del., 8 degrees. Washington, D.C., tied its record
for the date of 13 degrees.
   Saranac Lake, N.Y., near Lake Placid, had the coldest temperature
in the nation Monday morning, 28 below zero.
   But Billings reached 57 degrees to break their high temperature
record for the date, which was 56 degrees set in 1934. Oakland,
Calif., tied its high temperature mark with 65 degrees. That record
was set in 1976.
   Gale warnings were posted for Monday night on the North Carolina
coast, Lake Huron and the strait of Washington state. High wind
warnings were posted over the Montana Front Range, the Rockies and
Upper Yellowstone Valley.
   Winds gusted to 41 mph at Riverton, Wyo., and to 35 and 45 mph in
the higher elevations between Cheyenne and Rock Springs, Wyo.
   Snow fell Monday night over eastern Minnesota, eastern Iowa,
northern Illinois, Wisconsin, upper Michigan and eastern lower
Michigan. Rain was scattered over northern Florida and southern
Georgia, as well as from western Montana across the Idaho panhandle
into eastern Washington and along the northern Pacific Coast. Rain
was mixed with snow near Charleston, S.C.
   Snowfall during the 6 hours ending at 7 p.m. EST included 2
inches at Escanaba, Mich., and an inch at Duluth, Minn., and Green
Bay, Wis.
   For Tuesday, the National Weather Service forecast snow showers
extending from western New England across the lower Great Lakes,
much of Michigan and south through the Virginias. Rain will reach
from western North Dakota across Montana, the northern Plateau and
the northern Pacific Coast with rain becoming snow in the higher
elevations.
   High temperatures will be in the teens in northern Maine; in the
20s and 30s from the reminder of New England across the central
Atlantic Coast, the northern half of the Appalachians, the Great
Lakes, the Ohio Valley, the upper Mississippi Valley and eastern
North Dakota; the 40s and 50s from North Carolina across northern
Florida, the central Gulf of Mexico states, the Tennessee Valley,
the central Mississippi Valley, parts of the northern half of the
Plains, the upper Missouri Valley, the Rockies, the Plateau and the
northern half of the Pacific Coast; the 70s in southern Florida,
southern Texas southern Arizona and southern California; and in the
60s in most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
