<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 2157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada     12-12 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Returns for Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's government
announced its intention Monday to make sure Canada can start the
free trade agreement with the United States as scheduled Jan. 1.
   But his opponents said too many issues remain to be discussed for
the legislation to be rushed through Parliament, called back into
session for work on the trade bill.
   The prime minister's Progressive Conservative Party won 169 of
the 295 seats in the House of Commons in the hotly contested Nov. 21
elections, so it could force quick passage of the legislation.
   The measure will phase out all remaining tariffs between the
United States and Canada over a 10-year period.
   ``The people have spoken in a general election three weeks ago,''
Gov. Gen. Jeanne Sauve said in the formal ``throne speech''
traditionally opening a new parliamentary session in Ottawa. ``In
the election, my government sought and received a mandate for its
policies, including the free trade agreement between Canada and the
United States that is to take effect on Jan. 1, 1989.''
   The opposition Liberal Party, which won 82 seats in Commons, and
the socialist New Democratic Party with 43 seats have said they will
not stand in the way of ultimate passage but want extensive debate
on the problems they believe the trade agreement will bring.
   The bitter debate over free trade that marked the fall election
campaign would be renewed in Parliament.
   One seat, won by a Conservative who died after the election, is
vacant.
   Liberal leader John Turner, who led a self-proclaimed ``crusade''
against the trade agreement, said in an interview with the Canadian
Broadcasting Corp. that he was not stalling the legislation.
   ``To insist on a thorough debate - that's not stalling,'' he
said, noting that the popular vote showed more Canadians in favor of
the two parties opposing the agreement than for the Conservatives.
   New Democratic leader Ed Broadbent said he wanted amendments to
be introduced to protect workers whose jobs are lost in company
restructurings tied to the trade agreement.
   He told the CBC that Mulroney won a mandate for the trade
agreement, but ``he received no mandate to ramrod it right through
Parliament.''
   A delay of days, weeks or probably even months in completing the
enabling legislation needed would not hinder the agreement.
   The United States has completed all its legislation for the
agreement, signed by Mulroney and President Reagan last Jan. 2.
   In Canada, it passed the elected House of Commons last August but
then was bottled up in the Liberal-controlled, appointed Senate to
force the election. The legislation approved last August has expired
and the process now must be repeated in Commons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
