<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     12-12 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filipino Attackers Kill Police Major and His Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants early Tuesday shot and
killed a police major and his policeman son, who was organizing an
anti-communist group in a rebel-infested neighborhood in Cebu City,
police reported.
   Capt. Salvador Sanchez said that Maj. Jesus Negapatan, 59, and
his son, Patrolman Jesus Negapatan Jr., about 30, were standing on a
street corner in Cebu City when three men and a woman emerged from a
taxi. At least three of the four opened fire, Sanchez said.
   Sanchez said father and son were killed instantly and the
assailants escaped. He said the elder Negapatan was administrative
officer of the Cebu City police force and the son, a traffic
policeman, was organizing the anti-communist group in their
neighborhood.
   Sanchez said it was not clear if the killers were New People's
Army guerrillas or ordinary criminals.
   Cebu City is a major metropolitan area, about 350 miles southeast
of Manila.
   Faced with an upsurge in urban violence, the Philippine military
has begun organizing a new civilian anti-communist force, the
Civilian Armed Forces Geographical Units, to assist in guarding
villages and urban neighborhoods against the New People's Army.
   Volunteers for the Units are to phase out vigilante groups and
the Civilian Home Defense Force, both of which have been accused of
widespread human rights abuses in the fight against the rebels.
   President Corazon Aquino said on Monday at a meeting in Cagayan
de Oro that members of the new militia will be rigidly screened,
especially those who previously served in the Civilian Home Defense
Force.
   The New People's Army has waged a 19-year insurgency to establish
a Marxist state in the Philippines.
</TEXT>
