<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 2235EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Miners     12-12 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Miners,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peruvian Miners Agree to Halt Crippling Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government and a communist-led mine
workers' federation signed an accord late Monday to end an
8-week-old strike that has cost Peru nearly $300 million, Prime
Minister Armando Villanueva said.
   Strike leader Saul Cantoral said miners will resume work
nationwide in three days, bringing an end to a paralysis in Peru's
most important industry.
   Villanueva told reporters the strike cost the nation nearly $300
million, one-fourth of last year's mineral export income of $1.2
billion last year.
   Peru is a leading world producer of silver and copper and a major
source of gold, lead and zinc. It traditionally received more than
half of its hard currency earnings from mineral exports.
   Peru's 60,000 miners struck on Oct. 17 to force mine companies to
honor a government-union pact permitting labor contracts in the
mining industry to be negotiated jointly with all mining enterprises
rather than on a company-by-company basis.
   The strike came as Peru entered a severe recession, marked by
inflation expected to surpass 1,500 percent this year and a shortage
of dollar reserves to purchase vital imports.
   Industry officials said strikers were being manipulated by
communist guerrillas seeking to undermine the nation. The miners'
federation denied it.
   Terms of the new accord signed by Cantoral and other leaders of
the National Federation of Mine and Metalworkers and by Villanueva
were not immediately announced.
   Federation director Guillermo Diaz said earlier Monday that the
federation was demanding that the government promise to enact a law
to force public and private mining firms to abide by the
government-union pact.
   Such an agreement will greatly strengthen the miners' bargaining
position during contracts, industry analysts said.
   The National Mining Society, Peru's most important association of
private mine owners, has strongly opposed joint contract
negotiations. It says the federation will use its bargaining power
to cripple the industry at will.
   Government and industry officials said more than half the
strikers began returning to work last week. The federation, which
represents dozens of mine unions, denied the report.
   Thousands of highland miners, many with families, marched on Lima
after the strike began and set up camps around the city to publicize
their plight. Miners engaged in street protests which at times ended
in violence and arrests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
