<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Quake-Rescue     12-12 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Rescue,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials, Rescuers Recount Problems Organizing Quake Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers and officials trying to save
survivors of the earthquake in Soviet Armenia said Monday they
desperately need a better command system, more coordination, and
better equipment.
   In addition, no Soviet troops were visible among the rescue
workers in Leninaken, one of the hardest-hit cities in Wednesday's
earthquake.
   Instead, the rescue operations were being carried out mostly by
friends and relatives of those still trapped. They used small tools
like hammers and torches.
   Soviet Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov said enthusiam was plentiful,
but ``today the question is organization.'' He spoke at a news
conference late Monday in Yerevan, the Armenian capital.
   Sverre Kilde, a U.N. disaster relief officer, said the rescue
effort appeared well organized on the national and regional level,
but locally in Leninakan it was suffering from a lack of control.
   ``Here there are 50-60 people shouting in all directions,'' said
U.N. diaster relief officer Sverre Kilde, speaking of a rescue site
he visited in Leninakan on Sunday. ``It would have been much more
reasonable to have an army captain or colonel in charge of it.''
   Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov told reporters that more than
18,000 soldiers were in the earthquake area, but in Leninakan none
was seen helping with rescue operations.
   Asked about the situation, Yazov and Ryzhkov said the soldiers
were ensuring order in Leninakan and helping unload relief supplies
from cargo planes.
   They also said troops were involved in rescue operations in
Spitak, a city of more than 25,000 people that was almost totally
destroyed by the earthquake.
   Ryzhkov said soldiers had cut off both cities to all but relief
traffic.
   Two relief planes have crashed in heavy air traffic in the
region. A crash of a Soviet military plane on Sunday killed 78
people, and one of a Yugoslavian military aircraft left seven dead
early Monday.
   The Soviet premier gave high marks to the medical effort, saying
doctors had performed 2,500 complicated operations in the field
during the first 24 hours after the quake.
   However, area doctors said they badly need artificial kidney
machines and blood-filtering devices. They hope to receive more of
both from abroad.
   Veterans of rescue efforts for past earthquakes in Mexico City
and El Salvador say it is difficult to supply the remote Soviet area
near the Turkish border.
   Rescuers, meanwhile, pleaded for more cranes and bulldozers to
pull away slabs of concrete and other debris in an effort to free
those still trapped in the rubble.
</TEXT>
