<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--StolenSkull     12-12 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Stolen Skull,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syracuse Student Pleads Guilty To Stealing Skull</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Syracuse University art student pleaded
guilty Monday to stealing the skull of a 19th-century mayor from a
mausoleum.
   Kevin D. McQuain, 19, of New York City entered the plea to a
felony count of body stealing.
   In exchange for the guilty plea, Onondaga County Court Judge
Patrick J. Cunningham said he would not sentence McQuain to serve
time in jail and will get him youthful offender status, which will
clear the conviction from his permanent record.
   McQuain, a scholarship student who has been suspended from school
since his arrest Oct. 19, still must face action by university
officials.
   The freshman told police he took the skull of former Syracuse
Mayor John J. Crouse, who died in 1886, because he wanted to use it
for sculpting class. McQuain was charged after another student saw
him boiling the skull in the kitchen of his dormitory.
</TEXT>
