<HEAD>Forensics Expert Called In On New Bedford, Mass.-Area Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Washington-based forensics expert
arrived Monday to begin examining the bodies of six women found in
southeastern Massachusetts since July believed to be the victims of
a serial killer.
   Douglas Ubelaker of the Smithsonian Institution will seek more
details on the cause of death of all six and will attempt to
identify the three bodies that remain unidentified, according to a
spokesman for the investigation.
   High on Ubelaker's agenda will be examining a sixth body found
over the weekend by hunters in a wooded area of Dartmouth off
Interstate 195. The body is one of three which has yet to be
identified.
   ``To make a positive identification, we need to find something on
the skeleton that is absolutely unique,'' Ubelaker said in an
earlier interview.
   State police dogs and a specially trained dog from Connecticut
returned to the woods outside of New Bedford on Monday and combed a
6- to 8-square-mile area where the bodies have been found.
   Pina said Monday that he believes the sixth body was connected to
the other five and was likely the victim of the same killer or
killers.
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that it's all similar,'' he said.
The sixth woman, whose skeletal remains were badly decomposed, was
believed to have been dead for the longest period _ dating back to
last spring.
