<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Air Crash,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stunt Pilot Killed in Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UDINE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian Air Force stunt pilot who replaced
a colleague who died in the disaster at a West German air show in
August was killed on Monday when his plane crashed during a training
flight, news reports said.
   The Italian news agency ANSA reported that the plane, an
Aermacchi MB339, crashed about 10 minutes after takeoff into a field
in northeastern Italy outside the city of Udine. The pilot,
identified as Lt. Col. Paolo Scoponi, 36, was flying solo, ANSA said.
   It reported that the victim was an experienced test pilot who
recently joined the ``Frecce Tricolori,'' the Air Force squad which
performs air shows.
   Three Italian stunt jets from the squad collided during an air
show at the U.S. Ramstein Air Base on Aug. 28, and one of the jet
plunged into the crowd of spectators.
   Seventy people died and several hundred were injured. A report
issued in October by the West German defense ministry blamed pilot
error for the crash.
   The squad's name means ``Tri-color Arrows'' and refers to the
red, white and green of the Italian flag.
   Founded in 1930 as a school of aerobatics, it has been a separate
unit of the Italian air force since 1956.
</TEXT>
