<2ND_LINE>AM-Treasure Ship,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court: $40 Million Pirate Ship Wreck Belongs to Finder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold, silver, cannons and other wreckage from a
pirate ship that has lain buried in sand off Cape Cod for 271 years
belong to the salvage entrepreneur who found them, the Massachusetts
Supreme Court ruled Monday.
   Barry Clifford will be entitled to keep the artifacts, now worth
an estimated $40 million, and will not have give the state of
Massachusetts a 25 percent share, according to Clifford's attorney,
Allan H. Tufankjian.
   In a unanimous opinion, the high court rejected the state's claim
of sovereignty over the wrecked sailing vessel Whydah lying beneath
the sand in the waters of Wellfleet on Cape Cod, where it foundered
in April 1717.
   ``It's a great Christmas present,'' Clifford said in a telephone
interview from his home in Chatham, calling the Whydah the only
pirate ship in the world ever to be found and salvaged. ``This is
it. There's really nothing else.''
   He said it was unfair of the state to claim one-quarter of the
find when all the risks associated with underwater salvage were
taken by him and his company, Maritime Underwater Surveys Inc.
   In 1982, based on research from contemporary accounts, Clifford
found ``an unidentified, wrecked and abandoned vessel'' one mile off
Wellfleet under about 14 feet of water and 5 feet of sand.
   Since 1ereignty as surely as the Whydah foundered on the shoals
off Wellfleet,'' Justice Neil Lynch wrote for the highllinois, Box
</TEXT>
