<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0819EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Japan-CrimeMobs Adv15   12-12 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Crime Mobs, Adv 15,0769</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs Dec. 15 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Trouble at the Top of the Underworld in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOBE, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Each day children on their way home from
school calmly walk past the headquarters of Japan's largest
underworld syndicate, behind plastered beige walls in a classy
residential district overlooking the sea.
   Across town, a red-tiled building controlled by the gang is
within 100 yards of the Kobe District Courthouse. It bears the
golden, diamond-shaped logo of the gang, which leaders wear on their
lapels and which is printed on members' business cards.
   Over the past few years the Yamaguchi-gumi syndicate has waged a
successful war of revenge against a major rival, doubled its
membership and raked in millions of dollars annually, said Takashi
Ishii, assistant director of the National Police Agency's Organized
Crime Control Office
   But all is not well within the criminal empire.
   The year's business for the 20,000-member syndicate traditionally
starts Dec. 13, when ranking bosses gather at headquarters in this
western port city for a formal celebration called ``koto hajime'' _
the beginning of things.
   But since gang leader Masahisa Takenaka was killed by a splinter
group's gunman in 1985, custom has forced the Yamaguchi-gumi to
cancel the annual ceremony because it has no top don.
   Takenaka was replaced by two men, acting gang leader Kazuo
Nakanishi and ``young leader'' Yoshinori Watanabe, who led the gang
into a war to avenge Takenaka's killing, police say.
   Though that vendetta, which has left 25 dead and 70 injured by
police count, now seems to be nearing an end, police say the long
time without a leader has led to factionalism in the gang, weakening
its pyramid-style command structure.
   Public reaction to the high-profile violence has also plagued the
gang. Japan has low rates of violent crime and very strict
gun-control laws. But gunfights have brought attention to the gangs,
spawning grass-roots movements to rid residential areas of gang
headquarters and offices.
   A Yamaguchi-gumi subgang in the central Japanese city of
Hamamatsu was in the media spotlight until public opposition forced
it to relocate last year. The gang is now on the verge of collapse,
according to Ishii of the crime control office.
   But Masafumi Ueda, director of the office, said in an interview
that the public outcry and tough police crackdowns also may have
worked to the syndicate's benefit, putting many smaller gangs out of
business or forcing them to seek Yamaguchi-gumi protection.
   A recent issue of ``Endless Advance,'' an in-house journal
published by the Kyokuto Shinsei-kai, a large Tokyo syndicate,
attested to the trend toward consolidation.
   In the 120-page edition obtained by The Associated Press were
photos of top underworld figures gathered for dinner at a posh Tokyo
hotel to ``pursue friendly relations and cooperation'' and avoid
intergang trouble.
   Technically, the Yamaguchi-gumi has only 86 members, but each of
the top 86 controls a network of subordinate gangs, which, in turn,
have their own ``kasa'' _ Japanese for umbrella.
   Top bosses rarely face prosecution for serious crimes as
underlings take responsibility, sometimes even turning themselves
in, since doing prison time can bring a promotion.
   According to an annual report by the National Police Agency, more
than 86,000 gangsters in 3,201 gangs are spread across the country.
Roughly 40 percent belong to the big three nationwide syndicates _
the Yamaguchi-gumi, the Tokyo-based Sumiyoshi Rengo-kai and the
Inagawa-kai, also based in Tokyo.
   Ueda of the National Police Agency estimated total underworld
income at the yen equivalent of $15 billion annually, but he added
that ``is only a rough guess.''
   Yamaguchi-gumi income sources include gambling, the protection
racket, fraud, prostitution, money laundering and narcotics. These
and countless other scams are backed up by front operations in
construction, the stock market and real estate.
   Police believe the deaths of Hiroyuki Watanabe and his boss,
Kazuo Kengaku, an Osaka stock market speculator, are shadier
examples of what the Yamaguchi-gumi has done.
   The bodies of the men, who police allege had been kidnapped and
held for ransom, were dug up Oct. 18 _ entombed in a slab of
concrete. Two Yamaguchi-gumi affiliate members later confessed to
the crime.
   Meanwhile, Kobe residents seem to accept the Yamaguchi-gumi's
presence with a mixture of helplessness and inevitability.
   ``I've never had any trouble with gangsters, but I suppose I'd
prefer it if they'd leave,'' said a taxi driver. ``The thing is,
you'll never get rid of them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Dec. 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
