<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, Dec. 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, Dec. 22, the 357th day of 1988. There are nine
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On Dec. 22, 1944, during the World War II Battle of the Bulge,
the Germans demanded the surrender of encircled American troops at
Bastogne, Belgium. Brigadier General Anthony C. McAuliffe gave his
famous one-word reply: ``Nuts!'' The Americans were able to hold out
until additional U.S. forces ended the siege four days later.
   On this date:
   In 1775, a Continental naval fleet was organized in the
rebellious American colonies under the command of Ezek Hopkins.
   In 1807, Congress passed the Embargo Act, designed to force peace
between Britain and France by cutting off all trade with Europe.
   In 1864, during the Civil War, Union General William T. Sherman
sent a message to President Abraham Lincoln from Georgia, saying,
``I beg to present you as a Christmas gift the city of Savannah.''
   In 1894, French army officer Alfred Dreyfus was convicted of
treason in a court-martial that triggered worldwide charges of
anti-Semitism. (Dreyfus was ultimately vindicated.)
   In 1941, British Prime Minister Winston Churchill arrived in
Washington for a wartime conference with President Franklin D.
Roosevelt.
   In 1963, an official 30-day mourning period for President John F.
Kennedy ended.
   In 1971, the United Nations General Assembly voted to ratify the
election of Kurt Waldheim to be secretary-general.
   In 1977, three dozen people were killed when a 250-foot grain
elevator at the Continental Grain Company plant in Westwego, La.,
exploded.
   In 1984, in a case that drew national attention, New York City
resident Bernhard Goetz shot four black youths on a Manhattan
subway, claiming they were about to rob him.
   Ten years ago: In Guyana, a coroner's jury ruled that nearly all
of the more than 900 people who died at the Peoples Temple commune
in Jonestown had been murdered, with the exception of two that the
jury said committed suicide, and one who may or may not have
committed suicide.
   Five years ago: PLO chairman Yasser Arafat, driven into exile
from Lebanon by Syrian-backed Palestinian rebels, stopped in Cairo,
Egypt, where he received a warm welcome from President Hosni Mubarak.
   One year ago: The Reagan administration criticized Israel's
handling of the Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories,
particularly the military's use of live ammunition against civilians.
   Today's Birthdays: Lady Bird Johnson is 76. TV personality Gene
Rayburn is 71. The Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives, Jim
Wright, is 66. Actor Hector Elizondo is 52. Baseball player Steve
Carlton is 44. CBS News correspondent Diane Sawyer is 43. Baseball
player Steve Garvey is 40. Singers Maurice and Robin Gibb are 39.
Golfer Jan Stephenson is 37.
   Thought for today: ``The good things in history are usually of
very short duration, but afterwards have a decisive influence over
what happens over long periods of time.'' _ Hannah Arendt, American
writer (1906-1975).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
