<DOCNO> AP881212-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1422EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--RetiredMunchkin Adv25   12-12 1063</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Retired Munchkin, Adv25,1102</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 drawing.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ He worked his way through college as a midget in
sideshows at fairs and expositions. He became a living trademark for
a national brand of wieners. But the highpoint of Meinhardt Raabe's
career came when he landed the role of a Munchkin in ``The Wizard of
Oz.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENNEY FARMS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are no yellow brick roads or
wicked witches in this North Florida retirement community, but there
is a fugitive from the land of Oz.
   He's a Munchkin, name of Meinhardt Raabe.
   Although it's been half a century, Raabe can still repeat the
lines he sang as the Munchkin coroner in ``The Wizard of Oz,'' the
1939 movie classic starring Judy Garland.
   When the tornado dropped the house on the wicked witch, it was
Raabe, carrying a large death certificate, who sang, ``She's not
only merely dead, she's most sincerely dead.''
   The coroner had one of the nine speaking roles for the 116 little
people who played Munchkins in the movie based on L. Frank Baum's
books.
   At the time the movie was filmed, Raabe was promoting Oscar Mayer
wieners as ``Little Oscar _ The World's Smallest Chef.''
   He took a two-month leave of absence and headed for Hollywood,
where he was given the role in ``The Wizard Of Oz.''
   Raabe was 22 years old and only 46 inches tall. He had worked his
way through college in midget shows at fairs. He's since grown to
4-foot-7.
   When the film was made, Raabe says he had no idea it would become
a classic. He was only familiar with the scenes in which he played.
   ``We didn't know what came before or what came after,'' he says.
``We had no idea what the picture was all about until we saw it
released.
   ``At the time of its release, it was overshadowed by `Gone With
The Wind.'''
   ``Gone With The Wind'' won four Academy Awards, including best
picture that year.
   ``It was only after CBS got the film in 1956 and used it for
their promotions that it became as well known,'' he says.
   Now retired and living in this community established by J.C.
Penney, Raabe, 73, believes the movie has become an enduring classic
because people saw it as children and still remember it.
   ``That's one factor, but the second basic factor is there is
nothing in the picture that dates it,'' he says. ``There are no old
vintage cars or old vintage streetcars and it's a fantasy picture
that will be fantasy for generations to come.
   ``I have so many middle-aged people come up to me and say, `I
just bought the video of ``The Wizard of Oz'' for my grandchildren.'
But after talking to them, you realize that it was they themselves
who were most interested because it was nostalgia for them.''
   Although Raabe leads an active life as the horticulturist at
Penney Farms, he and his wife, Marie, often travel to Oz reunions,
including a recent one in Chesterton, Ind.
   ``One of the reasons why the Munchkins are getting attention is
that all the major stars of the picture are gone, so there are just
a few of us Munchkins left,'' Raabe says.
   There are fewer than 30 former Munchkins still living.
   ``It was 50 years ago and I was one of the younger ones,'' he
says. ``Many of them were 30 and 40 years older than I was at time.''
   Raabe says being involved in the movie was the experience of a
lifetime.
   ``For a young man of 22 from a farm in Wisconsin to be in that
atmosphere was naturally a big thrill,'' Raabe said. He got to meet
Judy Garland and many of the other top stars at MGM.
   When the little people chosen to play Munchkins were hired, each
was measured for a costume. While the costumes were made, the
Munchkins rehearsed their parts.
   ``As we marched, we had to be on a certain yellow brick on a
certain note. We were all well-rehearsed. So when the costumes were
finished, we were ready to do the shooting,'' he says.
   Work began at 6 a.m. each day and continued until 8 p.m. each
night.
   Raabe says he can't remember what he was paid for his role in the
movie, but remembers it was very low.
   ``By today's standards, people would say you were crazy to work
for that,'' he says.
   Raabe, born in Watertown, Wis. in 1915, was a member of the
Midget City cast at the Chicago World's Fair in 1934. He also
performed at the San Diego Exposition in 1935 and the Texas
Centennial and Cleveland Great Lakes World's Fair in 1936.
   ``By working at these world's fairs as a midget, I was able to
work my way through the university,'' Raabe says. He holds both a
bachelor's degree in accounting from the University of Wisconsin and
a master's degree in business administration from Drexel University.
   Raabe says some short people resent the word ``midget,'' but that
was the description widely used when he was in show business.
   ``My wife and I were both in show business, were both midgets. My
wife worked from 1929 to 1932 as a member of Rose's Royal Midgets,
the largest midget troupe in vaudeville,'' he says. They have been
married for 43 years.
   When Raabe graduated from college, he was unable to get a job as
an accountant because of his size.
   But his size worked to his advantage when he was hired as
``Little Oscar, the World's Smallest Chef'' _ a job he held for 30
years.
   Raabe, who wore a chef's uniform, traveled around the country
doing cooking shows, school shows, lectures and handing out samples.
   ``I was on the road all the time, I never had an office job,'' he
says. ``We were constantly on the road traveling.''
   When ``The Wizard of Oz'' was released in 1939, Raabe performed a
double duty.
   ``I traveled with the picture for six months,'' he says. ``I was
being paid by Oscar Mayer. I was getting the little promotion bit
ahead of the picture and we passed out wiener samples in the lobby
at the end.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1429EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--NewSouthPlantation Adv25   12-12 0935</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--New South Plantation, Adv25,0961</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ It stands as a symbol of the Old South, named for
the goddess of agriculture. But the historic Ceres Plantation east
of Vicksburg in it's new incarnation is also becoming a symbol of
the New South, an industrial park and high-tech center in a state
struggling to polish its image.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a prominent Confederate
minister fled to the old Ceres Plantation when Union gunboats began
the Civil War siege of Vicksburg, bringing along what was reputed to
be the biggest library in the South.
   Yankee soldiers who later sacked the mansion used those books to
``pave'' the muddy road to the Big Black River.
   Today, Yankees or anyone else with bucks to invest in high-tech
businesses are welcome at the former cotton plantation.
   The Old South is merging with the New South on the plantation's
1,300 acres, which have been acquired by the Warren County Port
Commission for development into an industrial park.
   The two-story, country-style antebellum home was named for the
goddess of agriculture. Now it is being offered as a potential
corporate headquarters in a state trying to diversify its economy.
 ers to clear away the debris.
   ``Bodies were ripped apart and the trains were tangled
together,'' said firefighter Chris Fitzgerald. ``We had to use our
heaviest cutting gear and it was like nibbling away at the wreckage
just a little at a time.''
   Among the first rescuers were boys from nearby Emanuel College.
   ``We just heard a crunch, just like metal going together,'' said
Henry Livesey, 12, a student at the private school. ``I saw a man
with metal stuck in his head. He was obviously dead.''
   Chris Reeves, 38, of Southampton, was in the buffet car when the
crash happened. ``There was furniture and enormous lumps of metal
flying everywhere,'' he said as he waited for treatment at St.
George's Hospital. ``All I can remember is dust and debris as you've
never experienced it in your life.''
   ``The whole of the buffet car disintegrated,'' Reeves said. ``The
roof split open like a ripe tomato and that's how we got out. We
tried to find people underneath the rubble but there was so much
debris, there was nothing we could do.''
   Ian Underhill, 41, of Farnborough, said there was ``a hell of a
bang'' as his train approached Clapham.
   ``The train seemed to shoot backwards and the guy opposite me
flew into my face,'' said Underhill, who also was taken to St.
George's. ``Amazingly enough, there was not a lot of panic. It was
fairly calm and people were helping one another to get out. I saw
one man helped out who had lost his foot and there were many others
with terrible injuries.''
   Mike Clarke, 41, of Northbourne, said the restaurant car ``just
disintegrated.
   ``The roof just split open and the bogey (the wheels) came up
through the floor,'' he said.
   Keith Larner, 36, from Southampton, said ``there were people
underneath me and under the metal and there were people with metal
in their bodies.
   ``A woman was trapped with metal which was in her chest and we
just started to get people out immediately. It was the most horrible
sight I have ever seen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1443EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--Writers'Colony Adv25   12-12 1042</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Writers' Colony, Adv25,1077</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ It's a place for aspiring women writers like the
Pennsylvania mother of seven who wrote that ``there hasn't been much
opportunity for quiet in my life.'' And if they get an invitation to
the writers' colony at Hedgebrook Farm on Puget Sound, it won't cost
them a cent. It's all a gift from a woman who believes that people
of her gender deserve to be heard.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA BLANDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANGLEY, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quaint farm on an island in Puget Sound
has been converted into a retreat for women who want to write and
think and dream in solitude, beyond the press of family and jobs.
   The writer's colony at Hedgebrook Farm, which began receiving its
first authors-in-residence in August, is the creation of Nancy
Skinner Nordhoff, the 56-year-old daughter of a shipping executive
who has long been active in community affairs in the Seattle area.
   ``Women need the chance to explore their craft without having to
wait until the kids are in college,'' says Nordhoff, a 1954 graduate
of Mount Holyoke College in South Hadley, Mass. ``Women have
something important to say, they need to be heard.''
   Women writers selected by a screening committee can spend two
weeks to two months at Hedgebrook Farm free of charge. Nordhoff
bought the farm with her own money _ she declines to say how much _
and foots all the bills.
   Why?
   ``It's a gift to myself and to the writers,'' she says. ``It's
because I know from my own life the pain of not being affirmed. You
know, I have the ability, I have the interest to be able to say
women deserve to be heard and to be able to do something about it.''
   The 30-acre farm, 30 miles north of Seattle on Whidbey Island,
has a remodeled yellow stucco farmhouse and two timber-framed,
skylighted cabins, with four others in the works.
   Every day a picnic basket lunch is delivered to each writer's
doorstep, ``with just a loud enough thump so that they know it's
there,'' Nordhoff says.
   Almost every article in the cabins is hand-crafted, from the
porcelain sink basins to the pillows and afghan for curling up next
to three ground-level windows. A loft and bed look out stained-glass
windows into the trees.
   None of the cabins' windows faces other cabins. Nordhoff says
they were designed that way so writers would feel ``separate, but
not isolated.''
   The cabins were designed by architect Chuck Dougherty, a
University of Washington graduate who now designs structures for the
Amish in Lancaster County, Pa.
   Writers are afforded solitude all day but eat dinner in the
farmhouse at a big wooden table looking out over Puget Sound, along
with Nordhoff and the ``farm family'' of carpenters, cooks and other
friends.
   ``It's a place where people can work the way they've always
wanted to,'' says Sheryl Feldman, 47, of Sommerville, Mass., a
non-fiction writer.
   Nordhoff gave up her long career as a community activist to
develop the farm.
   ``It was meetings, meetings, meetings, all the time,'' Nordhoff
says. ``Too much formality and ritual.''
   Nordhoff had been instrumental in forming the City Club, a United
Way volunteer bureau. She also served on Bellevue's Overlake
Hospital board and was president of the Seattle Junior League.
   Nordhoff says that after traveling around the country in a van,
she realized she felt most at home in the country, with her hands in
the dirt.
   She bought the farm as ``something for me,'' and as something she
wanted to share.
   Nordhoff, who now grows vegetables in her Hedgebrook garden,
co-wrote a book on fund-raising for non-profit organizations. But
she says she doesn't consider herself a writer.
   She says the idea for Hedgebrook came from a visit to the
McDowell writers' colony in New Hampshire. She liked the colony,
which is for published writers, but wondered where people who hadn't
published anything could go.
   ``The idea for Hedgebrook became attractive to me,'' Nordhoff
says. ``A place where I could say, `I care about women writers and
support what you are doing _ even if you haven't been published.'''
   A selection committee composed of five writers recommended to
Nordoff by bookstore owners, English professors and librarians,
screens the applicants. Two of the five are men. Nordhoff says they
look for women who are dedicated to being a writer. ``We want people
who can't not write,'' she says.
   An applicant must submit a sample of her writing and a letter
saying why she feels a stay at Hedgebrook Farm would be important
for her work.
   Letters from women have been pouring into Hedgebrook:
   ``I have seven children and there hasn't been much opportunity
for quiet in my life,'' wrote a Pennsylvania woman who wants to
write poetry.
   A 42-year-old counselor for disabled people in New Mexico wrote:
``I have been writing poetry since I was a teen-ager. For a long
time I put my work as a counselor first, but now I realize I need to
nurture parts of me I had previously set aside.''
   Although Nordhoff started out advertising mainly through local
networks, she is now receiving applications from all over the
country.
   She hopes to eventually accept writers from different locations,
but for now is focusing on writers from the Northwest.
   Fourteen writers were in residence at some time during the first
session that ended Dec. 10. The next session, which runs from Jan.
10 to June 30, can accommodate 18.
   Residents have included Judith Barringer, a published poet from
Portland, Ore., who used her stay to finish a second book of poems.
   Sharon Hashimoto of Seattle, who stayed for a month, used her
time to pull together a book of poems and write several short
stories. A science-fiction writer finished a couple of chapters.
   Writers choose how long they want to stay _ anywhere from a week
to two months.
   ``I feel fortunate to be able to do this,'' Nordhoff says.
``Helping an artist do her work _ that's the joy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
