<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1454EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv25   12-12 0916</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv25,0937</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Tyler Moore has six Emmys for two of the
best TV shows ever. She is a member of the Television Hall of Fame
and is co-founder of a studio that has made her one of the
wealthiest women in television.
   She has nothing left to prove in her trade.
   Yet, Moore is back in the trenches with a new CBS show called
``Annie McGuire.'' The show is near the bottom of the weekly Nielsen
ratings, along with ``The Van Dyke Show,'' a new effort by her
former co-star in ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' in the 1960s.
   She's struggling to survive in a ratings war that has changed
radically since she reigned in the 1970s with ``The Mary Tyler Moore
Show.'' Independent stations, syndicated shows, cable, pay channels,
video cassettes and the upstart Fox Broadcasting Co. are all
relatively new combatants in the ratings war. CBS, now mired
ingloriously in third place, no longer brags that it's the Tiffany
Network.
   ``You can't run away from it because it's tough,'' says Moore,
whose last situation comedy, ``Mary,'' and two attempts at a variety
show failed. ``Acting is what I do for a living. By that, I mean I
live to act. As long as I'm healthy enough I want to find a medium
to express myself. I hope to be playing old ladies in the near
future.
   ``It has nothing to do with money. It has to do with the joy one
has in plying one's trade. This is fun for me. It's rewarding.''
   Moore obviously does not need the money. She's quite wealthy from
the sale of MTM Enterprises, which she co-founded with former
husband Grant Tinker, to Britain's TVS. She retains a 20 percent
ownership.
   Eight years ago she moved to New York for the stage play ``Whose
Life Is It, Anyway?,'' then decided to stay. She has been married
for the past five years to a New York cardiologist, Dr. S. Robert
Levine. They also have a home in New York's Duchess County, where
Moore says she has discovered such pastimes as gardening, walking
and horseback riding.
   ``I've become almost bucolic,'' she says.
   Still, Moore, who professes she gets homesick for New York the
instant she crosses the Hudson River, is back in L.A. doing another
sitcom.
   Moore, wearing a red warm-up suit with her hair cut stylishly
short, is sitting on a couch in her trailer parked outside Stage 3
at the MTM Studios. It's the same trailer she used for ``The Mary
Tyler Moore Show'' and was also once used by Judy Garland.
   Up close, despite her diabetic condition and too many years spent
exposing her skin to the California sun, she looks as good as her
bank account. She credits this to a change in lifestyle. She has
quit smoking, does light impact aerobics and has adopted a healthier
diet.
   In ``Annie McGuire,'' Moore is a woman who works for the
Manhattan borough president, has a teen-age son and remarries a
structural engineer with a son and daughter. She has a mother
(Eileen Heckart) who's an ultra-liberal activist, and her new
husband (Denis Arndt) has a father (John Randolph) who's a staunch
conservative.
   The stories are a little different from the usual sitcom fare. In
one show she's held up by a man in a wheelchair, then feels
obligated to find him a job. In another, her husband admits to
having had an affair with his late wife's sister. Once, she had to
clear her father-in-law's reputation from an old accusation that
food poisoning in his restaurant cost Thomas E. Dewey the presidency.
   ``We're breaking a few molds,'' she says. ``We do some outlandish
things and conduct ourselves like adults having a great time.''
   It's Moore's first one-camera show without an audience since she
displayed only her legs as ``Sam'' on ``Richard Diamond, Private
Detective,'' in 1959. She says she finds it a much easier way to
work.
   ``CBS had asked me to come back and do another series after the
last attempt failed,'' she says. ``We wanted Elliot Shoenman, who
had been on `The Cosby Show,' to create the show. We talked over
various concepts for about a year.
   ``We did miscast a very talented actor (Edward J. Moore) as my
husband. He was replaced by Denis Arndt. And the first show turned
out a little broader than what we had in mind. But that's what CBS
saw and this put us in at 8:30 p.m. after Dick Van Dyke's new show,
which is very broad.''
   The writers strike gave them time to think it over. The first
show was scrapped and the first show on the air was actually the
second show. Moore says she wants CBS to move the show because she
feels its adult content deserves a later time slot.
   Moore realizes it's impossible to avoid comparisons to Mary
Richards, her character in ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show.''
   ``But Annie is radically different from Mary Richards,'' she
says. ``Annie's more mature, more creative and not as compulsive.
She can have a wrinkle in her skirt or a stain on her blouse.
Annie's a care-giver, she gives of herself to other people. She's
not terribly organized. She's a little cynical. She's
free-spirited.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
