<DOCNO> AP881212-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 2100EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReviews Adv00   12-12 0855</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Reviews, Adv00,0886</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At The Movies: ``Rain Man,'' ``The Naked Gun''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Rain Man''
   
   The autistic savant syndrome has been used to describe ``a
spectacular skill or talent that occurs in an autistic or retarded
child.'' It might seem a likely subject for a disease-of-the-month
television movie. Instead, it is the theme of a motion picture,
``Rain Man,'' which is the most original and compelling American
drama since ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.''
   Yes, it's a drama, though, as in ``Cuckoo,'' there are hearty
laughs. Essentially it's the saga of two long-lost brothers seeking
a reconciliation against heavy odds.
   Cruise is a rapacious wheeler-dealer trying to make a bundle by
importing sports cars in Los Angeles. His major deal is interrupted
by news that his father, from whom he was long estranged, has died
in Cincinnati. Cruise attends the funeral and learns he has been
disinherited. His father's $3 million estate has been placed in
trust.
   But for whom? Cruise is astounded to learn that he has an older
brother, Hoffman, who has been institutionalized most of his life.
Cruise decides to virtually kidnap the brother and fight the will in
California.
   Hoffman may seem like an automaton, but he has a superhuman way
with numbers. This pays off at the blackjack table in Las Vegas.
That helps ameliorate Cruise's rage, and he begins to understand and
cope with his brother.
   No good to give away all the plot. Suffice to say that the
inspired script by Ronald Bass and Barry Morrow (based on Morrow's
story) offers a wealth of surprises, both comedic and dramatic.
   Barry Levinson (``Tin Men,'' ``Good Morning, Vietnam'') directs
in masterful style. It is his best effort in what promises to be a
distinguished career. He maintains a beautiful balance between the
hard-driving, cynical Cruise and the childlike Hoffman.
   Hoffman's performance is astounding. He gets inside the skin of
Raymond Babbitt and never allows him to become monotonous or
pitiable. Cruise, dashing in his ``Risky Business'' shades, carries
a heavy load, talking at a fast clip as the car dealer and as the
exasperated brother struggling to communicate with Raymond. Cruise
has emerged as a superb actor as well as teen-age heartthrob.
   Valerina Golino is excellent as Cruise's understanding
girlfriend. Jerry Molen injects humanity into his role as Raymond's
guardian.
   Mark Johnson produced the United Artists film which is rated R,
mostly for Cruise's expletives. Running time: 130 minutes.
   _ By Bob Thomas, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Naked Gun''
   
   When was the last time you had some real fun at a movie? If you
have to stop and think, then run, don't walk, to the nearest theater
showing, ``The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad.''
   Be prepared for a zany, side-splitting collection of gags _ some
of them off color and most of them outrageous. And get ready to give
your laugh muscles a workout.
   ``Naked Gun'' is the latest product of those masters of hilarity,
David Zucker, Jim Abrahams and Jerry Zucker, who gave us the
memorable ``Airplane!'' and the not-so-memorable ``Top Secret!''
   This time they're parodying one of their own failures, the short
lived TV series, ``Police Squad!''
   Tried and true Leslie Nielsen is back as the unsmiling klutz of
the police world, Lt. Frank Drebin, who smashes police cars into
trash cans, gets his hand stuck in a fish tank and falls over his
own feet in the pursuit of justice. He's wonderful.
   Drebin, trying to foil a plot on the life of Queen Elizabeth II,
sets off a series of hilarious non-stop gags. For instance, he winds
up as the singer of the National Anthem and the umpire at a major
league baseball game where Reggie Jackson plays an unexpected role
as assassin-in-waiting.
   David Zucker's direction of these complex sight gags is flawless.
   Priscilla Presley is Drebin's romantic interest, Jane Spencer,
whose deadpan delivery is a match for Nielsen's. A scene in which
the two practice ``safe sex'' in body size condoms is typical of the
giggle power of this film.
   There is a villain, played by a silky Ricardo Montalban, a
bemused sidekick played by George Kennedy and lots of celebrity
cameos as well as a dumpy Queen Elizabeth look-alike.
   There are no messages here, and the story is just an excuse for
some terrific jokes. Call it slapstick. Call it crazy. Call it a hit.
   ``Naked Gun'' is rated PG-13 for language, double entendres and
implied nudity. The very young might wonder why the adults are
falling on the floor laughing.
   _ By Linda Deutsch, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
