<DOCNO> AP881212-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 2102EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   12-12 1146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv00,1197</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Funny Farm'' (Warner Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95; Rated PG)
   
   It takes courage for the makers of a comedy to put the word
``funny'' in the title. Sometimes it's an accurate assessment, as in
``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum,'' that 1966 bawdy
farce starring Zero Mostel.
   Then again, it might be the kiss of death. And Warner Bros.
``Funny Farm'' definitely shows signs of rigor mortis. This Chevy
Chase comedy is about as funny as picking cotton on a 103-degree
August day. The laughs, such as they are, are forced and the
situations predictable. The video reeks of country bumpkin cliches,
and Chase, as usual, does a turn or two with Murphy's Law.
   What makes this movie an even greater travesty is that it's
directed by George Roy Hill, who made the very excellent ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' and the Academy Award-winning ``The
Sting.''
   The thin story line revolves around a writer and his wife who
decide to leave the noise, filth and crowds of city life for the
bucolic splendors of the country. There our hero hopes to write THE
GREAT AMERICAN NOVEL. Instead, he becomes blocked out of his mind,
grows fat and lazy and idles while his wife turns a simple
experience with a squirrel into a best-selling children's book.
   In its theatrical release, ``Funny Farm,'' which co-stars Madolyn
Smith (``Urban Cowboy,'' ``All of Me''), stayed around for a blink.
   Perhaps some kind-hearted filmmaker will one day find some decent
material for Chase, whose acting talents and comedic genius have
been dashed in Hollywood. In the meantime, if you want to see this
basic plot work well, get the Kingston video, ``Mr. Blandings Builds
His Dream House.'' The 1948 black and white comedy stars Cary Grant,
Myrna Loy and Melvyn Douglas.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Sunset'' (RCA-Columbia Pictures Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95;
Rated R)
   
   What if Wyatt Earp met Tom Mix, and the legendary heroes team up
to solve a murder and get the bad guys? In Blake Edwards'
``Sunset,'' the real-life cowboys do indeed get together for what
turns out to be a surprisingly delightful romp.
   James Garner and Bruce Willis star as Earp and Mix respectively.
It's an interesting pairing that produces just the right screen
chemistry. Garner is his usual homey good-guy with just the right
amount of laidback seasoning. Willis, usually brash and pseudo-hip,
plays Mix with a certain reserve and honesty.
   The time is Hollywood in the 1920s. Mix is the hottest action
actor around, and has been cast to portray the great lawman Wyatt
Earp. Earp has been hired to be a consultant on the film. Only
problem is, the movie is pure Hollywood hogwash and Earp's character
is made to look like a moron. The movie doesn't sit too well with
Mix, either. So the two heroes soon have a meeting of the minds.
   Meanwhile, back at the ranch so to speak, the studio boss' wife
is an old pal of Earp's and asks him to help her with a little
problem. This tiny problem turns out to involve murder and scandal
and is centered on her husband, a venal brute played viciously by
Malcolm McDowell.
   The dialogue from Edwards' slick screenplay (based on a story by
Rod Amateau) is fresh and funny, and the action and adventure lure
us to another time, the glittery golden age of Hollywood. And best
of all, it's all true _ give or take a lie or two.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Dead'' (Vestron Video; VHS-Beta, $89.98; Rated PG)
   
   While most of ``The Dead'' takes place at a Christmas party, this
is not a video to watch with a bunch of pals and a few beers. John
Huston's interpretation of James Joyce's short story is quiet,
powerful and elegant.
   It requires attention, and you will be rewarded. ``The Dead'' can
be funny and sweet, but its lasting impression is a profoundly sad
vision of the lack of connection between a husband and wife.
   The story unravels during a rather proper but entertaining party
given annually by two unmarried sisters and their niece in 1904
Dublin. Among the guests are young lovers, a drunk, a rebellious
nationalist woman and the couple, Gretta (Anjelica Huston) and
Gabriel Conroy (Donal McCann).
   Anjelica Huston is a beautiful and surprisingly authentic Irish
woman, tormented by the memory a young man she loved as a teen-ager
and who she believes died for her.
   As those memories slowly are stirred by various events at the
party, Gabriel comes finally to realize ``how poor a part I've
played'' in her life. His preoccupation with a speech he gives at
the party suddenly seems so trivial, and his steadfastness so dreary.
   Nominated for an Academy Award for best screenplay, by Huston's
son, Tony, ``The Dead'' was finished just before John Huston died in
August 1987.
   ``The Dead'' is lovely to look at and truly moving.
   _ By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Verne Miller'' (Nelson Entertainment; VHS-Beta, $79.98; Rated R)
   
   ``Verne Miller'' is a tight, fast-paced, entertaining and
ostensibly accurate portrait of the Prohibition-era
lawman-turned-gangster who engineered the botched and bloody
``Kansas City Massacre'' trying to spring a pal.
   Scott Glenn has the title role of this unpretentious gangster
movie. He invests his character with a grace, nobility and charm the
real Verne Miller lacked.
   Filmed mostly on location in Alabama, it's full of nice period
costumes and architecture that frame some gorgeous performances,
including the brilliant Thomas G. Waites as Al Capone, Ed O'Ross as
brother Ralph Capone, Barbara Stock as speakeasy chanteuse Vi, and
Richard Bright as Adam Richetti.
   Writer-director Rod Hewitt took some chances with his abrupt
montage, but it works: Months pass between some scenes, minutes and
seconds between others. Yet each has its own compelling logic on the
journey Miller is making.
   On Nov. 29, 1933, Miller was found shot to death in a ditch
outside Detroit. Glenn's performance is so poised and intense that
he can give you the character while withholding his secrets.
Ultimately we don't know Verne Miller. But then, Glenn makes us wish
we could.
   This one's a real find.
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
