<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Thompson Adv23-25   12-12 0862</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Thompson, Adv23-25,0890</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec 23-25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Richard Thompson Still Has a Sense of Purpose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Thompson has been making records for over
20 years. His music, though, draws on sources much older.
   ``I hope that things like age aren't that important,'' said
Thompson, 39, a guitarist, singer and songwriter who helped form the
seminal English folk-rock group, Fairport Convention, in 1967.
``When I was 20, I was listening to people who were dead. You have
to listen to everything.''
   Fairport Convention seemed to work in the opposite direction of
rock music at the time. Instead of being influenced by the
psychedelic sounds of the Beatles on ``Sgt. Pepper,'' Fairport
Convention incorporated music from previous centuries. Rather than
use backward tape loops and distorted guitars, Fairport Convention
experimented with the fiddle and mandolin.
   Thompson, who left the group in 1971, recalled the sense of
purpose the members shared.
   ``We were concerned about reviving a traditional music in
Britain. I listened to a lot of Scottish music. That's a thing
that's important to me. We listened to traditional music and jazz
and rock 'n' roll.
   ``There was a great spirit of camaraderie and musical
exploration. I remember a feeling of kinship with the bandmates at
the time.''
   And hit singles were not important.
   ``I never even thought about it. It never crossed my mind that I
was going into the music business. I just found myself being a
professional musician.''
   His first solo album, ``Henry the Human Fly,'' came out in 1972,
and combined folk-rock music with Thompson's hard-edged singing.
   The same year, he married Linda Peters, a former backup singer,
and the two went on to record seven LPs together. In 1982, they
released ``Shoot Out the Lights,'' one of the most acclaimed records
of the year, but were divorced soon after.
   The popularity of the recording duo threatened to overshadow
Thompson's solo career as fans speculated whether his often bitter
love songs were about Peters.
   ``Songs are really work of the imagination,'' Thompson said. ``I
think it's putting too much of a limit to say this song's about this
person or that person. It should be bigger than that.''
   In ``I Still Dream,'' a ballad off his new album, ``Amnesia,''
Thompson sings: ``And I never was to know that I'd come to miss you
so. But time winds down and I turned my back long ago.'' He stressed
the song was not about his ex-wife.
   ``It's really a story song. It's not me. I'm telling a story
about a guy whose life seems aimless. It seems dull and dead. He's
compromised himself all the way.''
   Thompson took six weeks to make ``Amnesia,'' and for the first
time, recorded in the United States. ``Yankee, Go Home,'' another
song from the LP, might impress listeners as an attack against
American imperialisn, but Thompson doesn't see it that way.
   ``I see it as a friendly arm around the shoulder of America.
Saying how we in England used to have an empire and it got frittered
away. Finally, we've learned to adjust to this `tragic' fact. Now
it's your turn. It's time for America not to be Number 1.''
   On ``Jerusalem on the Jukebox,'' Thompson deals with a subject
familiar to most Americans: television evangelists.
   ```Jerusalem' is the name of a hymn sung in England. It's a great
song. I heard it played on a television show and was so alarmed that
things would reach this point.
   ``Is (evangelist) Jimmy Swaggert the tip of the iceberg? What
passes for spirituality?''
   Thompson says there is not yet an English equivalent to Jimmy
Swaggert, but there is the possibility: ``Britain is dying for
someone like Jimmy Swaggert. That sort of professional sincerity.
He'd be huge in Britain.''
   Many of Thompson's songs have sad overtones. He sings about
jealousy, lost love, death. But he noted that just because songs are
about sad events, they're not necessarily sad songs.
   ``It's sad, but cathartic. Expressing sadness isn't such a sad
business. It can make you feel quite good. I supposed I'm a really a
realist.''
   A realist, not a cynic. Rock was once considered a music for
young people, but many of its greatest performers are now
middle-aged and have struggled for a reason to continue.
   Not Thompson.
   ``Every once in a while, I step to one side and ask myself the
reason I'm playing music. Having re-established the direction, it's
easier to keep going,'' he said.
   ``If you see music as experiment and education, there is no end
to it. You're always looking for the next thing. If you're
commercially successful and you see that as the end, there's going
to be a real anti-climax.''
   And Thompson still believes in drawing on a wide array of music,
regardless of how many records he sells.
   ``Rock 'n' roll is now so multi-generational. You can fit almost
every musical style in existence into rock music these days. I'm on
the edge of it rather than the middle of it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec 23-25</NOTE>
