<1ST_LINE>a a BC-YE--Science'88 Adv00   12-12 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-YE--Science '88, Adv 00,0347</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Year's Top 10 Science Stories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   These were some of the top science stories of 1988:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SUPERCONDUCTIVITY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Researchers set a new high-temperature record, producing
compounds that became superconducting _ able to conduct electricity
without resistance _ at 234 degrees below zero Fahrenheit.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GENETICS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Researchers created a genetically engineered mouse with a human
immune system, and a patent was awarded for the first time to a
genetically engineered animal _ a mouse into which a cancer gene had
been inserted.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SPACE SHUTTLES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. space shuttle program resumed and the Soviets launched
their own shuttle on its first mission.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GREENHOUSE EFFECT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A summer drought across the United States led some scientists to
say that evidence of climatic changes produced by global warming _
the so-called ``greenhouse effect'' _ is already being felt.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RADON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The problem of radon gas in homes was recognized to be far more
widespread than previously believed, and the EPA estimated that
radon causes 20,000 deaths from lung cancer annually.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ABORTION PILL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   France approved the sale of an ``abortion pill,'' an anti-hormone
that interrupts pregnancy by blocking the implantation of a
fertilized egg on the uterine wall.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ASPIRIN AND HEART DISEASE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A study of 22,071 male doctors showed that a single aspirin a day
can cut the risk of heart attacks almost in half.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A new, more accurate means of testing for AIDS was developed, but
some researchers expressed disappointment that more treatments for
the deadly disease had not yet been found.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SUPERCOLLIDER</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A building site was selected in Texas for the $4.4 billion
superconducting super collider, bringing the world's largest atom
smasher a step closer to realization.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ASTRONOMY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Canadian astronomers reported the existence of 10
planet-like objects orbiting distant stars, rekindling speculation
about the existence of life beyond Earth.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Year-End Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
