<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Deals     12-12 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Deals,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Deals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   If you're under 50, skip this story.
   If you read it, you may wish you were older.
   Joan Rattner Heilman _ who is over 50 _ has compiled a book of
bargains for those born at least half a century ago, with
information varying from hotel, motel and restaurant discounts to
over-50 bike tours and ski clubs.
   Titled ``Unbelievably Good Deals and Great Adventures That You
Absolutely Can't Get Unless You're Over 50'' (Contemporary Books),
the paperback also deals with travel and tour tips, breaks on
airfare and car rentals, perks in parks, even going back to school.
   The idea for the book started with Ms. Heilman's national
magazine article, which got a response indicating ``everybody is
interested'' in the subject, she says. With about one-quarter of the
nation's population in the over-50 category, ``everybody is jumping
on the bandwagon and there are new things all the time,'' says Ms.
Heilman.
   She has updated the original 1988 book with some new ``deals''
for a 1989 edition.
   ``On your 50th birthday,'' Ms. Heilman writes, ``you qualify for
hundreds of special opportunities and money-saving offers that will
have lots of people wishing they were older. All for a couple of
good reasons.
   ``First, you deserve them, having successfully negotiated your
way through life's white waters.
   ``And second, as the fastest-growing segment of the American
population, you represent an enormous market of potential consumers,
a fact that has become quite apparent to the business community.''
   Her biggest piece of advice: ``Make a practice of asking if there
are breaks to which you are entitled wherever you go, from movies to
museums, concerts to historic sites, hotels to ski resorts,
restaurants to riverboats, in this country and abroad. Don't expect
clerks or ticket agents to volunteer them to you.''
   She adds: ``Remember to request your privileges before you pay or
when you order or make reservations, and always carry proof of age
or an over-50-club membership card, or, better yet, both.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   (The book is available at bookstores or by mail order from Best
Publications, Dept. UGD, 180 N. Michigan Ave., Chicago, Ill. 60601,
at $8.50 for the first copy and 50 cents more for each additional
copy.)
</TEXT>
