<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:RVs     12-12 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: RVs,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: RVs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY704, NY705</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of mature Americans are spending their time,
independence and money on traveling in recreation vehicles, reports
a national association for the retired.
   The American Association of Retired Persons (AARP) estimates that
nine million senior Americans use recreation vehicles each year.
   ``Mature travelers are good candidates for RV travel,'' says Ron
Noe, member services specialist for AARP, ``because many have the
time, discretionary funds and desire to see and experience the small
towns, big cities, popular attractions and natural beauty of the
United States.
   ``RVs provide them with an enjoyable, comfortable and economical
way to take it all in and enjoy the social benefits of camaraderie
on the road.''
   A University of Michigan survey of the recreation vehicle
consumer reported that nearly 10 percent of heads of households over
50 who own vehicles own 30 percent of the RVs in use.
   AARP reports that RV trips account for 18 percent of all trips
taken by those in the 55-59 age group. Seventy-two percent of all RV
trips are made by travelers 50 years and older, AARP says.
   Recreation vehicles include motor homes, travel trailers, truck
campers, folding camping trailers and van conversions.
</TEXT>
