<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0551EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Drivers     12-12 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Drivers,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Drivers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Older drivers pose a greater risk of being
involved in accidents but driving should not be restricted solely on
the basis of age, says a recent government study.
   The study by the National Research Council says roadway signs and
markings should be redesigned to better meet the needs of older
drivers, and that screening should be improved to identify impaired
drivers of all ages.
   The report urges states to tighten their screening programs and
issue restricted licenses in some cases such as limiting certain
applicants to daytime driving only.
   It criticized a movement in some states to allow drivers licenses
to be renewed by mail without drivers being required to undergo
vision tests at least every four years.
   But the study concluded that ``age alone is a poor predictor of
the (driving) performance of any individual,'' although
acknowledging after age 75 a driver is ``about twice as likely (per
mile driven) to be involved in a crash'' as middle-aged drivers.
   The National Research Council panel, composed of experts
assembled by the National Academy of Sciences, spent two years
examining questions about transportation and the elderly.
   It said problems of meeting the transportation needs of older
citizens will increase in the years ahead as the numer of people
over 75 increases and more elderly people live in the suburbs where
less public transportation is available.
   ``The states are not prepared to handle the growing number of
very old drivers or to identify those at high risk of accident
involvement,'' the study concluded.
   ``Most older persons will probably be quite capable and safe
drivers. But current statistics indicate that drivers 75 and over
are more at risk of crash involvement than the average driver. ...
Thes facts must be acknowledged even though there is no
justification for restricting driving on the basis of age alone.''
   Furthermore, the panel said, elderly people are more likely to
suffer serious or fatal injuries than other drivers in accidents of
similar severity.
   The study said elderly people, especially those 75 years or
older, often have problems reading traffic signs, seeing clearly at
night, gauging traffic flow when merging into traffic or making left
turns, and turning their heads when backing their vehicles.
   But ``when examined in terms of incidents, the problem that older
persons represent to overall traffic safety is small relative to
that of the (teen-age) driver,'' the committee wrote.
   The panel encouraged older drivers to buy automobiles equipped
with air bags, the devices that inflate automatically to protect the
head and upper torso in a crash.
   The committee also urged the use of seat belts, but suggested
manufacturers could make them more comfortable and easier to use. It
also suggested that roadway markings and signs be made larger or
brighter. It said the current road sign standard currently exceeds
the visual ability of about 40 percent of drivers who are 65 years
or older.
   Even with various design improvements in the coming years, an
increasing number of older people will require public transportation.
   Communities should improve public transit for the elderly,
develop subsidized taxi programs and construct walkways in suburban
areas if the transportation requirements of the elderly are to be
met, the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0551EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:WithDrivers-Vision     12-12 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: With Drivers-Vision,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: With Drivers-Vision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Older adults generally do not have to give up driving because of
aging changes in vision _ but they should recognize their
limitations, advises the American Optometric Association.
   More than 37 million Americans over 55 years old drive, and
according to the National Safety Council they have a poorer accident
record than drivers in their middle years.
   Failure to yield right-of-way, improper lane changes, passing and
turning are among the most common traffic violations committed by
older drivers, national studies have shown.
   According to the optometrists, changes in vision may interfere
with older drivers' abilities to see and recognize what is on the
road ahead, to see effectively at night, to see against the glare of
oncoming headlights and to recover quickly from glare.
   Other factors include faulty judging of distances between
themselves and other vehicles or objects, and the detection of
movement from the side while looking straight ahead.
   Suggestions from the optometrists on how older drivers can
compensate for vision changes include:
   _ Avoid driving at dusk.
   _ When driving at night, reduce speed, try to limit driving to
well-lighted or familiar roads, and keep headlights, taillights and
turn signals clean and properly adjusted.
   _ Take time to adjust to a new eyeglass or contact lens
prescription before driving.
   _ Avoid frames with wide side pieces that may block side vision.
   _ Wear quality sunglasses on sunny or bright, cloudy days, but
never wear sunglasses, or fashion-tinted lenses, when driving at
night.
   _ Confine driving to places, speeds and hours in which they are
comfortable and competent.
   _ Avoid pulling off alongside the highway. If necessary, use the
car's four-way emergency flashers.
   _ Keep windshield and rear windows clean, inside and out, and
replace worn wiper blades promptly.
   _ Keep rear view and outside mirrors clean and properly adjusted.
Be aware of their limitations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0552EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Alone     12-12 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Alone,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Alone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elderly Americans living alone were more likely
to still be alive two years later than those who made their home
with someone other than a spouse, a government researcher has
reported.
   More than three-quarters of them also were still living
independently after two years, said Dr. Mary Grace Kovar of the
National Center for Health Statistics.
   Her findings are based on interviews in 1984 and 1986 with people
who had been aged 70 and over in 1984.
   ``The most important thing is the stability. Most of these
people, two years later, are still living in the community. Those
who were living alone are still alone, and those with someone else
are still with someone else,'' Kovar said in a telephone interview.
   ``As you would expect, because these people are 72 or older,
death rates are high. But relatively few of them are in nursing
homes,'' she said.
   Of nearly 6.4 million elderly Americans living alone in 1984,
89.8 percent were still alive two years later, the study found.
   By comparison, 87.3 percent of those living with others survived
two years. Those living with a spouse did nearly as well as those
alone, 89.0 percent surviving. But, of those living with someone
else _ friends or family _ only 84.3 percent were still alive.
   People living with brothers and sisters tended to live longer,
but that may have been because longevity ran in the family, Kovar
speculated.
   Of those who had been on their own in 1984, 77.8 percent were
still living by themselves in 1986, she found. About 7.4 percent of
them had moved in with someone else _ most often family _ and 4.6
percent were in an institution.
   ``It certainly appears that for some of them life is better'' two
years later, Kovar said. ``Some have remarried ... and when we asked
those who had moved why ... we got'' answers ranging from health to
being nearer to children to spending the summer in Maine and winter
in Florida. One, she commented, even cited lower golf fees for
moving.
   A major factor in continued independence is likely that those
living alone were more healthy at the start of the study, she
concluded in the report, ``Aging in the Eighties, People Living
Alone _ Two Years Later.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0552EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:NursingHomes     12-12 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Nursing Homes,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Nursing Homes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 40 percent of nursing homes failed to
meet sanitary standards for food and nearly 30 percent failed to
meet standards for maintaining residents' personal cleanliness,
according to the federal government's first consumer guide to
nursing homes.
   The survey also found that more than one-fourth of the nursing
homes do not administer drugs properly.
   However, Dr. William L. Roper, chief of the Health Care Financing
Administration that compiled and released the statistics, cautioned
against reading more into the figures than is warranted.
   ``This is not the ultimate report card for nursing homes around
the country,'' Roper told reporters.
   He said the ``met-unmet'' criteria for each of the 32 categories
included in the state-by-state reports contains no measure of
severity and represented a one-time ``snapshot'' of conditions at
the nursing home's most recent unannounced inspection. To some
degree, he said, it relied on the subjective judgment of the
inspector.
   At the same time, Roper defended release of the report against
industry criticism that it would mislead consumers.
   One complaint was, for example, that a nursing home might be
given an ``unmet'' mark on proper administration of medication if
one patient was five minutes late getting his or her medicine.
   ``If one person was five minutes late, I'm sure they would not
have been dinged in the survey,'' Roper said. ``What we're looking
at, what the surveyors look at is the pattern of care over time.
   ``We are not in the business of making arbitrary, bureaucratic
judgments. We are trying to evaluate what is really happening to
people in that nursing home.''
   He added:
   ``What we are looking for ... is not nursing home providers that
barely scrape by. We're looking for people who are good providers,
consistently, over time, 365 days a year. And I have to believe that
if that's where a nursing home operator has his or her nursing home,
they are not going to be worried about being dinged on some trivial
point.''
   The 75-volume guide shows how each of the 15,000 nursing homes
fared on 32 health, safety and care standards based on periodic
inspections by state agencies. About 2,400 of the 15,000 received
passing marks in all 32 categories.
   According to the survey, nearly 43 percent of the homes failed to
meet sanitary standards for food. Almost 30 percent failed to meet
standards for maintaining residents' personal cleanliness and 29
percent failed to administer drugs according to doctors' orders.
   However, the report also said that only a small percentage of the
nursing homes failed to meet standards in many other categories.
Overall among skilled homes, the failure rate exceeded 15 percent in
only 10 categories.
   Paul Willging, executive vice president of the American Health
Care Association, which represents more than 9,000 nursing homes,
said the report ``is misleading _ it is going to confuse the
public'' by making it appear conditions are worse than they are. He
said that something like a cracked egg in a refrigerator could lead
to a nursing home failing to meet a care standard.
   But Elma Holder, executive director of the National Citizens'
Coalition on Nursing Home Reform, said: ``We think the national
statistics are misleading. Conditions are worse.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0552EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Alzheimer's     12-12 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Alzheimer's,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Alzheimer's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The focus on Alzheimer's disease generally is on the patients,
not their families.
   But a new program uses coloring books, a mascot dog and movies to
show elementary school pupils how the debilitating ailment can be
battled. For a few hours, the students put aside their reading,
writing and arithmetic to look at a disease that may not afflict
them for 60 years, if at all.
   The purpose of the effort is not so much to understand how the
disease works but to show how the loved ones of an Alzheimer's
sufferer can, with patience, helpful advice and love, minimize the
worst of the disease's effects.
   Alzheimer's, characterized by memory loss and other dementia,
afflicts an estimated 5 million mostly elderly Americans.
   The southern Massachusetts town of Westport, which is in the
third year of a federal Health and Human Services grant intended to
promote community programs, developed the daylong seminar on
Alzheimer's after meetings between school officials and William
Connolly of New Jersey-based Sandoz Pharmaceuticals Corp., who
spends summers there. Sandoz manufactures Hydergine, a drug that can
ease some symptoms of Alzheimer's in milder cases.
   Westport changed the emphasis because of mounting evidence that
children are often acutely aware of and confused by the decline of a
loved one.
   A coloring book titled ``Helping Grandma,'' by Westport High
School art teacher Betsey MacDonald, told the story of a grandmother
who gradually begins to show signs of memory loss.
   ``Children are often kept in the dark about aging,'' said
MacDonald. ``They automatically think that `old' means `sick.' But
children are wonderfully resilient and surprisingly insightful when
spoken to directly on the subject.''
   The point of the coloring book, geared toward elementary school
children, is to ``teach them understanding and to teach them that
what she needs is support.''
   Also, mature, well-behaved dogs from an animal shelter can
provide some stability and love for an Alzheimer's sufferer,
Connolly said. Jeff, a black and white mongrel from a Rhode Island
animal shelter, has become the national poster dog for the so-called
human-animal bonding campaign, and he travels with Connolly to
events on the subject.
   The Alzheimer's event was tried out earlier this year in
Bloomington, Ind.
</TEXT>
