<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0553EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Osteoporosis     12-12 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Osteoporosis,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Osteoporosis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women can help prevent brittle bones in old age by
regularly consuming dairy products throughout their lives, but
calcium supplements taken after menopause probably won't be
effective, researchers say.
   In a study in the Journal of the American Medical Association,
researchers said the key factors in bone density among
post-menopausal women were lifelong calcium intake and the naturally
occurring hormone estrone.
   Moderate exercise and calcium supplements taken later in life do
not appear to prevent osteoporosis, a frequently debilitating
disease most common among women in which the bones become thinner
and more brittle, they found.
   ``Swallowing calcium pills at 50 years of age probably is not
going to make your bones thicker,'' said Dr. Lewis Kuller, of the
Epidemiology Department at the University of Pittsburgh's School of
Public Health.
   Kuller, a co-author of the study involving 174 healthy
post-menopausal women over a four-year period, also said, ``There is
no evidence that moderate exercise in these women increased their
bone density.''
   ``The most important message ... is that an adequate calcium
intake during childhood, adolescence, post-adolescence and the
reproductive years is probably a very important part of good health
and will probably help prevent bone fracture and osteoporosis,'' he
said.
   Osteoporosis results in a loss of bone density and can lead to
bone fractures and spinal problems like dowager's hump. Some
estimates project that by age 70, one-quarter of the women in North
America will have suffered a fracture related to the disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0553EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Arthritis     12-12 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Arthritis,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Arthritis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Use the rubber end of a pencil or pen to push the buttons of a
telephone or turn the pages of a book.
   Use an electric stapler to help reduce fatigue in hands, wrists
and shoulders.
   If you aren't up to typing, use a dictating machine.
   These are among suggestions for office workers who suffer from
arthritis to help ease their work. The advice comes from Frances
Mason, who has had rheumatoid and psoriatic arthritis for nearly 20
years and is now a volunteer counselor for the New York chapter of
the Arthritis Foundation.
   ``Until recently,'' she said in a recent issue of AIMplus, an
arthritis information magazine, ``people with arthritis found it
very difficult to keep on working _ not because they didn't want to,
but because the attitude of society in generally has been that a
disabled person `just couldn't do the job.'''
   While attitudes have changed, she said, and many disabled persons
are finding less difficulty in finding and keeping a job, ``some
people with arthritis may find that their condition does somewhat
limit their abilities to accomplish as much as they would like.''
   She offers some other suggestions to ease that problem:
   _ Conserve energy by planning ahead; schedule the more demanding
tasks for times of day when you are feeling your best.
   _ Make sure your chair provides firm support for your lower back
and has armrests to help reduce fatigue in your shoulders. The chair
should be high enough to get in and out of without strain, and low
enough so you don't have to hunch over while working.
   _ To ease strain on your neck, place text on a tying rack rather
than keeping it flat beside your desk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
