<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Collecting,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Collecting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Collecting, from toy soldiers to vintage perfume bottles, is one
way for grandparents to share a hobby or activity with their
grandchildren.
   ``The important thing is that it's a shared activity, a special
bond between you and your grandchild,'' says Stephen Roedler,
director of the Manhattan Arts and Antiques Center in New York.
   ``What's more, when you explore the past together, your
grandchild gets a window into former times and can better appreciate
your world, too.''
   The collection can also encourage other activities, he says, both
with the grandchild and on your own. It could mean enrolling in
courses or seminars and sharing the learning with the grandchildren.
   Museums and galleries, magazines and journals are other
resources, he says.
   Roedler says there are numerous local clubs for collectors, where
news and information is exchanged.
   He suggests the possibility of a club for grandparent-grandchild
collectors.
</TEXT>
