<DOCNO> AP881212-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0555EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Pianos     12-12 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Pianos,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Pianos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   After the children grow up and leave home, there may be a problem
left over: what to do about the piano.
   Don't let it just sit in a corner of the living room gathering
dust, says the National Piano Foundation, which suggests parents of
adult children who have left the nest can find many enjoyable ways
to keep the piano an important part of their homes.
   A piano is not only a beautiful piece of furniture, but it
represents an investment, both in time and money, according to the
foundation.
   ``There are a lot of memories attached to our piano,'' says Paul
Krouse, a publisher from Lake Forest, Ill., who bought the family
piano with his wife, Anne, when they were first married. ``Even
though my eldest daughter _ our piano enthusiast _ has moved out of
the area, I wouldn't dream of giving it up.''
   Although the Krouses are not piano players themselves, they have
kept it in frequent use by hiring pianists to play at several
parties they've hosted. And they have a few friends who play the
piano when they visit.
   One way to enjoy your piano after the kids have stopped playing,
suggests the foundation, is to take lessons yourself.
   James Sevitz, a retired mechanical engineer in Huntington Beach,
Calif., recently began piano lessons, marking the first time he's
studied piano in nearly 50 years and the first time his piano has
been used regularly since his stepdaughter moved out of the house.
   ``When I retired I had all this new-found free time,'' says
Sevitz. ``And the piano wasn't getting much use, so I decided it was
a good time to learn to play _ something I've wanted to do all my
life.''
   Sevitz signed up for a piano class in beginning techniques with
Allen Giles, head of the piano department at Golden West College in
Huntington Beach.
   Giles teaches many adult students, as well as the college's
regular student body, and finds that playing piano is something for
which ``empty-nesters'' and recent retirees are perfectly suited.
   ``Older people make excellent piano students,'' says Giles.
``Those who are retired, of course, have a lot of free time, too.
But even working adults can fit piano study into their schedules and
budgets.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
