<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Briefs     12-12 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Briefs,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Briefs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of 45- to 64-year-olds in the United States will
increase by 30 percent in the 1990s, according to a population study
sponsored by Better Homes and Gardens magazine.
   The age group will increase by 40 to 50 percent in the South and
West, and by about 20 percent in the Northeast and Southwest, the
study reported.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   One-third of elderly Americans living in their communities say
their health is excellent or very good, reports the Statistical
Bulletin, a publication of the Metropolitan Life Insurance Co.
   The findings, among those aged 65 or over, are based on a
National Health Interview Survey conducted in 1983-84. The report
said the proportion does not change among those aged 85 and over.
   However, those interviewed did not include elderly people in
hospitals or nursing homes, the segment in poorest health.
   The proportion of blacks assessing their health as excellent or
very good was one-fourth.
   The most frequently reported disability was arthritis; second was
hypertension.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Hyatt Corp.'s first senior living community, a 223-unit
rental housing complex for those over 62, is scheduled for
completion in April 1989. Called Classic Residence, it will occupy
5.44 acres in Teaneck, N.J.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In order to detect lung disease, the National Jewish Center for
Immunology and Respiratory Medicine, in Denver, suggests that senior
citizens ask for a breathing test called spirometry as part of every
physical examination.
   The spirometer measures the lungs' ``forced vital capacity,'' say
researchers at the hospital, or how well a person can force air from
the lungs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Multiple medical problems come with age, resulting in multiple
drugs,'' says the director of geriatric programs at a New York
medical center, who warns users of possible over-medication or
over-accumulation.
   ``Without careful monitoring,'' says Dr. Geraldine Lanman of the
Long Island Jewish Medical Center, New Hyde Park, N.Y., ``the drugs
that keep our elderly alive longer, can also sharply minimize the
quality of life.''
   At the Daughters of Jacob Geriatric Center in New York, where the
average age of the residents is 87, about 80 to 90 percent of them
take a ``medication holiday'' from non-essential medication each
Monday.
   ``The program is designed to cleanse the body, decrease possible
side effects and provide the opportunity to re-evaluate prescription
patterns,'' says Claire Vogelman, president of Daughters of Jacob.
``Ultimately, some medications may be changed, some eliminated
completely.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Rowing is one of the best fitness sports for older Americans,
says Frederick ``Fritz'' Hagerman, an Ohio University exercise
physiologist and consultant to U.S. rowing teams in the past five
Olympics.
   In a recent rowing study including 14 men and women over age 60,
Hagerman found that virtually all showed improvement in
cardiovascular function.
   ``Rowing has tremendous potential among older people,'' says
Hagerman, chairman of zoological and biomedical sciences at the
university.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A University of Miami professor says American men over 85 are a
privileged minority, with more money, better health and more social
contact than women the same age.
   According to Charles Longino Jr., an authority on aging
demographics, a study of Census Bureau data disclosed one of the big
differences was that nearly half the men among America's 2.2 million
very old persons had spouses, while only one-tenth of the women were
still married.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
