<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     12-12 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was higher in thin trading in Europe
late this morning, but traders said they expected no major movement
in the U.S. currency ahead of Wednesday's release of U.S. trade
figures for October.
   Gold prices also rose.
   Trading volume was light with few players keen to take a strong
position before the trade figures are released and in advance of the
bi-weekly meeting of the Bundesbank on Thursday, when the West
German central bank could decide to raise a key interest rate,
dealers said.
   One trader with a branch of a major U.S. commercial bank in Milan
said the foreign exchange market expects the October trade deficit
to be little changed from its $10.5-billion shortfall in September.
   She said a single-figure deficit would ``clearly be positive''
for the dollar, but cautioned that ``we've seen this year that this
figure is pretty difficult to call accurately.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.49 yen to a closing 122.92 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 122.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.7378 West German marks, up from 1.7330; 1.4645
Swiss francs, up from 1.4605; 5.9415 French francs, up from 5.9240;
1.9622 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9560; 1,283.20 Italian lire, up
from 1,280.25; 1.1988 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1970.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8420, compared with
$1.8490 Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $421 a troy ounce, up
from $420.70 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $421, unchanged
from the opening bid.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $421 up from $420.30 bid late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.10 to close at a bid $422.29.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.16 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Friday.
</TEXT>
