<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-12 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Plunge, Dollar Edges Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
today, while the dollar edged up against the Japanese yen as
investors remained on the sidelines ahead of trade reports, dealers
said.
   The dollar closed at 122.92 yen, up 0.49 yen from Friday's close
of 122.43 yen. The currency opened at 122.70 yen and traded between
122.70-123.00 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 121.13 points or 0.41
percent to finish trading at 29,672.29. The index, a 34.52-point
winner Friday, gained 40.35 points in early morning trading but
erased the gain and continued to drop.
   The dollar's higher opening in Tokyo followed its firmness in the
Sydney market that opened earlier, dealers said.
   The dollar moved higher as foreign investors purchased the
currency in morning trading but fluctuated around 122.80 yen,
failing to rise beyond the 123-yen level, said a dealer with
Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo.
   ``Once it reached the upper part of the 122-yen range, the dollar
hardly moved,'' the dealer said.
   He said trading was thin because many currency players were
cautious ahead of the release of trade figures this week.
   Japanese trade figures for November were to be released later
today. The U.S. Commerce Department is to report the nation's trade
figure for October on Wednesday.
   Meanwhile, Paul Volcker, former chairman of the U.S. Federal
Reserve Board, said Sunday in Tokyo that the dollar should stabilize
because its further decline would raise import prices and lead to
inflation in the United States.
   Volcker said in a lecture at a meeting called the '89 Tokyo Forum
that cutting the U.S. fiscal deficits and preventing inflation are
vital for restoring trust in the dollar.
   On the stock exchange, share prices fell as investors stayed on
the sidelines in anticipation of the release of Japanese and U.S.
trade figures this week, said Yoshio Shimoyama of the Nikko
Securities.
   Frequent fluctuations of the index and lack of direction in
trading are typical toward the end of a year, Shimoyama said.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 600 million
shares in inactive trading.
</TEXT>
