<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-China     12-12 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-China,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Concludes Textiles Agreement With China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The EEC Commission said Monday it had
concluded a new four-year agreement on trade in textiles with China.
   The agreement, to replace the existing pact which expires at the
end of the year, will increase slightly the European Economic
Community's imports of textiles from China.
   The accord also places new restrictions on selected textile
imports including synthetic yarn, knitted gloves and suits.
   In addition, some textile products that were not subject to
quotas under the existing agreement will be brought under quota
coverage, the commission said.
   Textiles account for about one third of China's exports to the
EEC. They rose to 1.24 billion European currency units, or $1.47
billion in 1987 from 893.6 million Ecus,or $1.06 million in 1986.
</TEXT>
