<DOCNO> AP881212-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0952EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Tenneco-Future     12-12 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tenneco-Future,0824</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tenneco Still Profitable After Oil and Gas Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision to sell off Tenneco Oil Co. was a
difficult one, but the mammoth $7.3 billion sale still leaves
Tenneco Inc. with five profitable businesses.
   After the sale, the Houston-based company remains the city's
largest public company, with 1988 revenue close to $13 billion, and
projected revenue of about $14 billion in 1990.
   ``I think it will surprise a lot of people to realize that we are
as big as this without the oil company,'' Tenneco Chairman James L.
Ketelsen said in a wide-ranging interview published in Sunday's
editions of the Houston Chronicle.
   Ketelsen said the Tenneco Oil sale was difficult not only because
of the impact on the nearly 9,000 oil company and corporate
employees involved, but also because of Tenneco's new identity as a
``diversified industrial corporation.''
   The company's other businesses include shipbuilding, automotive,
chemicals, packaging and natural gas pipeline operations, which are
all making money.
   One business making money is Case IH, the construction and farm
equipment company that Tenneco formed in 1985 when JI Case acquired
the agricultural implement division of International Harvester Co.
for $513 million.
   Since then, Tenneco has plowed more than $700 million in capital
expenditures into the subsidiary. Case IH has become the company's
biggest business, but it has yet to show a profit.
   Ketelsen has designated 1989 as the make-or-break year for Case
IH. If the profit are not there, Case IH could have a ``for sale''
sign hanging on its corporate door.
   But Roger Khlopin of Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York
doubts that Tenneco has plans to divest any other operations.
   ``Nothing this company has said has led anyone to believe they
would sell anything other than exploration and production,'' he
said. ``They're building up, not ripping down.''
   Although Case IH's performance has fallen short of expectations,
Ketelsen said, the Harvester acquisition and the subsequent
consolidation and reorganization of Case IH were planned as a
five-year project.
   What the company did not count on was the recession in the U.S.
farm belt that resulted in North American tractor sales falling from
90,000 in 1984 to 61,000 in 1986 and 1987, or last summer's drought
that made many farmers postpone new equipment purchases.
   To help matters, Tenneco installed a new management team at the
Case IH headquarters in Racine, Wis. The new president, James K.
Ashford, previously headed Tenneco Automotive, which more than
doubled its operating income during his five years as the top
executive.
   Tenneco's other business segments are demonstrating growth and
improved profit at rates ranging from modest to booming, Ketelsen
said.
   Natural gas transmission is Tenneco's original business and its
second largest source of revenue after agricultural and construction
equipment. Since the natural gas transmission industry is mature,
overall growth opportunities are limited, he said.
   Nevertheless, the Tennessee Gas Pipeline Group is a consistently
strong earner and supplier of cash flow, Ketelsen said. Its
20,000-mile system from Texas and the Gulf of Mexico to New England
serves one of the two areas where demand for natural gas is growing.
   Increases in federal defense spending since 1981 have helped
Tenneco's Newport News Shipbuilding and Dry Dock Co. grow at a
compound annual rate of 15.6 percent, but Ketelsen acknowledged that
defense expenditures probably will be cut in the Bush administration.
   An $8 billion backlog that includes construction of two aircraft
carriers and two submarines, along with future contracts for
modernization and upgrading of existing U.S. Navy vessels, should
ensure at least incremental growth, the Tenneco chairman said.
   Packaging Corporation of America offers the best potential for
solid growth, Ketelsen said. Although it is the second-smallest
Tenneco unit by revenues, PCA should have the second-highest
operating profits for 1988 and should grow at an annual rate of 15
percent to 20 percent over the next five years, he said.
   Cardboard boxes are PCA's primary product. Ketelsen said $65
million of PCA's projected 1988 operating income of $220 million
will come from specialty products the company did not make five
years ago.
   Albright & Wilson Ltd. of London, a specialty chemicals producer
and Tenneco's smallest subsidiary, should grow an average of 20
percent for the next five years, the chairman said.
   Albright & Wilson is a major supplier of phosphates for
detergents, soaps and shampoos, primarily in Europe, and is the
world's largest producer of sodium chlorate, used to bleach paper
products.
   Tenneco Automotive has grown at a 13 percent rate for the past
five years and is the leading manufacturer of mufflers, exhaust
systems and shock absorbers for the replacement parts and
accessories market.
   Tenneco's other two major business segments _ natural gas
pipelines and shipbuilding _ also will be solid performers, though
not as the others, Ketelsen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
