<DOCNO> AP881212-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1012EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Economy     12-12 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Economy,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Raise Hopes that Higher Interest Rates Are Working</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales fell by a larger-than-expected 0.5
percent in November as producer prices rose 0.3 percent, less than
forecast, the government said Monday, raising hopes that higher
interest rates were slowing down consumer spending and inflation.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 7.5
points, or 0.4 percent, to 1,742.8 after the Department of Trade and
Industry issued its two reports late in the morning. But the index
had been down as much as 11.8 points shortly before the economic
figures were released. The pound held steady at about $1.8405.
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson pushed up interest rates
to 13 percent from a decade low of 7.5 percent in June to discourage
consumer spending and curb inflation, which has picked up to an
annual rate of 6.4 percent from 3.3 percent in January.
   Private economists had forecast a rise or fall of 0.2 percent in
retail sales and a 0.4-percent gain in producer prices.
   ``There are fairly clear signs that growth in retail sales is a
lot slower than it was earlier this year,'' said economist Gwyn
Hacche of the London investment firm James Capel and Co. ``It's in
the right direction.''
   But he added: ``I wouldn't expect there to be clear evidence of
the kind of slowdown we want probably for a few months. Really, the
growth has got to come down quite a lot further.''
   Retail sales were up 5.2 percent from November 1987, the
Department of Trade and Industry said.
   By comparison, retail sales volume rose 2.0 percent in October
from the previous month and was up 6.2 percent from a year earlier.
   Producer output prices, or prices of manufactured goods, were up
4.8 percent from November 1987, the department reported.
   By comparison, output prices rose 0.4 percent in October from the
previous month and were up 4.7 percent from a year earlier. These
figures weren't seasonally adjusted.
</TEXT>
