<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     12-12 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Lower At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were lower at midday Monday, but
prices were above their worst levels in response to favorable
economic news.
   The government reported a 0.5-percent fall in retail sales volume
in November, which dealers said supported the view that recent rises
in British interest rates had begun to bite into the country's
consumer boom.
   Most private organizations had forecast a rise or fall of 0.2
percent. Since November 1987, retail sales have risen 5.2 percent.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 7.5
points, or 0.4 percent, to 1,742.8. The index moved down as much as
11.8 points shortly before the economic figures were released.
   Volume was light, as 230.1 million shares changed hands by
midday, compared with 320.4 million at the same time Friday.
   A separate report on British producer output prices showed a rise
of 0.3 percent in November from October and of 4.8 percent from
November 1987. These figures, at the bottom end of market
expectations, also were favorable, dealers said.
</TEXT>
