<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1116EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Church'sClosures     12-12 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Church's Closures,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church's Chicken Decides To Close Unprofitable Units</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church's Fried Chicken, embroiled in a battle
to prevent a hostile takeover by Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and
Biscuits, announced today it would immediately close 120 of its
stores, whose losses have totaled $7.4 million in the past year.
   ``Our decision to close certain unprofitable stores within the
Church's system will have a positive effect on cash flow,'' Ernest
Renaud, president and chief financial officer of the San
Antonio-based company, said in a statement.
   ``The closings are an important part of our plan to improve
profitability of Church's,'' he said. The closings will be in 20
states.
   In the statement, Renaud said the closings would allow for
between $22 million and $27 million in write-offs for this fiscal
year.
   Church's, which has gone through several management changes in
the past two years, currently has about 1,500 restaurants and is
second in the fast-food chicken industry behind Kentucky Fried
Chicken. Popeyes is third in the industry with about 725 restaurants.
   Church's expects to see sales this year of $520 million, down
from $570 million in 1986 and $633 million in 1984.
   Popeyes is expected to have sales of $485 million this year.
   The restaurant closings come at a time when Church's is in the
midst of a takeover battle with New Orleans-based Popeyes, which has
made an $8-per-share, $290 million unsolicited bid for Church's.
   Church's board of directors has rejected the offer as inadequate.
The company also claims that former Church's employees gave Popeyes
confidential information which it used in the takeover bid.
   A federal judge in New Orleans earlier this month issued an order
preventing Popeyes' owner Al Copeland from buying Church's stock
until 10 working days after Popeyes revealed information on its
buyout offer.
   Popeyes' first takeover deadline was Nov. 30, but has been
extended to Friday. Copeland says he already owns 3.2 percent of
Church's stock and has been offered 14.6 million shares _ or about
40.6 percent _ of the 35.9 million outstanding shares of Church's
stock.
   Meanwhile, Church's has been courting offers from other
investors, but also has become the subject of a class-action suit
filed by a shareholder who claims the offer by Popeyes is adequate
and that the Church's board's refusal to accept it could cost
shareholders huge profits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
