<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1129EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SocieteGenerale     12-12 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Societe Generale,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Largest Holding Company Forecasts Big Loss This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Societe Generale de Belgique, Belgium's
largest holding company, Monday forecast a loss of between 500
million and 2 billion Belgian francs _ between $13.5 and $54 million
_ this year due to restructuring costs.
   But the company said it expected much better results next year,
possibly more than doubling the 3.611 billion francs, or $97.5
million, profit made last year.
   SGB said in a statement that its operating results would have
totaled about 10 billion francs, or $270.2 million, in 1988 if
restructuring costs were not subtracted.
   Those costs, however, were estimated to be between 10.5 billion
francs and 12 billion francs, or the equivalent of $283.8 to $324.3
million, wiping out the profit and leaving the estimated loss of 500
million to 2 billion francs.
   The company predicted that it would post operating results of
about 12 billion francs in 1989 but declined to give a specific net
profit forecast because the extent of restructuring costs was
uncertain for that year.
   Meanwhile in Paris, French company Suez, now the leading SGB
shareholder, announced that that Compagnie Generale d'Electricite
would sell its 3.3 percent stake in SGB in order to acquire a 2.8
percent holding.
   Belgian Groupe AG, second SGB shareholder, confirmed that
Sodecom, the holding company which contained 42 percent of SGB, was
being divided into three new units.
   One will be fully controlled by Suez, a second by Groupe AG and
the two companies will share the third.
   Groupe AG said that an effort will be made to return 12 percent
of SGB shares to the public. Only two percent are currently traded
and an additional 5 percent is being placed with institutional
investors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
