<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Pennwalt     12-12 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pennwalt,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investor Group Offers Nearly $700 Million for Pennwalt Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment partnership offered almost $700
million cash today for Pennwalt Corp., a large Philadelphia-based
chemical concern that makes industrial products such as caustic soda
and chlorine.
   The New York investor group Centaur Partners, which already owns
12.7 percent of Pennwalt's approximately 7.6 million shares
outstanding, said it would pay other stockholders $100 a share for
the rest.
   Pennwalt's stock rocketed higher on the New York Stock Exchange
after the announcement, from $83 at Friday's close to $98 a share
around mid-day today.
   Company officials declined to comment on the offer. But Pennwalt,
a rumored takeover target for months, had taken several defensive
steps to thwart any unwelcome suitors, including the $460 million
sale of pharmaceutical operations three months ago and a stock
repurchase completed last week.
   ``We believe that our offer represents a fair price and is in the
best interest of Pennwalt's shareholders,'' Centaur principals Abbey
J. Butler and Melvyn J. Estrin said in a letter to Pennwalt
management.
   The partners, who claimed to have assembled bank financing to
make the purchase, said they were willing to negotiate any aspect of
their offer including price.
   At the same time, the partners indicated they would resort to
more hostile means to buy Pennwalt, saying they had moved to
invalidate the company's so-called ``poison pill'' shareholders
rights plan with a lawsuit in Philadelphia federal court.
   The poison pill, which many companies have adopted, is designed
to make an unwanted takeover prohibitively expensive.
   Pennwalt produces and markets industrial chemicals, and is a
leading maker of chlorinated plastic, commonly used in building
cable insulation. The company, which had sales of nearly $1.2
billion last year, also has operations in mineral and petroleum
processing.
   In August, the company sold its pharmaceutical unit, maker of
products such as Allerest allergy relief pills and Desenex foot
powder, to the British firm Fisons. Pennwalt also repurchased about
37.6 percent of its outstanding stock as part of a plan to boost the
price.
   Those moves were seen partly as a defensive move against Centaur
principals Butler and Estrin, financiers who had indicated they
might make an offer for Pennwalt.
   Butler, 51, is former chairman of Financial World magazine and is
president of C.B. Equities Corp., a New York-based investment
portfolio mangement company. Estrin, 45, is a Washington-based
investor and former chairman of American Health Services, a hospital
and nursing home management concern.
</TEXT>
