<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gained ground today, extending
last week's advance as traders awaited a spate of economic reports
due out over the next several days.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 51.21 points last
week, rose 12.63 to 2,156.12 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 724 up, 552 down and
566 unchanged.
   Analysts said stocks seemed to draw some benefit from a rise in
the dollar against leading foreign currencies and declines in
open-market interest rates.
   The week began in an atmosphere of caution about prospects for
Federal Reserve policy and interest rates, and the pending monthly
report due out Wednesday on the nation's international trade balance.
   Brokers said it would be no surprise if Fed policymakers, meeting
Tuesday and Wednesday, decided to tighten credit conditions a bit
further, especially if the news on trade isn't good.
   Advance estimates call for the October data to be about the same
as September's, when imports exceeded exports by $9 billion,
excluding freight and insurance costs.
   Pennwalt jumped 15] to 98|. A New York partnership said it would
offer $100 apiece for the Pennwalt shares it doesn't already own.
   Pillsbury climbed 4\ to 62{. Grand Metropolitan PLC raised its
offer for the company's stock from $60 a share to $63 a share.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up ] at
46\; International Business Machines, up 1[ at 121{; DuPont, up } at
83[, and American Telephone & Telegraph, up [ at 29|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.63 to 156.22. On the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .69 at 296.92.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 63.67 million shares at noontime,
down from 68.22 million at the same point Friday.
