<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Portugal-TV Adv17-18   12-12 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Portugal-TV, Adv 17-18,0892</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 17-18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scramble Under Way for New TV Stations in Portugal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It has all the ingredients for the kind
of soap opera television viewers love: an intriguing former prime
minister, international big business and the Roman Catholic Church
fighting for wealth and power.
   But this is not Dallas. This is Portugal. And a real-life battle
for control of one or two new, commercial television channels is
brewing in Western Europe's poorest nation.
   Most observers say former Social Democrat Prime Minister
Fransisco Pinto Balsemao, publisher of the country's most respected
weekly paper, Expresso, is in the best position to win the first
concession.
   But British press baron Robert Maxwell and the Portuguese Church
are also eager to profit by bringing information, opinion and, above
all, advertising, into the homes of Portugal's 10 million
inhabitants.
   RTP, Portugal's 32-year-old, two-channel state television system,
already carries advertising.
   According to Radio Televisao Commercial, the commercial arm of
RTP, 72.9 percent of Portuguese watch TV every day. RTC says this is
the highest rate in Western Europe.
   The most popular programs _ usually early evening ``TV novels''
like ``Roque Santeiro'' imported from Portuguese-speaking Brazil _
find up to 90 percent of the country's viewing population glued to
the screen.
   ``There is certainly demand for more choice _ new stations,''
said Fernando Santos, sales director at RTC, adding that many
Portuguese, especially in poorer, isolated, rural areas have little
other entertainment.
   ``They're all waiting for private TV because they think it will
bring better programs.''
   But some enterprising Portuguese cannot wait. High-powered
satellite dishes, capable of picking up neighboring Spain's two
programs and several Eurosatellite channels, have sprouted on more
affluent rooftops in Lisbon, Oporto and the southern Algarve.
   At 200,000 escudos (about $1,300) per dish, the antennae are too
expensive for the average Portuguese, whose minimum monthly wage is
27,100 escudos ($179) _ about half that of Spain and a quarter of
the minimum monthly wage in France.
   Poorer areas often solve the problem by pooling cash to buy
communal dishes that can pick up programs from abroad for easy _ but
illegal _ retransmission by cable to individual homes.
   Plans to introduce commercial television via private extension of
the regular network were first discussed in 1982 but only now are
likely to become a reality.
   In October Social Democrat Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva and
the main opposition Socialist Party reached an agreement to secure
the necessary two-thirds parliamentary majority on a vote expected
next spring to change the constitutional clause that restricts
private ownership of TV stations.
   But the government could set up new channels by concession now
without having to transfer ownership.
   ``It's very much a question of political will,'' Balsemao said,
and, according to RTC's Santos, a new commercial channel could be up
and running by the end of 1989.
   Balsemao has already attracted support from Portuguese publishing
circles and a minority participation from Britain's independent
Granada TV, to register SIC _ Independent Society for Communication.
   He sees privatization of RTP-2, the second state-owned channel,
as the quickest way to bring commercial television to Portugal.
   ``The longer the government waits, the more inroads foreign TV
interests will make here, and the more difficult it will be for new
Portuguese stations to break into the market.''
   Maxwell, head of Maxwell Communications PLC and publisher of a
new European newspaper, could be one of the foreign interests.
   Maxwell Communications has set up a joint venture with Lisbon
communications concern Emaudio International connected with
Socialist President Mario Soares and has already started to make
inroads into the Portuguese media market.
   ``Our principal objective is to control a regular TV channel, but
we plan to go ahead with the launch of a Portuguese satellite
channel by 1990 at the latest,'' Raul Junqueiro, mastermind of
Emaudio's TV plans, said.
   Emaudio is already making headway in the expanding newspaper
market here. Two weeks ago, it launched the first of two planned
newspapers _ a non-glossy, investigative weekly called Primeira
Pagina. Maxwell plans to launch a daily called ``24 Horas'' by the
end of January.
   Magalhaes Crespo, president of the Administrative Council of
Radio Renascenca, the Church's nationwide radio network, and
frontman for the future Televisao Catolica, says the Church's
position as a mainstay of Portugal's education system gives it a
right to own a TV channel.
   Market surveys show 29 percent of adult listeners tune in to
Radio Renascenca, a figure twice that of the combined audience of
its two state-owned competitors.
   But many are wary of the objectivity of a Church-controlled
channel.
   ``It's true we are conservative in our outlook,'' Crespo said.
``But, in the case of our radio station, we never mix comment with
information.''
   More channels may not mean better television, Santos of RTC said.
   ``If these new channels want to make profits, they will have to
resort to showing low-cost repeats of old films.''
   It costs 10 times as much to produce a home-grown product, he
said, than to buy a foreign import.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 17-18</NOTE>
