<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Trade,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Rises 38 Percent From Year Earlier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus continued to rise in November,
shooting up 38 percent to $6.55 billion from $4.75 billion a year
earlier, the Finance Ministry said Monday.
   Japan's surplus with the United States climbed to $4.42 billion
from $4.21 billion a year earlier, the ministry said, reversing 11
straight months of decline.
   While the overall November surplus was smaller than October's
$7.69 billion surplus, it surpassed forecasts of a $6.5 billion
surplus.
   Exports surged 19.5 percent over a year earlier to $22.6 billion
from $18.9 billion, while imports climbed 13.4 percent over a year
earlier to $16.1 billion from $14.2 billion, ministry officials said.
   The officials predicted that strong export growth ``will continue
in the future.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
