<DOCNO> AP881212-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1348EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Pillsbury 2ndld-Writethru f0065 12-12 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, 2nd ld - Writethru, f0065,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met Raises Offer for Pillsbury; Company Chairmen Meet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 new grafs to UPDATE with Pillsbury rejecting
higher tender offer, editing to conform; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Grand Met said...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC of Britain today
increased its cash tender offer for Pillsbury Co. common stock by $3
per share to $63, but Pillsbury quickly rejected the proposal as it
had a separate offer for a richer, negotiated deal.
   Late Sunday, Grand Met had said it would amend its tender offer
in a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. The amended
offer values Pillsbury's more than 86 million outstanding shares at
about $5.42 billion.
   But Pillsbury's board of directors immediately rejected the
$63-per-share offer as ``inadequate and not in the best interests of
the company and its shareholders.''
   Grand Met said Sunday it decided to raise its formal tender offer
after Minneapolis-based Pillsbury declined to endorse its offer to
pay $65 a share for a friendly, negotiated acquisition.
   Pillsbury had said earlier Sunday night that Grand Met was
willing to raise its offer to as much as $66 a share.
   Both companies issued statements saying that Pillsbury Chairman
Philip L. Smith met over the weekend with Grand Met Chief Executive
Officer Allen Sheppard in New York but did not reach an agreement.
   The jockeying occurred ahead of a hearing this afternoon in
Delaware Chancery Court on Pillsbury's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover
measures, the cornerstone of its defense against Grand Met. The
British company's offer is conditioned on the removal of the pill.
   As of Friday night, stockholders had tendered 87.4 percent of
Pillsbury shares to Grand Met under its $60 bid. Grand Met, a major
hotel and beverage conglomerate, has declined to buy any of the
shares until the court rules on Pillsbury's defense.
   Court Chancellor William Duffy has told participants that after
oral arguments today, he will make a decision by the end of this
week.
   At an initial meeting Friday evening, Pillsbury said Sheppard
indicated he was prepared to increase Grand Met's offer to $63 a
share. Smith responded that he ``was not willing to discuss at this
time'' a price which was not in the range of $68 to $73 a share,
Pillsbury's statement said.
   On Saturday morning, Grand Met indicated it was making a formal
offer of $65 a share for a negotiated acquisition, according to both
companies' statements.
   Pillsbury said its board of directors met Sunday but there was
``no enthusiasm'' for the $65-a-share proposal.
   At a meeting Sunday afternoon, Sheppard indicated that although
$65 was his official final offer, $66 a share ``could be
available,'' according to Pillsbury's statement.
   According to Grand Met's statement, Sheppard said Friday night
the British company was willing to pay $63 per share and ``perhaps a
little more'' in a negotiated acquisition, but didn't specify how
much more.
   Pillsbury said its board has authorized Smith to be available for
any discussions with Grand Met officials ``which are designed to
maximize values to Pillsbury shareholders.''
   The fight to take over Pillsbury, a company that includes the
Burger King fast-food chain as well as a variety of products bearing
the Pillsbury brand, has coincided with the even bigger takeover of
food and tobacco giant RJR Nabisco, which was bought in a leveraged
buyout last week in a deal estimated to be worth about $25 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881212-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1431EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     12-12 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0329</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market worked its way higher today,
extending last week's advance as traders awaited a spate of economic
reports due out over the next several days.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 51.21 points last
week, rose 14.40 to 2,157.89 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 780 up, 598 down and
550 unchanged.
   Analysts said stocks seemed to draw some benefit from a rise in
the dollar against leading foreign currencies and declines in
open-market interest rates.
   The week began in an atmosphere of caution about prospects for
Federal Reserve policy and interest rates, and the pending monthly
report due out Wednesday on the nation's international trade balance.
