<HEAD>Dollar Ends Higher In Europe, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against major foreign currencies on
Monday in Europe after spending most of the day fluctuating in a
narrow range, and gold prices declined.
   Dealers said there was no particular reason for the dollar's
strength on Monday. Trading generally was trendless because most
market participants were awaiting the release Wednesday of U.S.
trade figures for October, they said.
   The trade deficit was expected to be little changed in October
from September's seasonally adjusted $10.4 billion. But a few
dealers said they were more bearish, and were looking for a gap
between $11 billion and $12 billion.
   One dealer said a smaller-than-expected deficit would boost the
dollar to its next resistance level at 1.7750 West German marks,
while a bearish figure would depress the dollar to the next big
support level, which is 1.7150 marks.
   The dollar rose to 1.7410 marks on Monday from 1.7330 marks on
Friday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.49 yen to close at closing 122.92 yen. Later in
London, the dollar was quoted at 122.83 yen.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8418 from $1.8490 on
Friday.
