<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-12 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Rally On Export Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures closed higher Monday on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid unconfirmed rumors of impending grain sales to
the Soviet Union, but soybean prices finished mostly lower in
response to weekend rains in South America.
   Traders were expecting the Agriculture Department to offer the
Soviet Union up to 3 million metric tons of wheat at subsidized
prices, analysts said.
   The Soviets also were rumored to be in the market for up to 1
million metric tons of U.S. corn and sorghum, said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   But the soybean market declined on reports of significant weekend
rainfall in Brazil and Argentina, where hot, dry weather has forced
delays in soybean planting, analysts said.
   ``They got good rains and there's more in the forecasts for both
Brazil and Argentina, especially Argentina,'' Lespinasse said.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher with December
at $4.28{ a bushel; corn was 1} cents to 5 cents higher with
December at $2.61\ a bushel; oats were 2\ cents to 4{ cents higher
with December at $2.08 a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to 4\
cents higher with January at $7.70 a bushel.
</TEXT>
