<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Church'sChicken     12-12 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church's Chicken,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church's Chicken Decides To Close Unprofitable Units</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Popeyes, no apostrophe, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church's Fried Chicken Inc., which is fighting
a hostile takeover takeover bid from a rival restaurant chain, said
Monday it was closing 120 unprofitable restaurants and taking
writeoffs of up to $27 million.
   Church's is scrambling to fend off the hostile overtures from the
parent of New Orleans-based Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and
Biscuits, whose latest $8-per-share, $290 million offer expires
Friday.
   Ernest Renaud, Church's president and chief executive officer,
said the restaurant closings in 20 states involved outlets that lost
$7.4 million in the past 12 months. He said the losses from the
restaurants were affecting the company's cash flow as it struggled
with tough economic situations and the takeover attempt.
   There will be 24 closings in Texas; 12 in Illinois; 10 in
Alabama, nine in Virginia, seven in Ohio, six in Kansas and Missouri
and three to four each in several other states.
   ``There was just too much chicken competition in those areas. We
just overbuilt,'' Renaud said. ``We were taking big losses for a
long time. These units were just a big drain.
   ``They should have been closed a year ago, but this is just part
of my plan to make the company profitable again,'' he said.
   Renaud said the comapny would take write-offs of between $22
million and $27 million for its current fiscal year.
   Church's stock dipped 25 cents to $7.75 a share Monday in New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   Church's, which has gone through several management changes and
poor sales over the past two years, had 1,500 restaurants before the
closures, second behind Kentucky Fried Chicken. Church's expects
sales this year of $520 million, down from $570 million in 1986 and
$633 million in 1984.
   Popeyes, the nation's third-largest chicken chain with about 725
restaurants, expects to have sales of $485 million this year.
   Church's board of directors has rejected Popeyes' offer as
inadequate and is challenging various aspects of it in federal court
as well as seeking possible other suitors.
   A federal judge in New Orleans earlier this month issued an order
preventing Popeyes from buying Church's stock until 10 working days
after Popeyes disclosed further information on its buyout offer.
   Popeyes' first takeover deadline was Nov. 30, but has been
extended to Friday. Popeyes Chairman Al Copeland says he already
owns 3.2 percent of Church's stock and says he has been tendered
14.6 million _ about 40.6 percent _ of Church's 35.9 million
outstanding shares under the $8 a share offer.
</TEXT>
