<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Pepperell     12-12 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pepperell,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farley Calls for Pepperell Shareholder Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc. asked West Point-Pepperell Inc. on
Monday to call a special shareholder meeting to consider Farley's
$1.4 billion takeover bid, and Pepperell promptly indicated it would
review the shareholder vote calling for the meeting.
   Farley, a Chicago-based apparel manufacturer, had received
requests for a meeting from shareholders representing more than the
required 25 percent of Pepperell's shares, chairman William Farley
said in a statement.
   A Pepperell spokeswoman said the company had received the request
and had named the Corporation Trust Co. of Wilmington, Del., to
independently review the shareholders solicitations that had been
sent out and returned to Farley.
   A report on the meeting should be issued by Dec. 19, said the
spokeswoman, who asked that her name not be used.
   Pepperell stock on Monday rose 75 cents to close at $42.25 a
share in New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Pepperell, which is based in West Point Ga., is the country's
largest publicly held textile manufacturer and makes Gold Toe socks,
Arrow shirts and Martex towels.
   Farley, maker of Fruit of the Loom underwear and several other
clothing brands, last Wednesday extended its $48-per-share buyout
bid through midnight EST Dec. 14. The company announced on Dec. 2
its intention to seek the special shareholder meeting.
   ``Our intention from the outset has been to sit down with
Pepperell's board and negotiate a mutually acceptable acquisition of
Pepperell,'' Farley said. ``But the board would not meet with us.''
   At the meeting, Farley would ask shareholders to replace the
board with nominees representing the Chicago company, Farley said.
   The new board would then dismantle defenses Pepperell has
arranged against takeovers, he said.
   Farley is seeking to overturn Pepperell's ``poison pill''
takeover defense plan in court. The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals has scheduled a hearing on the matter in Atlanta for the
week of Jan. 9.
</TEXT>
