<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-12 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Light Trading, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened marginally against major
foreign currencies Monday but exchange dealers said trading was
extremely slow, reflecting a reluctance to do business in advance of
the government's market-moving monthly trade report.
   Gold prices eased. Republic National Bank quoted bullion at
$420.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $422.50 late Friday.
   Currency strategists read little significance into the dollar's
small gain, saying it largely was due to internal market influences
of supply and demand, not any outside news.
   But some said speculation that the Federal Reserve would move to
tighten interest rates may have strengthened the dollar a bit.
Higher interest rates make dollar-denominated investments more
attractive.
   Many dealers said the overwhelming force shaping the market's
behavior was reticence to take any risky positions before the
Commerce Department's report on the October trade deficit, due
Wednesday.
   The highly unpredictable monthly trade numbers are seen as one of
the most visible symbols of U.S. economic strength and
competitiveness abroad, with an enormous potential to influence
financial markets.
   A large trade deficit would likely depress the dollar's value,
while a small deficit would help stabilize or boost the currency.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.49 yen to close at 122.92 yen. Later
in London the dollar was quoted at 122.83 yen. By the time trading
ended in New York the dollar fetched 122.80 yen, up from 122.49 yen
late Friday.
   The British pound fell in London to $1.8418 from $1.8490 on
Friday. In New York, sterling fetched $1.8435, down from $1.8495
late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates on
Friday, included: 1.7415 West German marks, up from 1.7352; 1.4643
Swiss francs, up from 1.4620; 1.1970 Canadian dollars, up from
evels late Friday
included: 1.7410 West German marks, up from 1.7330; 1.4650 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4605; 5.9520 French francs, up from 5.9240; 1.9635
Dutch guilders, up from 1.9560; 1,282.75 Italian lire, up from
1,280.25; and 1.1983 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1970.
   In bullion trading, gold for current delivery fell $2.80 a troy
ounce from late Friday's level to $420.10 on the New York Commodity
Exchange. Earlier in London gold fell $1 an ounce to $419.75. Gold
fell $1.05 an ounce in Zurich to $419.25 and fell $2.10 in Hong Kong
to $422.29.
   Silver bullion for current delivery fell 0.6 cent a troy ounce on
the New York Comex to $6.169. In London silver fell 2 cents an ounce
to $6.14.
</TEXT>
