<1ST_LINE>u f AM-UnisysDirectors     12-12 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unisys Directors,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unisys Elects Two Directors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. elected two new directors as
it and announced a reorganization of its management Monday in what
was described as part of a long-term strategy to ``sell solutions,
not machines.''
   Jan Lindelow, a senior vice president, will resign from the
company at the end of the year in connection with the management
shuffle. Lindelow's responsibilities would have been reduced and he
decided to look for another job, Unisys spokesman J. Peter Hynes
said.
   Hynes said the reduction of Lindelow's responsibilities was not a
reflection of his abilities.
   The computer company also extended its stock repurchase plan and
declared dividends at a board meeting Monday in Detroit.
   The chief financial officer of Unisys, Curtis A. Hessler, was
elected to the board of directors and promoted to executive vice
president.
   Paul C. Ely Jr., currently chairman of Convergent Inc., also was
elected to the board and will assume the position of executive vice
president with the completion of the Unisys acquisition of
Convergent, a maker of small but speedy computer workstations.
   Hynes said the acquisition of Convergent allowed the company to
reorganize its management and its engineering and manufacturing
divisions.
   Hynes said the company's long-term strategy focuses on three
areas: small computers, such as the Convergent machines; large,
traditional mainframe computers; and networking, which is the
process of allowing different computer systems to communicate with
each other.
   ``It's part of our overall strategy, which is selling solutions,
not machines,'' he said. ``We believe the customer does not care
about the machine as much as the customer cares about what the
machine will do for him,'' Hynes said.
   Under the new management, Hessler will be responsible for
implementing the company's financial and strategic plans. Ely will
become president of a newly formed Network Computing Group.
   Also under the new management, the current president of
Convergent, Cyril J. Yansouni, will be a Unisys corporate vice
president.
   A current Unisys executive vice president and director, James A.
Unruh, will be responsible for all commercial marketing operations.
He currently is in charge of international marketing operations and
the implementation of the annual financial plan.
   A Unisys senior vice president, Hollis L. Caswell, will become
president of a newly formed Computer Systems Group, responsible for
marketing the mainframe systems and peripheral products.
   The reorganization is expected to be implemented during the first
quarter of 1989, after Convergent shareholders vote on the
acquisition Dec. 22.
   In Detroit, the board declared a quarterly dividend of 25 cents
per common share and a 93.75 cent dividend on the company's Series A
cumulative convertible preferred stock.
   The board also extended for one year its periodic repurchase of
the company's common and preferred stock, which was implemented last
year.
   During 1988, the company purchased nearly 2 million of its
authorized 10 million shares and reissued about half to fund stock
option and other employee benefit plans.
   Unisys is a $10 billion manufacturer of commercial information
systems, defense systems and related services. It has more than
90,000 employees and 60,000 customers in more than 100 countries.
</TEXT>
