<DOCNO> AP881212-0308 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1825EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-12 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Plunge On Supplies Buildup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices fell steeply Monday on New York's Commodity
Exchange after the exchange reported the first increase in nearly a
month in deliverable supplies of the metal.
   On other markets, precious metals mostly were lower; livestock
and meat futures moved sharply higher; energy futures were mixed;
grains and soybeans were mixed; and stock-index futures fell.
   Copper settled 1 cent to 4.40 cents lower on the Commodity
Exchange with the spot contract for delivery in December at $1.585 a
pound and the more actively traded March contract at $1.352 a pound.
   Daily increases in the amount of warehoused copper registered
with the Commodity Exchange have been rare since October 1987, when
the Comex copper inventory stood at nearly 90,000 short tons.
   Late last week, the exchange reported that warehouse stocks had
dropped to 5,204 tons and copper for December delivery on the
exchange soared to an all-time high of $1.6475 a pound.
   But copper traders who had expected the trend to continue were
shocked Monday morning when the Comex reported that warehouse stocks
had risen to 6,545 tons, a 24 percent increase from last week's
tally.
   ``That was an unpleasant surprise to the market,'' said Craig
Sloane, metals analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New
York.
   The Comex last reported an increase in copper stocks on Nov. 17.
   Meanwhile, the world's other major copper futures market, the
London Metal Exchange, reported a 1,925-ton decline in its warehouse
stocks of copper, which was a smaller decrease than traders had
expected, Sloane said.
   Platinum futures prices fell sharply in a technically inspired
sell-off, dragging a gold prices lower as well, but silver futures
were mixed, analysts said.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, platinum settled $8.60 to
$11.10 lower with January at $589.10 a troy ounce. On the Comex,
gold settled $2.80 to $3.10 lower with February at $424.60 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.7 cent lower to 0.4 cent higher with March at
$6.298 a troy ounce.
   Pork futures rose strongly on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange on
speculation that last week's drop in slaughters meant hog kills had
passed their seasonal peak, said Dale Durchholz, an analyst with
Agri-Visor Services Inc., Bloomington, Ill.
   Strong retail demand and the arrival of wintry conditions in the
Midwest also contributed to the advance in pork futures, he said.
   ``Farmers just havent' been willing to move hogs with the kind of
temperatures we've had because it stresses them a little more,''
Durchholz said.
   Cattle futures rallied in sympathy with the pork complex and in
reaction to renewed demand, he said.
   Live cattle settled .25 cent to .60 cent higher with December at
72.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent to 1 cent higher
with January at 83.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .63 cent to 1.20
cents higher with December at 42.77 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.03 cent to 1.35 cent higher with February at 44.60
cents a pound.
   Home heating oil prices closed sharply higher and lent support to
crude oil futures after sub-zero temperatures hit the Northeast,
analysts said. Gasoline futures retreated.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents 22 cents higher
with January at $16.06 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent to .70
cent higher with January at 50.20 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .11 cent to .40 cent lower with January at 44.20 cents a gallon.
   Grain futures finished higher on the Chicago Board of Trade amid
rumors of impending grain sales to the Soviet Union while soybean
prices settled mostly lower in response to weekend rains in South
America.
   The Agriculture Department issued a monthly grain supply-demand
report after the close in which it increased its estimate for the
U.S. wheat stockpile at the end of the current marketing year to 533
million bushels from 528 million bushels.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher with December at $4.28{
a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 4} cents higher with December at
$2.61{ a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 5{ cents higher with December
at $2.07{ a bushel; soybeans were 4\ cents lower to 4} cents higher
with January at $7.69\ a bushel.
   Stock index futures fell moderately on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 settled 1.15 points lower at 279.30. Each point is worth
$500.
</TEXT>
