<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     12-12 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Orders Change in Tender Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Disney-held company seeking to acquire Polaroid
Corp. amended its takeover offer Monday to meet a federal court
order that was blocking the bid.
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. said its hostile $42-a-share bid for
Polaroid was now contingent on whether a judge in Delaware
invalidated or rescinded the Polaroid employee stock ownership plan
being challenged by Shamrock.
   Analysts said the move would not dramatically alter Shamrock's
$2.6 billion tender offer, which has been in abeyance pending court
action.
   In Delaware, U.S. District Judge Caleb Wright on Monday ordered
Shamrock to modify the language of the offer and issue a news
release on the changes. The Burbank, Calif.-based television
concern, wholly owned by the Roy E. Disney family, met the
conditions immediately.
   Shamrock said it would purchase Polaroid shares under its $42
offer only if the employee stock plan was invalidated by Delaware
Chancery Court, where Shamrock is challenging the plan.
   Previously, Shamrock had maintained that the deal could have
proceeded merely if the 10 million shares in the stock plan were
ruled not part of the company's outstanding shares.
   If the $300 million plan is invalidated, Shamrock would try to
buy 62 million outstanding shares. If not, it would be faced with
acquiring about 72 million shares under an earlier $40-a-share
offer, analysts said.
   Shamrock owns 5 million shares of Polaroid.
   Polaroid spokeswoman Marcia Phillips said the company had no
comment on the development.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Philadelphia last month
ordered the district court to issue a preliminary injunction
blocking the takeover bid until Shamrock clarified its position on
the employee stock plan.
   The plan places 14 percent of the company stock in employee
hands, a move Shamrock claims was designed intentionally to defend
against its hostile takeover bid. Under Delaware law, a hostile
bidder must acquire at least 85 percent of a company.
   Cambridge-based Polaroid, which introduced instant snapshots in
1948, is incorporated in Delaware.
   ``I don't think this implies a change in the approach of Shamrock
to the offer or really any material change in the offer,'' said Alex
Henderson, an analyst with Prudential Bache Securities.
   Arguments in the chancery court case are scheduled for Friday.
Shamrock said it would extend its offer for Polaroid past next
Monday's expiration date to wait for a court ruling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
