<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Blackstone-Nikko     12-12 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blackstone-Nikko,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Investment Firm Buys 20 Percent Stake in Blackstone Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nikko Securities Co. Ltd., a Japanese investment
giant, has acquired a 20 percent stake in a holding partnership
formed by The Blackstone Group, a rapidly-growing investment banking
firm, the two concerns said Monday.
   The deal formalizes a business relationship that began when Nikko
invested $100 million in a Blackstone buyout fund last year. It
gives Blackstone an infusion of capital and better access to the
Japanese capital markets.
   It is the latest in a series of alliances that has seen Japanese
investment firms buy stakes in the relatively smaller Wall Street
investment boutiques that are becoming an increasingly potent force
in the mergers and acquisitions arena.
   Last summer, Nomura Securities Co. bought a 20 percent stake in
the buyout firm Wasserstein, Perella & Co., and Yamaichi Securities
Co. agreed to buy a 25 percent equity interest in another small
buyout firm, Lodestar Group.
   Tokyo-based Nikko Securities said it would pay $100 million for
the interest in the Blackstone holding partnership.
   In exchange, it will be allowed to participate in 20 percent of
the profits generated by Blackstone's financial advisory activities
and its investment banking affiliates, such as Blackstone Financial
Management which oversees investments in two mutual funds.
   The agreement ``formalizes a basis for close cooperation on
U.S.-Japan M&A transactions between the two firms,'' the statement
said.
   Blackstone was founded three years ago and is headed by Peter G.
Peterson, the former U.S. Commerce secretary and onetime chairman of
Lehman Brothers Kuhn Loeb Inc. which has become part of Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. Among its six general partners is David Stockman,
the former director of the Office of Management and Budget under
President Reagan.
   In October 1987, Nikko paid $100 million to become one of three
limited partner-investors in Blackstone Capital Partners,
Blackstone's buyout fund that currently has more than $750 million
of equity capital.
   The fund's biggest deals to date include the $2.6 billion buyout
of Wickes Co. and its $600 million purchase of 51 percent of USX
Corp.'s transportation subsidiaries which it operates in partnership
with USX.
   Blackstone also has advised on merger and aquisition deals valued
at more than $15 billion, including Sony Corp.'s $2 billion purchase
of CBS Records and the acquisition of Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. by
Japan's Bridgestone Corp.
   ``We have been pleased and impressed with Blackstone's
performance and basic philosophy,'' said Yasuo Kanzaki, executive
vice president of Nikko Securities.
   He said Nikko and the ``vast majority of Japanese corporations
share Blackstone's strictly friendly philosophy in both its advisory
and principal actvities.''
   Nikko Securities is one of the biggest Japanese investment houses
with $4.7 billion in capital as of September 1988.
   Peterson, who is chairman of Blackstone Group, and Stephen A.
Schwarzman, president, said in a joint statement that the investment
by Nikko would help Blackstone finance its diversification plans
into areas such as the restructuring of troubled companies, obtain
better access to the Japanese capital markets and provide better
service to its existing clients.
   ``Finally it provides all these benefits while permitting us the
freedom to continue to operate out business in the way we have,''
the statement said.
</TEXT>
