<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LatinDebt     12-12 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Latin Debt,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group of Eight Meet to Discuss Latin American Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic and finance ministers from
seven Latin American nations agreed Monday to take ``urgent'',
collective measures to reduce their foreign debt.
   The so-called Group of Eight also agreed in a closed-door meeting
to present the measures, which were undisclosed, to their respective
presidents.
   The group is composed of ministers from Argentina, Brazil,
Colombia, Peru, Uruguay, Venezuela and Mexico. Panama dropped out of
the group last year due to internal political turmoil. Together, the
eight member countries owe around $400 billion in foreign debt along
with $25 billion in interest due in 1989.
   The measures should be accompanied by a call for cut in interst
rates below the market rate, according to Brazilian Finance Minister
Mailson da Nobrega.
   In the six years since the world debt crisis erupted, this is the
first time that debtor nations have proposed an apparently
unconventional, collective answer to the debt question, some
observers said. At past meetings some members have stressed that
each country's particular characteristics make a case-by-case direct
resolution of their respective debts with creditors the more
appropriate path to follow.
   During the Rio meeting, as in past years, the Group of Eight
avoided talk of a debt cartel.
</TEXT>
