<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Chevron-Charge     12-12 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chevron-Charge,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chevron Announces $100 Million Loss on Irving Oil Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron Corp. announced Monday it will post
a loss in excess of $100 million after taxes in the fourth quarter
on the sale of its 48.9 percent stake in Irving Oil Ltd.
   But a spokesman for the oil giant said the charge should not
result in a net loss for the quarter.
   Chevron said it sold its interest in Irving Oil on Friday after
having an interest in the firm for more than 30 years, said Steve
McLennan, manager of investor relations for Chevron.
   Chevron would not disclose the details of the transaction. Irving
Oil is a privately-held company based in New Brunswick, Canada, that
operates a refinery and has a number of marketing outlets.
   Chevron officials denied that the sale, which had been negotiated
``for some time,'' was prompted by anything in particular.
   ``It's been a profitable enterprise for us,'' he said. ``The
charge we're taking in the fourth quarter is, in a sense, undoing a
little bit of the profits of the past. Overall, it's been a
profitable investment.''
   McLennan said it ``was in neither one of our interests'' to
continue the minority interest. The two companies have some ``very,
very small'' joint operations that will continue under contract, he
added.
   ``Although it is a substantial loss to take, it should not put us
in the red for the quarter,'' said McLennan. ``It shouldn't really
even come close.''
   Chevron had net income of $220 million, or 64 cents a share, in
the foureth quarter a year ago after taking a charge of $93 million
related to the disposition and write-off of assets.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Chevron rose 12{ cents
a share to $46 on Monday.
</TEXT>
